43 
44 It will be seen that this mere painstaking burrower and grub-worm of
45 a poor devil of a Sub-Sub appears to have gone through the long
46 Vaticans and street-stalls of the earth, picking up whatever random
47 allusions to whales he could anyways find in any book whatsoever,
48 sacred or profane.  Therefore you must not, in every case at least,
49 take the higgledy-piggledy whale statements, however authentic, in
50 these extracts, for veritable gospel cetology.  Far from it.  As
51 touching the ancient authors generally, as well as the poets here
52 appearing, these extracts are solely valuable or entertaining, as
53 affording a glancing bird's eye view of what has been promiscuously
54 said, thought, fancied, and sung of Leviathan, by many nations and
55 generations, including our own.
56 
57 So fare thee well, poor devil of a Sub-Sub, whose commentator I am.
58 Thou belongest to that hopeless, sallow tribe which no wine of this
59 world will ever warm; and for whom even Pale Sherry would be too
60 rosy-strong; but with whom one sometimes loves to sit, and feel
61 poor-devilish, too; and grow convivial upon tears; and say to them
62 bluntly, with full eyes and empty glasses, and in not altogether
63 unpleasant sadness--Give it up, Sub-Subs!  For by how much the more
64 pains ye take to please the world, by so much the more shall ye for
65 ever go thankless!  Would that I could clear out Hampton Court and
66 the Tuileries for ye!  But gulp down your tears and hie aloft to the
67 royal-mast with your hearts; for your friends who have gone before
68 are clearing out the seven-storied heavens, and making refugees of
69 long-pampered Gabriel, Michael, and Raphael, against your coming.
70 Here ye strike but splintered hearts together--there, ye shall strike
71 unsplinterable glasses!
