503 
504 Loomings.
505 
506 
507 Call me Ishmael.  Some years ago--never mind how long
508 precisely--having little or no money in my purse, and nothing
509 particular to interest me on shore, I thought I would sail about a
510 little and see the watery part of the world.  It is a way I have of
511 driving off the spleen and regulating the circulation.  Whenever I
512 find myself growing grim about the mouth; whenever it is a damp,
513 drizzly November in my soul; whenever I find myself involuntarily
514 pausing before coffin warehouses, and bringing up the rear of every
515 funeral I meet; and especially whenever my hypos get such an upper
516 hand of me, that it requires a strong moral principle to prevent me
517 from deliberately stepping into the street, and methodically knocking
518 people's hats off--then, I account it high time to get to sea as soon
519 as I can.  This is my substitute for pistol and ball.  With a
520 philosophical flourish Cato throws himself upon his sword; I quietly
521 take to the ship.  There is nothing surprising in this.  If they but
522 knew it, almost all men in their degree, some time or other, cherish
523 very nearly the same feelings towards the ocean with me.
524 
525 There now is your insular city of the Manhattoes, belted round by
526 wharves as Indian isles by coral reefs--commerce surrounds it with
527 her surf.  Right and left, the streets take you waterward.  Its
528 extreme downtown is the battery, where that noble mole is washed by
529 waves, and cooled by breezes, which a few hours previous were out of
530 sight of land.  Look at the crowds of water-gazers there.
531 
532 Circumambulate the city of a dreamy Sabbath afternoon.  Go from
533 Corlears Hook to Coenties Slip, and from thence, by Whitehall,
534 northward.  What do you see?--Posted like silent sentinels all around
535 the town, stand thousands upon thousands of mortal men fixed in ocean
536 reveries.  Some leaning against the spiles; some seated upon the
537 pier-heads; some looking over the bulwarks of ships from China; some
538 high aloft in the rigging, as if striving to get a still better
539 seaward peep.  But these are all landsmen; of week days pent up in
540 lath and plaster--tied to counters, nailed to benches, clinched to
541 desks.  How then is this?  Are the green fields gone?  What do they
542 here?
543 
544 But look! here come more crowds, pacing straight for the water, and
545 seemingly bound for a dive.  Strange!  Nothing will content them but
546 the extremest limit of the land; loitering under the shady lee of
547 yonder warehouses will not suffice.  No.  They must get just as nigh
548 the water as they possibly can without falling in.  And there they
549 stand--miles of them--leagues.  Inlanders all, they come from lanes
550 and alleys, streets and avenues--north, east, south, and west.  Yet
551 here they all unite.  Tell me, does the magnetic virtue of the
552 needles of the compasses of all those ships attract them thither?
553 
554 Once more.  Say you are in the country; in some high land of lakes.
555 Take almost any path you please, and ten to one it carries you down
556 in a dale, and leaves you there by a pool in the stream.  There is
557 magic in it.  Let the most absent-minded of men be plunged in his
558 deepest reveries--stand that man on his legs, set his feet a-going,
559 and he will infallibly lead you to water, if water there be in all
560 that region.  Should you ever be athirst in the great American
561 desert, try this experiment, if your caravan happen to be supplied
562 with a metaphysical professor.  Yes, as every one knows, meditation
563 and water are wedded for ever.
564 
565 But here is an artist.  He desires to paint you the dreamiest,
566 shadiest, quietest, most enchanting bit of romantic landscape in all
567 the valley of the Saco.  What is the chief element he employs?  There
568 stand his trees, each with a hollow trunk, as if a hermit and a
569 crucifix were within; and here sleeps his meadow, and there sleep his
570 cattle; and up from yonder cottage goes a sleepy smoke.  Deep into
571 distant woodlands winds a mazy way, reaching to overlapping spurs of
572 mountains bathed in their hill-side blue.  But though the picture
573 lies thus tranced, and though this pine-tree shakes down its sighs
574 like leaves upon this shepherd's head, yet all were vain, unless the
575 shepherd's eye were fixed upon the magic stream before him.  Go visit
576 the Prairies in June, when for scores on scores of miles you wade
577 knee-deep among Tiger-lilies--what is the one charm
578 wanting?--Water--there is not a drop of water there!  Were Niagara
579 but a cataract of sand, would you travel your thousand miles to see
580 it?  Why did the poor poet of Tennessee, upon suddenly receiving two
581 handfuls of silver, deliberate whether to buy him a coat, which he
582 sadly needed, or invest his money in a pedestrian trip to Rockaway
583 Beach?  Why is almost every robust healthy boy with a robust healthy
584 soul in him, at some time or other crazy to go to sea?  Why upon your
585 first voyage as a passenger, did you yourself feel such a mystical
586 vibration, when first told that you and your ship were now out of
587 sight of land?  Why did the old Persians hold the sea holy?  Why did
588 the Greeks give it a separate deity, and own brother of Jove?  Surely
589 all this is not without meaning.  And still deeper the meaning of
590 that story of Narcissus, who because he could not grasp the
591 tormenting, mild image he saw in the fountain, plunged into it and
592 was drowned.  But that same image, we ourselves see in all rivers and
593 oceans.  It is the image of the ungraspable phantom of life; and this
594 is the key to it all.
595 
596 Now, when I say that I am in the habit of going to sea whenever I
597 begin to grow hazy about the eyes, and begin to be over conscious of
598 my lungs, I do not mean to have it inferred that I ever go to sea as
599 a passenger.  For to go as a passenger you must needs have a purse,
600 and a purse is but a rag unless you have something in it.  Besides,
601 passengers get sea-sick--grow quarrelsome--don't sleep of nights--do
602 not enjoy themselves much, as a general thing;--no, I never go as a
603 passenger; nor, though I am something of a salt, do I ever go to sea
604 as a Commodore, or a Captain, or a Cook.  I abandon the glory and
605 distinction of such offices to those who like them.  For my part, I
606 abominate all honourable respectable toils, trials, and tribulations
607 of every kind whatsoever.  It is quite as much as I can do to take
608 care of myself, without taking care of ships, barques, brigs,
609 schooners, and what not.  And as for going as cook,--though I confess
610 there is considerable glory in that, a cook being a sort of officer
611 on ship-board--yet, somehow, I never fancied broiling fowls;--though
612 once broiled, judiciously buttered, and judgmatically salted and
613 peppered, there is no one who will speak more respectfully, not to
614 say reverentially, of a broiled fowl than I will.  It is out of the
615 idolatrous dotings of the old Egyptians upon broiled ibis and roasted
616 river horse, that you see the mummies of those creatures in their
617 huge bake-houses the pyramids.
618 
619 No, when I go to sea, I go as a simple sailor, right before the mast,
620 plumb down into the forecastle, aloft there to the royal mast-head.
621 True, they rather order me about some, and make me jump from spar to
622 spar, like a grasshopper in a May meadow.  And at first, this sort of
623 thing is unpleasant enough.  It touches one's sense of honour,
624 particularly if you come of an old established family in the land,
625 the Van Rensselaers, or Randolphs, or Hardicanutes.  And more than
626 all, if just previous to putting your hand into the tar-pot, you have
627 been lording it as a country schoolmaster, making the tallest boys
628 stand in awe of you.  The transition is a keen one, I assure you,
629 from a schoolmaster to a sailor, and requires a strong decoction of
630 Seneca and the Stoics to enable you to grin and bear it.  But even
631 this wears off in time.
632 
633 What of it, if some old hunks of a sea-captain orders me to get a
634 broom and sweep down the decks?  What does that indignity amount to,
635 weighed, I mean, in the scales of the New Testament?  Do you think
636 the archangel Gabriel thinks anything the less of me, because I
637 promptly and respectfully obey that old hunks in that particular
638 instance?  Who ain't a slave?  Tell me that.  Well, then, however the
639 old sea-captains may order me about--however they may thump and punch
640 me about, I have the satisfaction of knowing that it is all right;
641 that everybody else is one way or other served in much the same
642 way--either in a physical or metaphysical point of view, that is; and
643 so the universal thump is passed round, and all hands should rub each
644 other's shoulder-blades, and be content.
645 
646 Again, I always go to sea as a sailor, because they make a point of
647 paying me for my trouble, whereas they never pay passengers a single
648 penny that I ever heard of.  On the contrary, passengers themselves
649 must pay.  And there is all the difference in the world between
650 paying and being paid.  The act of paying is perhaps the most
651 uncomfortable infliction that the two orchard thieves entailed upon
652 us.  But BEING PAID,--what will compare with it?  The urbane activity
653 with which a man receives money is really marvellous, considering
654 that we so earnestly believe money to be the root of all earthly
655 ills, and that on no account can a monied man enter heaven.  Ah! how
656 cheerfully we consign ourselves to perdition!
657 
658 Finally, I always go to sea as a sailor, because of the wholesome
659 exercise and pure air of the fore-castle deck.  For as in this world,
660 head winds are far more prevalent than winds from astern (that is, if
661 you never violate the Pythagorean maxim), so for the most part the
662 Commodore on the quarter-deck gets his atmosphere at second hand from
663 the sailors on the forecastle.  He thinks he breathes it first; but
664 not so.  In much the same way do the commonalty lead their leaders in
665 many other things, at the same time that the leaders little suspect
666 it.  But wherefore it was that after having repeatedly smelt the sea
667 as a merchant sailor, I should now take it into my head to go on a
668 whaling voyage; this the invisible police officer of the Fates, who
669 has the constant surveillance of me, and secretly dogs me, and
670 influences me in some unaccountable way--he can better answer than
671 any one else.  And, doubtless, my going on this whaling voyage,
672 formed part of the grand programme of Providence that was drawn up a
673 long time ago.  It came in as a sort of brief interlude and solo
674 between more extensive performances.  I take it that this part of the
675 bill must have run something like this:
676 
677 
678 "GRAND CONTESTED ELECTION FOR THE PRESIDENCY OF THE UNITED STATES.
679 "WHALING VOYAGE BY ONE ISHMAEL.
680 "BLOODY BATTLE IN AFFGHANISTAN."
681 
682 
683 Though I cannot tell why it was exactly that those stage managers,
684 the Fates, put me down for this shabby part of a whaling voyage, when
685 others were set down for magnificent parts in high tragedies, and
686 short and easy parts in genteel comedies, and jolly parts in
687 farces--though I cannot tell why this was exactly; yet, now that I
688 recall all the circumstances, I think I can see a little into the
689 springs and motives which being cunningly presented to me under
690 various disguises, induced me to set about performing the part I did,
691 besides cajoling me into the delusion that it was a choice resulting
692 from my own unbiased freewill and discriminating judgment.
693 
694 Chief among these motives was the overwhelming idea of the great
695 whale himself.  Such a portentous and mysterious monster roused all
696 my curiosity.  Then the wild and distant seas where he rolled his
697 island bulk; the undeliverable, nameless perils of the whale; these,
698 with all the attending marvels of a thousand Patagonian sights and
699 sounds, helped to sway me to my wish.  With other men, perhaps, such
700 things would not have been inducements; but as for me, I am tormented
701 with an everlasting itch for things remote.  I love to sail forbidden
702 seas, and land on barbarous coasts.  Not ignoring what is good, I am
703 quick to perceive a horror, and could still be social with it--would
704 they let me--since it is but well to be on friendly terms with all
705 the inmates of the place one lodges in.
706 
707 By reason of these things, then, the whaling voyage was welcome; the
708 great flood-gates of the wonder-world swung open, and in the wild
709 conceits that swayed me to my purpose, two and two there floated into
710 my inmost soul, endless processions of the whale, and, mid most of
711 them all, one grand hooded phantom, like a snow hill in the air.
712 
713 
714 
715 CHAPTER 2
716 
717 The Carpet-Bag.
718 
719 
720 I stuffed a shirt or two into my old carpet-bag, tucked it under my
721 arm, and started for Cape Horn and the Pacific.  Quitting the good
722 city of old Manhatto, I duly arrived in New Bedford.  It was a
723 Saturday night in December.  Much was I disappointed upon learning
724 that the little packet for Nantucket had already sailed, and that no
725 way of reaching that place would offer, till the following Monday.
726 
727 As most young candidates for the pains and penalties of whaling stop
728 at this same New Bedford, thence to embark on their voyage, it may as
729 well be related that I, for one, had no idea of so doing.  For my
730 mind was made up to sail in no other than a Nantucket craft, because
731 there was a fine, boisterous something about everything connected
732 with that famous old island, which amazingly pleased me.  Besides
733 though New Bedford has of late been gradually monopolising the
734 business of whaling, and though in this matter poor old Nantucket is
735 now much behind her, yet Nantucket was her great original--the Tyre
736 of this Carthage;--the place where the first dead American whale was
737 stranded.  Where else but from Nantucket did those aboriginal
738 whalemen, the Red-Men, first sally out in canoes to give chase to the
739 Leviathan?  And where but from Nantucket, too, did that first
740 adventurous little sloop put forth, partly laden with imported
741 cobblestones--so goes the story--to throw at the whales, in order to
742 discover when they were nigh enough to risk a harpoon from the
743 bowsprit?
744 
745 Now having a night, a day, and still another night following before
746 me in New Bedford, ere I could embark for my destined port, it
747 became a matter of concernment where I was to eat and sleep
748 meanwhile.  It was a very dubious-looking, nay, a very dark and
749 dismal night, bitingly cold and cheerless.  I knew no one in the
750 place.  With anxious grapnels I had sounded my pocket, and only
751 brought up a few pieces of silver,--So, wherever you go, Ishmael,
752 said I to myself, as I stood in the middle of a dreary street
753 shouldering my bag, and comparing the gloom towards the north with
754 the darkness towards the south--wherever in your wisdom you may
755 conclude to lodge for the night, my dear Ishmael, be sure to inquire
756 the price, and don't be too particular.
757 
758 With halting steps I paced the streets, and passed the sign of "The
759 Crossed Harpoons"--but it looked too expensive and jolly there.
760 Further on, from the bright red windows of the "Sword-Fish Inn,"
761 there came such fervent rays, that it seemed to have melted the
762 packed snow and ice from before the house, for everywhere else the
763 congealed frost lay ten inches thick in a hard, asphaltic
764 pavement,--rather weary for me, when I struck my foot against the
765 flinty projections, because from hard, remorseless service the soles
766 of my boots were in a most miserable plight.  Too expensive and
767 jolly, again thought I, pausing one moment to watch the broad glare
768 in the street, and hear the sounds of the tinkling glasses within.
769 But go on, Ishmael, said I at last; don't you hear? get away from
770 before the door; your patched boots are stopping the way.  So on I
771 went.  I now by instinct followed the streets that took me waterward,
772 for there, doubtless, were the cheapest, if not the cheeriest inns.
773 
774 Such dreary streets! blocks of blackness, not houses, on either
775 hand, and here and there a candle, like a candle moving about in a
776 tomb.  At this hour of the night, of the last day of the week, that
777 quarter of the town proved all but deserted.  But presently I came to
778 a smoky light proceeding from a low, wide building, the door of which
779 stood invitingly open.  It had a careless look, as if it were meant
780 for the uses of the public; so, entering, the first thing I did was
781 to stumble over an ash-box in the porch.  Ha! thought I, ha, as the
782 flying particles almost choked me, are these ashes from that
783 destroyed city, Gomorrah?  But "The Crossed Harpoons," and "The
784 Sword-Fish?"--this, then must needs be the sign of "The Trap."
785 However, I picked myself up and hearing a loud voice within, pushed
786 on and opened a second, interior door.
787 
788 It seemed the great Black Parliament sitting in Tophet.  A hundred
789 black faces turned round in their rows to peer; and beyond, a black
790 Angel of Doom was beating a book in a pulpit.  It was a negro church;
791 and the preacher's text was about the blackness of darkness, and the
792 weeping and wailing and teeth-gnashing there.  Ha, Ishmael, muttered
793 I, backing out, Wretched entertainment at the sign of 'The Trap!'
794 
795 Moving on, I at last came to a dim sort of light not far from the
796 docks, and heard a forlorn creaking in the air; and looking up, saw a
797 swinging sign over the door with a white painting upon it, faintly
798 representing a tall straight jet of misty spray, and these words
799 underneath--"The Spouter Inn:--Peter Coffin."
800 
801 Coffin?--Spouter?--Rather ominous in that particular connexion,
802 thought I.  But it is a common name in Nantucket, they say, and I
803 suppose this Peter here is an emigrant from there.  As the light
804 looked so dim, and the place, for the time, looked quiet enough, and
805 the dilapidated little wooden house itself looked as if it might have
806 been carted here from the ruins of some burnt district, and as the
807 swinging sign had a poverty-stricken sort of creak to it, I thought
808 that here was the very spot for cheap lodgings, and the best of pea
809 coffee.
810 
811 It was a queer sort of place--a gable-ended old house, one side
812 palsied as it were, and leaning over sadly.  It stood on a sharp
813 bleak corner, where that tempestuous wind Euroclydon kept up a worse
814 howling than ever it did about poor Paul's tossed craft.  Euroclydon,
815 nevertheless, is a mighty pleasant zephyr to any one in-doors, with
816 his feet on the hob quietly toasting for bed.  "In judging of that
817 tempestuous wind called Euroclydon," says an old writer--of whose
818 works I possess the only copy extant--"it maketh a marvellous
819 difference, whether thou lookest out at it from a glass window where
820 the frost is all on the outside, or whether thou observest it from
821 that sashless window, where the frost is on both sides, and of which
822 the wight Death is the only glazier."  True enough, thought I, as
823 this passage occurred to my mind--old black-letter, thou reasonest
824 well.  Yes, these eyes are windows, and this body of mine is the
825 house.  What a pity they didn't stop up the chinks and the crannies
826 though, and thrust in a little lint here and there.  But it's too
827 late to make any improvements now.  The universe is finished; the
828 copestone is on, and the chips were carted off a million years ago.
829 Poor Lazarus there, chattering his teeth against the curbstone for
830 his pillow, and shaking off his tatters with his shiverings, he might
831 plug up both ears with rags, and put a corn-cob into his mouth, and
832 yet that would not keep out the tempestuous Euroclydon.  Euroclydon!
833 says old Dives, in his red silken wrapper--(he had a redder one
834 afterwards) pooh, pooh!  What a fine frosty night; how Orion
835 glitters; what northern lights!  Let them talk of their oriental
836 summer climes of everlasting conservatories; give me the privilege of
837 making my own summer with my own coals.
838 
839 But what thinks Lazarus?  Can he warm his blue hands by holding them
840 up to the grand northern lights?  Would not Lazarus rather be in
841 Sumatra than here?  Would he not far rather lay him down lengthwise
842 along the line of the equator; yea, ye gods! go down to the fiery pit
843 itself, in order to keep out this frost?
844 
845 Now, that Lazarus should lie stranded there on the curbstone before
846 the door of Dives, this is more wonderful than that an iceberg should
847 be moored to one of the Moluccas.  Yet Dives himself, he too lives
848 like a Czar in an ice palace made of frozen sighs, and being a
849 president of a temperance society, he only drinks the tepid tears of
850 orphans.
851 
852 But no more of this blubbering now, we are going a-whaling, and there
853 is plenty of that yet to come.  Let us scrape the ice from our
854 frosted feet, and see what sort of a place this "Spouter" may be.
855 
856 
857 
858 CHAPTER 3
859 
860 The Spouter-Inn.
861 
862 
863 Entering that gable-ended Spouter-Inn, you found yourself in a wide,
864 low, straggling entry with old-fashioned wainscots, reminding one of
865 the bulwarks of some condemned old craft.  On one side hung a very
866 large oilpainting so thoroughly besmoked, and every way defaced,
867 that in the unequal crosslights by which you viewed it, it was only
868 by diligent study and a series of systematic visits to it, and
869 careful inquiry of the neighbors, that you could any way arrive at an
870 understanding of its purpose.  Such unaccountable masses of shades
871 and shadows, that at first you almost thought some ambitious young
872 artist, in the time of the New England hags, had endeavored to
873 delineate chaos bewitched.  But by dint of much and earnest
874 contemplation, and oft repeated ponderings, and especially by
875 throwing open the little window towards the back of the entry, you at
876 last come to the conclusion that such an idea, however wild, might
877 not be altogether unwarranted.
878 
879 But what most puzzled and confounded you was a long, limber,
880 portentous, black mass of something hovering in the centre of the
881 picture over three blue, dim, perpendicular lines floating in a
882 nameless yeast.  A boggy, soggy, squitchy picture truly, enough to
883 drive a nervous man distracted.  Yet was there a sort of indefinite,
884 half-attained, unimaginable sublimity about it that fairly froze you
885 to it, till you involuntarily took an oath with yourself to find out
886 what that marvellous painting meant.  Ever and anon a bright, but,
887 alas, deceptive idea would dart you through.--It's the Black Sea in a
888 midnight gale.--It's the unnatural combat of the four primal
889 elements.--It's a blasted heath.--It's a Hyperborean winter
890 scene.--It's the breaking-up of the icebound stream of Time.  But at
891 last all these fancies yielded to that one portentous something in
892 the picture's midst.  THAT once found out, and all the rest were
893 plain.  But stop; does it not bear a faint resemblance to a gigantic
894 fish? even the great leviathan himself?
895 
896 In fact, the artist's design seemed this: a final theory of my own,
897 partly based upon the aggregated opinions of many aged persons with
898 whom I conversed upon the subject.  The picture represents a
899 Cape-Horner in a great hurricane; the half-foundered ship weltering
900 there with its three dismantled masts alone visible; and an
901 exasperated whale, purposing to spring clean over the craft, is in
902 the enormous act of impaling himself upon the three mast-heads.
903 
904 The opposite wall of this entry was hung all over with a heathenish
905 array of monstrous clubs and spears.  Some were thickly set with
906 glittering teeth resembling ivory saws; others were tufted with knots
907 of human hair; and one was sickle-shaped, with a vast handle sweeping
908 round like the segment made in the new-mown grass by a long-armed
909 mower.  You shuddered as you gazed, and wondered what monstrous
910 cannibal and savage could ever have gone a death-harvesting with such
911 a hacking, horrifying implement.  Mixed with these were rusty old
912 whaling lances and harpoons all broken and deformed.  Some were
913 storied weapons.  With this once long lance, now wildly elbowed,
914 fifty years ago did Nathan Swain kill fifteen whales between a
915 sunrise and a sunset.  And that harpoon--so like a corkscrew now--was
916 flung in Javan seas, and run away with by a whale, years afterwards
917 slain off the Cape of Blanco.  The original iron entered nigh the
918 tail, and, like a restless needle sojourning in the body of a man,
919 travelled full forty feet, and at last was found imbedded in the
920 hump.
921 
922 Crossing this dusky entry, and on through yon low-arched way--cut
923 through what in old times must have been a great central chimney with
924 fireplaces all round--you enter the public room.  A still duskier
925 place is this, with such low ponderous beams above, and such old
926 wrinkled planks beneath, that you would almost fancy you trod some
927 old craft's cockpits, especially of such a howling night, when this
928 corner-anchored old ark rocked so furiously.  On one side stood a
929 long, low, shelf-like table covered with cracked glass cases, filled
930 with dusty rarities gathered from this wide world's remotest nooks.
931 Projecting from the further angle of the room stands a dark-looking
932 den--the bar--a rude attempt at a right whale's head.  Be that how it
933 may, there stands the vast arched bone of the whale's jaw, so wide, a
934 coach might almost drive beneath it.  Within are shabby shelves,
935 ranged round with old decanters, bottles, flasks; and in those jaws
936 of swift destruction, like another cursed Jonah (by which name indeed
937 they called him), bustles a little withered old man, who, for their
938 money, dearly sells the sailors deliriums and death.
939 
940 Abominable are the tumblers into which he pours his poison.  Though
941 true cylinders without--within, the villanous green goggling glasses
942 deceitfully tapered downwards to a cheating bottom.  Parallel
943 meridians rudely pecked into the glass, surround these footpads'
944 goblets.  Fill to THIS mark, and your charge is but a penny; to THIS
945 a penny more; and so on to the full glass--the Cape Horn measure,
946 which you may gulp down for a shilling.
947 
948 Upon entering the place I found a number of young seamen gathered
949 about a table, examining by a dim light divers specimens of
950 SKRIMSHANDER.  I sought the landlord, and telling him I desired to be
951 accommodated with a room, received for answer that his house was
952 full--not a bed unoccupied.  "But avast," he added, tapping his
953 forehead, "you haint no objections to sharing a harpooneer's blanket,
954 have ye?  I s'pose you are goin' a-whalin', so you'd better get used
955 to that sort of thing."
956 
957 I told him that I never liked to sleep two in a bed; that if I should
958 ever do so, it would depend upon who the harpooneer might be, and
959 that if he (the landlord) really had no other place for me, and the
960 harpooneer was not decidedly objectionable, why rather than wander
961 further about a strange town on so bitter a night, I would put up
962 with the half of any decent man's blanket.
963 
964 "I thought so.  All right; take a seat.  Supper?--you want supper?
965 Supper'll be ready directly."
966 
967 I sat down on an old wooden settle, carved all over like a bench on
968 the Battery.  At one end a ruminating tar was still further adorning
969 it with his jack-knife, stooping over and diligently working away at
970 the space between his legs.  He was trying his hand at a ship under
971 full sail, but he didn't make much headway, I thought.
972 
973 At last some four or five of us were summoned to our meal in an
974 adjoining room.  It was cold as Iceland--no fire at all--the landlord
975 said he couldn't afford it.  Nothing but two dismal tallow candles,
976 each in a winding sheet.  We were fain to button up our monkey
977 jackets, and hold to our lips cups of scalding tea with our half
978 frozen fingers.  But the fare was of the most substantial kind--not
979 only meat and potatoes, but dumplings; good heavens! dumplings for
980 supper!  One young fellow in a green box coat, addressed himself to
981 these dumplings in a most direful manner.
982 
983 "My boy," said the landlord, "you'll have the nightmare to a dead
984 sartainty."
985 
986 "Landlord," I whispered, "that aint the harpooneer is it?"
987 
988 "Oh, no," said he, looking a sort of diabolically funny, "the
989 harpooneer is a dark complexioned chap.  He never eats dumplings, he
990 don't--he eats nothing but steaks, and he likes 'em rare."
991 
992 "The devil he does," says I.  "Where is that harpooneer?  Is he
993 here?"
994 
995 "He'll be here afore long," was the answer.
996 
997 I could not help it, but I began to feel suspicious of this "dark
998 complexioned" harpooneer.  At any rate, I made up my mind that if it
999 so turned out that we should sleep together, he must undress and get
1000 into bed before I did.
1001 
1002 Supper over, the company went back to the bar-room, when, knowing not
1003 what else to do with myself, I resolved to spend the rest of the
1004 evening as a looker on.
1005 
1006 Presently a rioting noise was heard without.  Starting up, the
1007 landlord cried, "That's the Grampus's crew.  I seed her reported in
1008 the offing this morning; a three years' voyage, and a full ship.
1009 Hurrah, boys; now we'll have the latest news from the Feegees."
1010 
1011 A tramping of sea boots was heard in the entry; the door was flung
1012 open, and in rolled a wild set of mariners enough.  Enveloped in
1013 their shaggy watch coats, and with their heads muffled in woollen
1014 comforters, all bedarned and ragged, and their beards stiff with
1015 icicles, they seemed an eruption of bears from Labrador.  They had
1016 just landed from their boat, and this was the first house they
1017 entered.  No wonder, then, that they made a straight wake for the
1018 whale's mouth--the bar--when the wrinkled little old Jonah, there
1019 officiating, soon poured them out brimmers all round.  One complained
1020 of a bad cold in his head, upon which Jonah mixed him a pitch-like
1021 potion of gin and molasses, which he swore was a sovereign cure for
1022 all colds and catarrhs whatsoever, never mind of how long standing,
1023 or whether caught off the coast of Labrador, or on the weather side
1024 of an ice-island.
1025 
1026 The liquor soon mounted into their heads, as it generally does even
1027 with the arrantest topers newly landed from sea, and they began
1028 capering about most obstreperously.
1029 
1030 I observed, however, that one of them held somewhat aloof, and though
1031 he seemed desirous not to spoil the hilarity of his shipmates by his
1032 own sober face, yet upon the whole he refrained from making as much
1033 noise as the rest.  This man interested me at once; and since the
1034 sea-gods had ordained that he should soon become my shipmate (though
1035 but a sleeping-partner one, so far as this narrative is concerned),
1036 I will here venture upon a little description of him.  He stood full
1037 six feet in height, with noble shoulders, and a chest like a
1038 coffer-dam.  I have seldom seen such brawn in a man.  His face was
1039 deeply brown and burnt, making his white teeth dazzling by the
1040 contrast; while in the deep shadows of his eyes floated some
1041 reminiscences that did not seem to give him much joy.  His voice at
1042 once announced that he was a Southerner, and from his fine stature, I
1043 thought he must be one of those tall mountaineers from the
1044 Alleghanian Ridge in Virginia.  When the revelry of his companions
1045 had mounted to its height, this man slipped away unobserved, and I
1046 saw no more of him till he became my comrade on the sea.  In a few
1047 minutes, however, he was missed by his shipmates, and being, it
1048 seems, for some reason a huge favourite with them, they raised a cry
1049 of "Bulkington!  Bulkington! where's Bulkington?" and darted out of
1050 the house in pursuit of him.
1051 
1052 It was now about nine o'clock, and the room seeming almost
1053 supernaturally quiet after these orgies, I began to congratulate
1054 myself upon a little plan that had occurred to me just previous to
1055 the entrance of the seamen.
1056 
1057 No man prefers to sleep two in a bed.  In fact, you would a good deal
1058 rather not sleep with your own brother.  I don't know how it is, but
1059 people like to be private when they are sleeping.  And when it comes
1060 to sleeping with an unknown stranger, in a strange inn, in a strange
1061 town, and that stranger a harpooneer, then your objections
1062 indefinitely multiply.  Nor was there any earthly reason why I as a
1063 sailor should sleep two in a bed, more than anybody else; for sailors
1064 no more sleep two in a bed at sea, than bachelor Kings do ashore.  To
1065 be sure they all sleep together in one apartment, but you have your
1066 own hammock, and cover yourself with your own blanket, and sleep in
1067 your own skin.
1068 
1069 The more I pondered over this harpooneer, the more I abominated the
1070 thought of sleeping with him.  It was fair to presume that being a
1071 harpooneer, his linen or woollen, as the case might be, would not be
1072 of the tidiest, certainly none of the finest.  I began to twitch all
1073 over.  Besides, it was getting late, and my decent harpooneer ought
1074 to be home and going bedwards.  Suppose now, he should tumble in upon
1075 me at midnight--how could I tell from what vile hole he had been
1076 coming?
1077 
1078 "Landlord!  I've changed my mind about that harpooneer.--I shan't
1079 sleep with him.  I'll try the bench here."
1080 
1081 "Just as you please; I'm sorry I cant spare ye a tablecloth for a
1082 mattress, and it's a plaguy rough board here"--feeling of the knots
1083 and notches.  "But wait a bit, Skrimshander; I've got a carpenter's
1084 plane there in the bar--wait, I say, and I'll make ye snug enough."
1085 So saying he procured the plane; and with his old silk handkerchief
1086 first dusting the bench, vigorously set to planing away at my bed,
1087 the while grinning like an ape.  The shavings flew right and left;
1088 till at last the plane-iron came bump against an indestructible knot.
1089 The landlord was near spraining his wrist, and I told him for
1090 heaven's sake to quit--the bed was soft enough to suit me, and I did
1091 not know how all the planing in the world could make eider down of a
1092 pine plank.  So gathering up the shavings with another grin, and
1093 throwing them into the great stove in the middle of the room, he went
1094 about his business, and left me in a brown study.
1095 
1096 I now took the measure of the bench, and found that it was a foot too
1097 short; but that could be mended with a chair.  But it was a foot too
1098 narrow, and the other bench in the room was about four inches higher
1099 than the planed one--so there was no yoking them.  I then placed the
1100 first bench lengthwise along the only clear space against the wall,
1101 leaving a little interval between, for my back to settle down in.
1102 But I soon found that there came such a draught of cold air over me
1103 from under the sill of the window, that this plan would never do at
1104 all, especially as another current from the rickety door met the one
1105 from the window, and both together formed a series of small
1106 whirlwinds in the immediate vicinity of the spot where I had thought
1107 to spend the night.
1108 
1109 The devil fetch that harpooneer, thought I, but stop, couldn't I
1110 steal a march on him--bolt his door inside, and jump into his bed,
1111 not to be wakened by the most violent knockings?  It seemed no bad
1112 idea; but upon second thoughts I dismissed it.  For who could tell
1113 but what the next morning, so soon as I popped out of the room, the
1114 harpooneer might be standing in the entry, all ready to knock me
1115 down!
1116 
1117 Still, looking round me again, and seeing no possible chance of
1118 spending a sufferable night unless in some other person's bed, I
1119 began to think that after all I might be cherishing unwarrantable
1120 prejudices against this unknown harpooneer.  Thinks I, I'll wait
1121 awhile; he must be dropping in before long.  I'll have a good look at
1122 him then, and perhaps we may become jolly good bedfellows after
1123 all--there's no telling.
1124 
1125 But though the other boarders kept coming in by ones, twos, and
1126 threes, and going to bed, yet no sign of my harpooneer.
1127 
1128 "Landlord! said I, "what sort of a chap is he--does he always keep
1129 such late hours?"  It was now hard upon twelve o'clock.
1130 
1131 The landlord chuckled again with his lean chuckle, and seemed to be
1132 mightily tickled at something beyond my comprehension.  "No," he
1133 answered, "generally he's an early bird--airley to bed and airley to
1134 rise--yes, he's the bird what catches the worm.  But to-night he
1135 went out a peddling, you see, and I don't see what on airth keeps him
1136 so late, unless, may be, he can't sell his head."
1137 
1138 "Can't sell his head?--What sort of a bamboozingly story is this you
1139 are telling me?" getting into a towering rage.  "Do you pretend to
1140 say, landlord, that this harpooneer is actually engaged this blessed
1141 Saturday night, or rather Sunday morning, in peddling his head around
1142 this town?"
1143 
1144 "That's precisely it," said the landlord, "and I told him he couldn't
1145 sell it here, the market's overstocked."
1146 
1147 "With what?" shouted I.
1148 
1149 "With heads to be sure; ain't there too many heads in the world?"
1150 
1151 "I tell you what it is, landlord," said I quite calmly, "you'd better
1152 stop spinning that yarn to me--I'm not green."
1153 
1154 "May be not," taking out a stick and whittling a toothpick, "but I
1155 rayther guess you'll be done BROWN if that ere harpooneer hears you a
1156 slanderin' his head."
1157 
1158 "I'll break it for him," said I, now flying into a passion again at
1159 this unaccountable farrago of the landlord's.
1160 
1161 "It's broke a'ready," said he.
1162 
1163 "Broke," said I--"BROKE, do you mean?"
1164 
1165 "Sartain, and that's the very reason he can't sell it, I guess."
1166 
1167 "Landlord," said I, going up to him as cool as Mt. Hecla in a
1168 snow-storm--"landlord, stop whittling.  You and I must understand one
1169 another, and that too without delay.  I come to your house and want a
1170 bed; you tell me you can only give me half a one; that the other half
1171 belongs to a certain harpooneer.  And about this harpooneer, whom I
1172 have not yet seen, you persist in telling me the most mystifying and
1173 exasperating stories tending to beget in me an uncomfortable feeling
1174 towards the man whom you design for my bedfellow--a sort of
1175 connexion, landlord, which is an intimate and confidential one in the
1176 highest degree.  I now demand of you to speak out and tell me who and
1177 what this harpooneer is, and whether I shall be in all respects safe
1178 to spend the night with him.  And in the first place, you will be so
1179 good as to unsay that story about selling his head, which if true I
1180 take to be good evidence that this harpooneer is stark mad, and I've
1181 no idea of sleeping with a madman; and you, sir, YOU I mean,
1182 landlord, YOU, sir, by trying to induce me to do so knowingly, would
1183 thereby render yourself liable to a criminal prosecution."
1184 
1185 "Wall," said the landlord, fetching a long breath, "that's a purty
1186 long sarmon for a chap that rips a little now and then.  But be easy,
1187 be easy, this here harpooneer I have been tellin' you of has just
1188 arrived from the south seas, where he bought up a lot of 'balmed New
1189 Zealand heads (great curios, you know), and he's sold all on 'em but
1190 one, and that one he's trying to sell to-night, cause to-morrow's
1191 Sunday, and it would not do to be sellin' human heads about the
1192 streets when folks is goin' to churches.  He wanted to, last Sunday,
1193 but I stopped him just as he was goin' out of the door with four
1194 heads strung on a string, for all the airth like a string of inions."
1195 
1196 This account cleared up the otherwise unaccountable mystery, and
1197 showed that the landlord, after all, had had no idea of fooling
1198 me--but at the same time what could I think of a harpooneer who
1199 stayed out of a Saturday night clean into the holy Sabbath, engaged
1200 in such a cannibal business as selling the heads of dead idolators?
1201 
1202 "Depend upon it, landlord, that harpooneer is a dangerous man."
1203 
1204 "He pays reg'lar," was the rejoinder.  "But come, it's getting
1205 dreadful late, you had better be turning flukes--it's a nice bed;
1206 Sal and me slept in that ere bed the night we were spliced.  There's
1207 plenty of room for two to kick about in that bed; it's an almighty
1208 big bed that.  Why, afore we give it up, Sal used to put our Sam and
1209 little Johnny in the foot of it.  But I got a dreaming and sprawling
1210 about one night, and somehow, Sam got pitched on the floor, and came
1211 near breaking his arm.  Arter that, Sal said it wouldn't do.  Come
1212 along here, I'll give ye a glim in a jiffy;" and so saying he lighted
1213 a candle and held it towards me, offering to lead the way.  But I
1214 stood irresolute; when looking at a clock in the corner, he exclaimed
1215 "I vum it's Sunday--you won't see that harpooneer to-night; he's come
1216 to anchor somewhere--come along then; DO come; WON'T ye come?"
1217 
1218 I considered the matter a moment, and then up stairs we went, and I
1219 was ushered into a small room, cold as a clam, and furnished, sure
1220 enough, with a prodigious bed, almost big enough indeed for any four
1221 harpooneers to sleep abreast.
1222 
1223 "There," said the landlord, placing the candle on a crazy old sea
1224 chest that did double duty as a wash-stand and centre table; "there,
1225 make yourself comfortable now, and good night to ye."  I turned
1226 round from eyeing the bed, but he had disappeared.
1227 
1228 Folding back the counterpane, I stooped over the bed.  Though none of
1229 the most elegant, it yet stood the scrutiny tolerably well.  I then
1230 glanced round the room; and besides the bedstead and centre table,
1231 could see no other furniture belonging to the place, but a rude
1232 shelf, the four walls, and a papered fireboard representing a man
1233 striking a whale.  Of things not properly belonging to the room,
1234 there was a hammock lashed up, and thrown upon the floor in one
1235 corner; also a large seaman's bag, containing the harpooneer's
1236 wardrobe, no doubt in lieu of a land trunk.  Likewise, there was a
1237 parcel of outlandish bone fish hooks on the shelf over the
1238 fire-place, and a tall harpoon standing at the head of the bed.
1239 
1240 But what is this on the chest?  I took it up, and held it close to
1241 the light, and felt it, and smelt it, and tried every way possible to
1242 arrive at some satisfactory conclusion concerning it.  I can compare
1243 it to nothing but a large door mat, ornamented at the edges with
1244 little tinkling tags something like the stained porcupine quills
1245 round an Indian moccasin.  There was a hole or slit in the middle of
1246 this mat, as you see the same in South American ponchos.  But could
1247 it be possible that any sober harpooneer would get into a door mat,
1248 and parade the streets of any Christian town in that sort of guise?
1249 I put it on, to try it, and it weighed me down like a hamper, being
1250 uncommonly shaggy and thick, and I thought a little damp, as though
1251 this mysterious harpooneer had been wearing it of a rainy day.  I
1252 went up in it to a bit of glass stuck against the wall, and I never
1253 saw such a sight in my life.  I tore myself out of it in such a hurry
1254 that I gave myself a kink in the neck.
1255 
1256 I sat down on the side of the bed, and commenced thinking about this
1257 head-peddling harpooneer, and his door mat.  After thinking some time
1258 on the bed-side, I got up and took off my monkey jacket, and then
1259 stood in the middle of the room thinking.  I then took off my coat,
1260 and thought a little more in my shirt sleeves.  But beginning to feel
1261 very cold now, half undressed as I was, and remembering what the
1262 landlord said about the harpooneer's not coming home at all that
1263 night, it being so very late, I made no more ado, but jumped out of
1264 my pantaloons and boots, and then blowing out the light tumbled into
1265 bed, and commended myself to the care of heaven.
1266 
1267 Whether that mattress was stuffed with corn-cobs or broken crockery,
1268 there is no telling, but I rolled about a good deal, and could not
1269 sleep for a long time.  At last I slid off into a light doze, and had
1270 pretty nearly made a good offing towards the land of Nod, when I
1271 heard a heavy footfall in the passage, and saw a glimmer of light
1272 come into the room from under the door.
1273 
1274 Lord save me, thinks I, that must be the harpooneer, the infernal
1275 head-peddler.  But I lay perfectly still, and resolved not to say a
1276 word till spoken to.  Holding a light in one hand, and that identical
1277 New Zealand head in the other, the stranger entered the room, and
1278 without looking towards the bed, placed his candle a good way off
1279 from me on the floor in one corner, and then began working away at
1280 the knotted cords of the large bag I before spoke of as being in the
1281 room.  I was all eagerness to see his face, but he kept it averted
1282 for some time while employed in unlacing the bag's mouth.  This
1283 accomplished, however, he turned round--when, good heavens! what a
1284 sight!  Such a face!  It was of a dark, purplish, yellow colour, here
1285 and there stuck over with large blackish looking squares.  Yes, it's
1286 just as I thought, he's a terrible bedfellow; he's been in a fight,
1287 got dreadfully cut, and here he is, just from the surgeon.  But at
1288 that moment he chanced to turn his face so towards the light, that I
1289 plainly saw they could not be sticking-plasters at all, those black
1290 squares on his cheeks.  They were stains of some sort or other.  At
1291 first I knew not what to make of this; but soon an inkling of the
1292 truth occurred to me.  I remembered a story of a white man--a
1293 whaleman too--who, falling among the cannibals, had been tattooed by
1294 them.  I concluded that this harpooneer, in the course of his distant
1295 voyages, must have met with a similar adventure.  And what is it,
1296 thought I, after all!  It's only his outside; a man can be honest in
1297 any sort of skin.  But then, what to make of his unearthly
1298 complexion, that part of it, I mean, lying round about, and
1299 completely independent of the squares of tattooing.  To be sure, it
1300 might be nothing but a good coat of tropical tanning; but I never
1301 heard of a hot sun's tanning a white man into a purplish yellow one.
1302 However, I had never been in the South Seas; and perhaps the sun
1303 there produced these extraordinary effects upon the skin.  Now, while
1304 all these ideas were passing through me like lightning, this
1305 harpooneer never noticed me at all.  But, after some difficulty
1306 having opened his bag, he commenced fumbling in it, and presently
1307 pulled out a sort of tomahawk, and a seal-skin wallet with the hair
1308 on.  Placing these on the old chest in the middle of the room, he
1309 then took the New Zealand head--a ghastly thing enough--and crammed
1310 it down into the bag.  He now took off his hat--a new beaver
1311 hat--when I came nigh singing out with fresh surprise.  There was no
1312 hair on his head--none to speak of at least--nothing but a small
1313 scalp-knot twisted up on his forehead.  His bald purplish head now
1314 looked for all the world like a mildewed skull.  Had not the stranger
1315 stood between me and the door, I would have bolted out of it quicker
1316 than ever I bolted a dinner.
1317 
1318 Even as it was, I thought something of slipping out of the window,
1319 but it was the second floor back.  I am no coward, but what to make
1320 of this head-peddling purple rascal altogether passed my
1321 comprehension.  Ignorance is the parent of fear, and being completely
1322 nonplussed and confounded about the stranger, I confess I was now as
1323 much afraid of him as if it was the devil himself who had thus broken
1324 into my room at the dead of night.  In fact, I was so afraid of him
1325 that I was not game enough just then to address him, and demand a
1326 satisfactory answer concerning what seemed inexplicable in him.
1327 
1328 Meanwhile, he continued the business of undressing, and at last
1329 showed his chest and arms.  As I live, these covered parts of him
1330 were checkered with the same squares as his face; his back, too, was
1331 all over the same dark squares; he seemed to have been in a Thirty
1332 Years' War, and just escaped from it with a sticking-plaster shirt.
1333 Still more, his very legs were marked, as if a parcel of dark green
1334 frogs were running up the trunks of young palms.  It was now quite
1335 plain that he must be some abominable savage or other shipped aboard
1336 of a whaleman in the South Seas, and so landed in this Christian
1337 country.  I quaked to think of it.  A peddler of heads too--perhaps
1338 the heads of his own brothers.  He might take a fancy to
1339 mine--heavens! look at that tomahawk!
1340 
1341 But there was no time for shuddering, for now the savage went about
1342 something that completely fascinated my attention, and convinced me
1343 that he must indeed be a heathen.  Going to his heavy grego, or
1344 wrapall, or dreadnaught, which he had previously hung on a chair, he
1345 fumbled in the pockets, and produced at length a curious little
1346 deformed image with a hunch on its back, and exactly the colour of a
1347 three days' old Congo baby.  Remembering the embalmed head, at first
1348 I almost thought that this black manikin was a real baby preserved
1349 in some similar manner.  But seeing that it was not at all limber,
1350 and that it glistened a good deal like polished ebony, I concluded
1351 that it must be nothing but a wooden idol, which indeed it proved to
1352 be.  For now the savage goes up to the empty fire-place, and removing
1353 the papered fire-board, sets up this little hunch-backed image, like
1354 a tenpin, between the andirons.  The chimney jambs and all the bricks
1355 inside were very sooty, so that I thought this fire-place made a very
1356 appropriate little shrine or chapel for his Congo idol.
1357 
1358 I now screwed my eyes hard towards the half hidden image, feeling but
1359 ill at ease meantime--to see what was next to follow.  First he takes
1360 about a double handful of shavings out of his grego pocket, and
1361 places them carefully before the idol; then laying a bit of ship
1362 biscuit on top and applying the flame from the lamp, he kindled the
1363 shavings into a sacrificial blaze.  Presently, after many hasty
1364 snatches into the fire, and still hastier withdrawals of his fingers
1365 (whereby he seemed to be scorching them badly), he at last succeeded
1366 in drawing out the biscuit; then blowing off the heat and ashes a
1367 little, he made a polite offer of it to the little negro.  But the
1368 little devil did not seem to fancy such dry sort of fare at all; he
1369 never moved his lips.  All these strange antics were accompanied by
1370 still stranger guttural noises from the devotee, who seemed to be
1371 praying in a sing-song or else singing some pagan psalmody or other,
1372 during which his face twitched about in the most unnatural manner.
1373 At last extinguishing the fire, he took the idol up very
1374 unceremoniously, and bagged it again in his grego pocket as
1375 carelessly as if he were a sportsman bagging a dead woodcock.
1376 
1377 All these queer proceedings increased my uncomfortableness, and
1378 seeing him now exhibiting strong symptoms of concluding his business
1379 operations, and jumping into bed with me, I thought it was high time,
1380 now or never, before the light was put out, to break the spell in
1381 which I had so long been bound.
1382 
1383 But the interval I spent in deliberating what to say, was a fatal
1384 one.  Taking up his tomahawk from the table, he examined the head of
1385 it for an instant, and then holding it to the light, with his mouth
1386 at the handle, he puffed out great clouds of tobacco smoke.  The next
1387 moment the light was extinguished, and this wild cannibal, tomahawk
1388 between his teeth, sprang into bed with me.  I sang out, I could not
1389 help it now; and giving a sudden grunt of astonishment he began
1390 feeling me.
1391 
1392 Stammering out something, I knew not what, I rolled away from him
1393 against the wall, and then conjured him, whoever or whatever he might
1394 be, to keep quiet, and let me get up and light the lamp again.  But
1395 his guttural responses satisfied me at once that he but ill
1396 comprehended my meaning.
1397 
1398 "Who-e debel you?"--he at last said--"you no speak-e, dam-me, I
1399 kill-e."  And so saying the lighted tomahawk began flourishing about
1400 me in the dark.
1401 
1402 "Landlord, for God's sake, Peter Coffin!" shouted I.  "Landlord!
1403 Watch!  Coffin!  Angels! save me!"
1404 
1405 "Speak-e! tell-ee me who-ee be, or dam-me, I kill-e!" again growled
1406 the cannibal, while his horrid flourishings of the tomahawk scattered
1407 the hot tobacco ashes about me till I thought my linen would get on
1408 fire.  But thank heaven, at that moment the landlord came into the
1409 room light in hand, and leaping from the bed I ran up to him.
1410 
1411 "Don't be afraid now," said he, grinning again, "Queequeg here
1412 wouldn't harm a hair of your head."
1413 
1414 "Stop your grinning," shouted I, "and why didn't you tell me that
1415 that infernal harpooneer was a cannibal?"
1416 
1417 "I thought ye know'd it;--didn't I tell ye, he was a peddlin' heads
1418 around town?--but turn flukes again and go to sleep.  Queequeg, look
1419 here--you sabbee me, I sabbee--you this man sleepe you--you sabbee?"
1420 
1421 "Me sabbee plenty"--grunted Queequeg, puffing away at his pipe and
1422 sitting up in bed.
1423 
1424 "You gettee in," he added, motioning to me with his tomahawk, and
1425 throwing the clothes to one side.  He really did this in not only a
1426 civil but a really kind and charitable way.  I stood looking at him a
1427 moment.  For all his tattooings he was on the whole a clean, comely
1428 looking cannibal.  What's all this fuss I have been making about,
1429 thought I to myself--the man's a human being just as I am: he has
1430 just as much reason to fear me, as I have to be afraid of him.
1431 Better sleep with a sober cannibal than a drunken Christian.
1432 
1433 "Landlord," said I, "tell him to stash his tomahawk there, or pipe,
1434 or whatever you call it; tell him to stop smoking, in short, and I
1435 will turn in with him.  But I don't fancy having a man smoking in bed
1436 with me.  It's dangerous.  Besides, I ain't insured."
1437 
1438 This being told to Queequeg, he at once complied, and again politely
1439 motioned me to get into bed--rolling over to one side as much as to
1440 say--I won't touch a leg of ye."
1441 
1442 "Good night, landlord," said I, "you may go."
1443 
1444 I turned in, and never slept better in my life.
1445 
1446 
1447 
1448 CHAPTER 4
1449 
1450 The Counterpane.
1451 
1452 
1453 Upon waking next morning about daylight, I found Queequeg's arm
1454 thrown over me in the most loving and affectionate manner.  You had
1455 almost thought I had been his wife.  The counterpane was of
1456 patchwork, full of odd little parti-coloured squares and triangles;
1457 and this arm of his tattooed all over with an interminable Cretan
1458 labyrinth of a figure, no two parts of which were of one precise
1459 shade--owing I suppose to his keeping his arm at sea unmethodically
1460 in sun and shade, his shirt sleeves irregularly rolled up at various
1461 times--this same arm of his, I say, looked for all the world like a
1462 strip of that same patchwork quilt.  Indeed, partly lying on it as
1463 the arm did when I first awoke, I could hardly tell it from the
1464 quilt, they so blended their hues together; and it was only by the
1465 sense of weight and pressure that I could tell that Queequeg was
1466 hugging me.
1467 
1468 My sensations were strange.  Let me try to explain them.  When I was
1469 a child, I well remember a somewhat similar circumstance that befell
1470 me; whether it was a reality or a dream, I never could entirely
1471 settle.  The circumstance was this.  I had been cutting up some caper
1472 or other--I think it was trying to crawl up the chimney, as I had
1473 seen a little sweep do a few days previous; and my stepmother who,
1474 somehow or other, was all the time whipping me, or sending me to bed
1475 supperless,--my mother dragged me by the legs out of the chimney and
1476 packed me off to bed, though it was only two o'clock in the afternoon
1477 of the 21st June, the longest day in the year in our hemisphere.  I
1478 felt dreadfully.  But there was no help for it, so up stairs I went
1479 to my little room in the third floor, undressed myself as slowly as
1480 possible so as to kill time, and with a bitter sigh got between the
1481 sheets.
1482 
1483 I lay there dismally calculating that sixteen entire hours must
1484 elapse before I could hope for a resurrection.  Sixteen hours in bed!
1485 the small of my back ached to think of it.  And it was so light too;
1486 the sun shining in at the window, and a great rattling of coaches in
1487 the streets, and the sound of gay voices all over the house.  I felt
1488 worse and worse--at last I got up, dressed, and softly going down in
1489 my stockinged feet, sought out my stepmother, and suddenly threw
1490 myself at her feet, beseeching her as a particular favour to give me a
1491 good slippering for my misbehaviour; anything indeed but condemning
1492 me to lie abed such an unendurable length of time.  But she was the
1493 best and most conscientious of stepmothers, and back I had to go to
1494 my room.  For several hours I lay there broad awake, feeling a great
1495 deal worse than I have ever done since, even from the greatest
1496 subsequent misfortunes.  At last I must have fallen into a troubled
1497 nightmare of a doze; and slowly waking from it--half steeped in
1498 dreams--I opened my eyes, and the before sun-lit room was now wrapped
1499 in outer darkness.  Instantly I felt a shock running through all my
1500 frame; nothing was to be seen, and nothing was to be heard; but a
1501 supernatural hand seemed placed in mine.  My arm hung over the
1502 counterpane, and the nameless, unimaginable, silent form or phantom,
1503 to which the hand belonged, seemed closely seated by my bed-side.
1504 For what seemed ages piled on ages, I lay there, frozen with the most
1505 awful fears, not daring to drag away my hand; yet ever thinking that
1506 if I could but stir it one single inch, the horrid spell would be
1507 broken.  I knew not how this consciousness at last glided away from
1508 me; but waking in the morning, I shudderingly remembered it all, and
1509 for days and weeks and months afterwards I lost myself in confounding
1510 attempts to explain the mystery.  Nay, to this very hour, I often
1511 puzzle myself with it.
1512 
1513 Now, take away the awful fear, and my sensations at feeling the
1514 supernatural hand in mine were very similar, in their strangeness,
1515 to those which I experienced on waking up and seeing Queequeg's pagan
1516 arm thrown round me.  But at length all the past night's events
1517 soberly recurred, one by one, in fixed reality, and then I lay only
1518 alive to the comical predicament.  For though I tried to move his
1519 arm--unlock his bridegroom clasp--yet, sleeping as he was, he still
1520 hugged me tightly, as though naught but death should part us twain.
1521 I now strove to rouse him--"Queequeg!"--but his only answer was a
1522 snore.  I then rolled over, my neck feeling as if it were in a
1523 horse-collar; and suddenly felt a slight scratch.  Throwing aside the
1524 counterpane, there lay the tomahawk sleeping by the savage's side, as
1525 if it were a hatchet-faced baby.  A pretty pickle, truly, thought I;
1526 abed here in a strange house in the broad day, with a cannibal and a
1527 tomahawk!  "Queequeg!--in the name of goodness, Queequeg, wake!"  At
1528 length, by dint of much wriggling, and loud and incessant
1529 expostulations upon the unbecomingness of his hugging a fellow male
1530 in that matrimonial sort of style, I succeeded in extracting a grunt;
1531 and presently, he drew back his arm, shook himself all over like a
1532 Newfoundland dog just from the water, and sat up in bed, stiff as a
1533 pike-staff, looking at me, and rubbing his eyes as if he did not
1534 altogether remember how I came to be there, though a dim
1535 consciousness of knowing something about me seemed slowly dawning
1536 over him.  Meanwhile, I lay quietly eyeing him, having no serious
1537 misgivings now, and bent upon narrowly observing so curious a
1538 creature.  When, at last, his mind seemed made up touching the
1539 character of his bedfellow, and he became, as it were, reconciled to
1540 the fact; he jumped out upon the floor, and by certain signs and
1541 sounds gave me to understand that, if it pleased me, he would dress
1542 first and then leave me to dress afterwards, leaving the whole
1543 apartment to myself.  Thinks I, Queequeg, under the circumstances,
1544 this is a very civilized overture; but, the truth is, these savages
1545 have an innate sense of delicacy, say what you will; it is marvellous
1546 how essentially polite they are.  I pay this particular compliment to
1547 Queequeg, because he treated me with so much civility and
1548 consideration, while I was guilty of great rudeness; staring at him
1549 from the bed, and watching all his toilette motions; for the time my
1550 curiosity getting the better of my breeding.  Nevertheless, a man
1551 like Queequeg you don't see every day, he and his ways were well
1552 worth unusual regarding.
1553 
1554 He commenced dressing at top by donning his beaver hat, a very tall
1555 one, by the by, and then--still minus his trowsers--he hunted up his
1556 boots.  What under the heavens he did it for, I cannot tell, but his
1557 next movement was to crush himself--boots in hand, and hat on--under
1558 the bed; when, from sundry violent gaspings and strainings, I
1559 inferred he was hard at work booting himself; though by no law of
1560 propriety that I ever heard of, is any man required to be private
1561 when putting on his boots.  But Queequeg, do you see, was a creature
1562 in the transition stage--neither caterpillar nor butterfly.  He was
1563 just enough civilized to show off his outlandishness in the strangest
1564 possible manners.  His education was not yet completed.  He was an
1565 undergraduate.  If he had not been a small degree civilized, he very
1566 probably would not have troubled himself with boots at all; but then,
1567 if he had not been still a savage, he never would have dreamt of
1568 getting under the bed to put them on.  At last, he emerged with his
1569 hat very much dented and crushed down over his eyes, and began
1570 creaking and limping about the room, as if, not being much accustomed
1571 to boots, his pair of damp, wrinkled cowhide ones--probably not made
1572 to order either--rather pinched and tormented him at the first go off
1573 of a bitter cold morning.
1574 
1575 Seeing, now, that there were no curtains to the window, and that the
1576 street being very narrow, the house opposite commanded a plain view
1577 into the room, and observing more and more the indecorous figure that
1578 Queequeg made, staving about with little else but his hat and boots
1579 on; I begged him as well as I could, to accelerate his toilet
1580 somewhat, and particularly to get into his pantaloons as soon as
1581 possible.  He complied, and then proceeded to wash himself.  At that
1582 time in the morning any Christian would have washed his face; but
1583 Queequeg, to my amazement, contented himself with restricting his
1584 ablutions to his chest, arms, and hands.  He then donned his
1585 waistcoat, and taking up a piece of hard soap on the wash-stand
1586 centre table, dipped it into water and commenced lathering his face.
1587 I was watching to see where he kept his razor, when lo and behold, he
1588 takes the harpoon from the bed corner, slips out the long wooden
1589 stock, unsheathes the head, whets it a little on his boot, and
1590 striding up to the bit of mirror against the wall, begins a vigorous
1591 scraping, or rather harpooning of his cheeks.  Thinks I, Queequeg,
1592 this is using Rogers's best cutlery with a vengeance.  Afterwards I
1593 wondered the less at this operation when I came to know of what fine
1594 steel the head of a harpoon is made, and how exceedingly sharp the
1595 long straight edges are always kept.
1596 
1597 The rest of his toilet was soon achieved, and he proudly marched out
1598 of the room, wrapped up in his great pilot monkey jacket, and
1599 sporting his harpoon like a marshal's baton.
