1604 
1605 Breakfast.
1606 
1607 
1608 I quickly followed suit, and descending into the bar-room accosted
1609 the grinning landlord very pleasantly.  I cherished no malice towards
1610 him, though he had been skylarking with me not a little in the matter
1611 of my bedfellow.
1612 
1613 However, a good laugh is a mighty good thing, and rather too scarce a
1614 good thing; the more's the pity.  So, if any one man, in his own
1615 proper person, afford stuff for a good joke to anybody, let him not
1616 be backward, but let him cheerfully allow himself to spend and be
1617 spent in that way.  And the man that has anything bountifully
1618 laughable about him, be sure there is more in that man than you
1619 perhaps think for.
1620 
1621 The bar-room was now full of the boarders who had been dropping in
1622 the night previous, and whom I had not as yet had a good look at.
1623 They were nearly all whalemen; chief mates, and second mates, and
1624 third mates, and sea carpenters, and sea coopers, and sea
1625 blacksmiths, and harpooneers, and ship keepers; a brown and brawny
1626 company, with bosky beards; an unshorn, shaggy set, all wearing
1627 monkey jackets for morning gowns.
1628 
1629 You could pretty plainly tell how long each one had been ashore.
1630 This young fellow's healthy cheek is like a sun-toasted pear in hue,
1631 and would seem to smell almost as musky; he cannot have been three
1632 days landed from his Indian voyage.  That man next him looks a few
1633 shades lighter; you might say a touch of satin wood is in him.  In
1634 the complexion of a third still lingers a tropic tawn, but slightly
1635 bleached withal; HE doubtless has tarried whole weeks ashore.  But
1636 who could show a cheek like Queequeg? which, barred with various
1637 tints, seemed like the Andes' western slope, to show forth in one
1638 array, contrasting climates, zone by zone.
1639 
1640 "Grub, ho!" now cried the landlord, flinging open a door, and in we
1641 went to breakfast.
1642 
1643 They say that men who have seen the world, thereby become quite at
1644 ease in manner, quite self-possessed in company.  Not always, though:
1645 Ledyard, the great New England traveller, and Mungo Park, the Scotch
1646 one; of all men, they possessed the least assurance in the parlor.
1647 But perhaps the mere crossing of Siberia in a sledge drawn by dogs as
1648 Ledyard did, or the taking a long solitary walk on an empty stomach,
1649 in the negro heart of Africa, which was the sum of poor Mungo's
1650 performances--this kind of travel, I say, may not be the very best
1651 mode of attaining a high social polish.  Still, for the most part,
1652 that sort of thing is to be had anywhere.
1653 
1654 These reflections just here are occasioned by the circumstance that
1655 after we were all seated at the table, and I was preparing to hear
1656 some good stories about whaling; to my no small surprise, nearly
1657 every man maintained a profound silence.  And not only that, but they
1658 looked embarrassed.  Yes, here were a set of sea-dogs, many of whom
1659 without the slightest bashfulness had boarded great whales on the
1660 high seas--entire strangers to them--and duelled them dead without
1661 winking; and yet, here they sat at a social breakfast table--all of
1662 the same calling, all of kindred tastes--looking round as sheepishly
1663 at each other as though they had never been out of sight of some
1664 sheepfold among the Green Mountains.  A curious sight; these bashful
1665 bears, these timid warrior whalemen!
1666 
1667 But as for Queequeg--why, Queequeg sat there among them--at the head
1668 of the table, too, it so chanced; as cool as an icicle.  To be sure I
1669 cannot say much for his breeding.  His greatest admirer could not
1670 have cordially justified his bringing his harpoon into breakfast with
1671 him, and using it there without ceremony; reaching over the table
1672 with it, to the imminent jeopardy of many heads, and grappling the
1673 beefsteaks towards him.  But THAT was certainly very coolly done by
1674 him, and every one knows that in most people's estimation, to do
1675 anything coolly is to do it genteelly.
1676 
1677 We will not speak of all Queequeg's peculiarities here; how he
1678 eschewed coffee and hot rolls, and applied his undivided attention to
1679 beefsteaks, done rare.  Enough, that when breakfast was over he
1680 withdrew like the rest into the public room, lighted his
1681 tomahawk-pipe, and was sitting there quietly digesting and smoking
1682 with his inseparable hat on, when I sallied out for a stroll.
