1686 CHAPTER 6
1687 
1688 The Street.
1689 
1690 
1691 If I had been astonished at first catching a glimpse of so outlandish
1692 an individual as Queequeg circulating among the polite society of a
1693 civilized town, that astonishment soon departed upon taking my first
1694 daylight stroll through the streets of New Bedford.
1695 
1696 In thoroughfares nigh the docks, any considerable seaport will
1697 frequently offer to view the queerest looking nondescripts from
1698 foreign parts.  Even in Broadway and Chestnut streets, Mediterranean
1699 mariners will sometimes jostle the affrighted ladies.  Regent Street
1700 is not unknown to Lascars and Malays; and at Bombay, in the Apollo
1701 Green, live Yankees have often scared the natives.  But New Bedford
1702 beats all Water Street and Wapping.  In these last-mentioned haunts
1703 you see only sailors; but in New Bedford, actual cannibals stand
1704 chatting at street corners; savages outright; many of whom yet carry
1705 on their bones unholy flesh.  It makes a stranger stare.
1706 
1707 But, besides the Feegeeans, Tongatobooarrs, Erromanggoans,
1708 Pannangians, and Brighggians, and, besides the wild specimens of the
1709 whaling-craft which unheeded reel about the streets, you will see
1710 other sights still more curious, certainly more comical.  There
1711 weekly arrive in this town scores of green Vermonters and New
1712 Hampshire men, all athirst for gain and glory in the fishery.  They
1713 are mostly young, of stalwart frames; fellows who have felled
1714 forests, and now seek to drop the axe and snatch the whale-lance.
1715 Many are as green as the Green Mountains whence they came.  In some
1716 things you would think them but a few hours old.  Look there! that
1717 chap strutting round the corner.  He wears a beaver hat and
1718 swallow-tailed coat, girdled with a sailor-belt and sheath-knife.
1719 Here comes another with a sou'-wester and a bombazine cloak.
1720 
1721 No town-bred dandy will compare with a country-bred one--I mean a
1722 downright bumpkin dandy--a fellow that, in the dog-days, will mow his
1723 two acres in buckskin gloves for fear of tanning his hands.  Now when
1724 a country dandy like this takes it into his head to make a
1725 distinguished reputation, and joins the great whale-fishery, you
1726 should see the comical things he does upon reaching the seaport.  In
1727 bespeaking his sea-outfit, he orders bell-buttons to his waistcoats;
1728 straps to his canvas trowsers.  Ah, poor Hay-Seed! how bitterly will
1729 burst those straps in the first howling gale, when thou art driven,
1730 straps, buttons, and all, down the throat of the tempest.
1731 
1732 But think not that this famous town has only harpooneers, cannibals,
1733 and bumpkins to show her visitors.  Not at all.  Still New Bedford is
1734 a queer place.  Had it not been for us whalemen, that tract of land
1735 would this day perhaps have been in as howling condition as the coast
1736 of Labrador.  As it is, parts of her back country are enough to
1737 frighten one, they look so bony.  The town itself is perhaps the
1738 dearest place to live in, in all New England.  It is a land of oil,
1739 true enough: but not like Canaan; a land, also, of corn and wine.
1740 The streets do not run with milk; nor in the spring-time do they pave
1741 them with fresh eggs.  Yet, in spite of this, nowhere in all America
1742 will you find more patrician-like houses; parks and gardens more
1743 opulent, than in New Bedford.  Whence came they? how planted upon
1744 this once scraggy scoria of a country?
1745 
1746 Go and gaze upon the iron emblematical harpoons round yonder lofty
1747 mansion, and your question will be answered.  Yes; all these brave
1748 houses and flowery gardens came from the Atlantic, Pacific, and
1749 Indian oceans.  One and all, they were harpooned and dragged up
1750 hither from the bottom of the sea.  Can Herr Alexander perform a feat
1751 like that?
1752 
1753 In New Bedford, fathers, they say, give whales for dowers to their
1754 daughters, and portion off their nieces with a few porpoises a-piece.
1755 You must go to New Bedford to see a brilliant wedding; for, they
1756 say, they have reservoirs of oil in every house, and every night
1757 recklessly burn their lengths in spermaceti candles.
1758 
1759 In summer time, the town is sweet to see; full of fine maples--long
1760 avenues of green and gold.  And in August, high in air, the beautiful
1761 and bountiful horse-chestnuts, candelabra-wise, proffer the passer-by
1762 their tapering upright cones of congregated blossoms.  So omnipotent
1763 is art; which in many a district of New Bedford has superinduced
1764 bright terraces of flowers upon the barren refuse rocks thrown aside
1765 at creation's final day.
1766 
1767 And the women of New Bedford, they bloom like their own red roses.
1768 But roses only bloom in summer; whereas the fine carnation of their
1769 cheeks is perennial as sunlight in the seventh heavens.  Elsewhere
1770 match that bloom of theirs, ye cannot, save in Salem, where they tell
1771 me the young girls breathe such musk, their sailor sweethearts smell
1772 them miles off shore, as though they were drawing nigh the odorous
1773 Moluccas instead of the Puritanic sands.
