1845 Shaking off the sleet from my ice-glazed hat and jacket, I seated
1846 myself near the door, and turning sideways was surprised to see
1847 Queequeg near me.  Affected by the solemnity of the scene, there was
1848 a wondering gaze of incredulous curiosity in his countenance.  This
1849 savage was the only person present who seemed to notice my entrance;
1850 because he was the only one who could not read, and, therefore, was
1851 not reading those frigid inscriptions on the wall.  Whether any of
1852 the relatives of the seamen whose names appeared there were now among
1853 the congregation, I knew not; but so many are the unrecorded
1854 accidents in the fishery, and so plainly did several women present
1855 wear the countenance if not the trappings of some unceasing grief,
1856 that I feel sure that here before me were assembled those, in whose
1857 unhealing hearts the sight of those bleak tablets sympathetically
1858 caused the old wounds to bleed afresh.
1859 
1860 Oh! ye whose dead lie buried beneath the green grass; who standing
1861 among flowers can say--here, HERE lies my beloved; ye know not the
1862 desolation that broods in bosoms like these.  What bitter blanks in
1863 those black-bordered marbles which cover no ashes!  What despair in
1864 those immovable inscriptions!  What deadly voids and unbidden
1865 infidelities in the lines that seem to gnaw upon all Faith, and
1866 refuse resurrections to the beings who have placelessly perished
1867 without a grave.  As well might those tablets stand in the cave of
1868 Elephanta as here.
1869 
1870 In what census of living creatures, the dead of mankind are included;
1871 why it is that a universal proverb says of them, that they tell no
1872 tales, though containing more secrets than the Goodwin Sands; how it
1873 is that to his name who yesterday departed for the other world, we
1874 prefix so significant and infidel a word, and yet do not thus entitle
1875 him, if he but embarks for the remotest Indies of this living earth;
1876 why the Life Insurance Companies pay death-forfeitures upon
1877 immortals; in what eternal, unstirring paralysis, and deadly,
1878 hopeless trance, yet lies antique Adam who died sixty round centuries
1879 ago; how it is that we still refuse to be comforted for those who we
1880 nevertheless maintain are dwelling in unspeakable bliss; why all the
1881 living so strive to hush all the dead; wherefore but the rumor of a
1882 knocking in a tomb will terrify a whole city.  All these things are
1883 not without their meanings.
1884 
1885 But Faith, like a jackal, feeds among the tombs, and even from these
1886 dead doubts she gathers her most vital hope.
1887 
1888 It needs scarcely to be told, with what feelings, on the eve of a
1889 Nantucket voyage, I regarded those marble tablets, and by the murky
1890 light of that darkened, doleful day read the fate of the whalemen who
1891 had gone before me.  Yes, Ishmael, the same fate may be thine.  But
1892 somehow I grew merry again.  Delightful inducements to embark, fine
1893 chance for promotion, it seems--aye, a stove boat will make me an
1894 immortal by brevet.  Yes, there is death in this business of
1895 whaling--a speechlessly quick chaotic bundling of a man into
1896 Eternity.  But what then?  Methinks we have hugely mistaken this
1897 matter of Life and Death.  Methinks that what they call my shadow
1898 here on earth is my true substance.  Methinks that in looking at
1899 things spiritual, we are too much like oysters observing the sun
1900 through the water, and thinking that thick water the thinnest of air.
1901 Methinks my body is but the lees of my better being.  In fact take
1902 my body who will, take it I say, it is not me.  And therefore three
1903 cheers for Nantucket; and come a stove boat and stove body when they
1904 will, for stave my soul, Jove himself cannot.
