1909 
1910 The Pulpit.
1911 
1912 
1913 I had not been seated very long ere a man of a certain venerable
1914 robustness entered; immediately as the storm-pelted door flew back
1915 upon admitting him, a quick regardful eyeing of him by all the
1916 congregation, sufficiently attested that this fine old man was the
1917 chaplain.  Yes, it was the famous Father Mapple, so called by the
1918 whalemen, among whom he was a very great favourite.  He had been a
1919 sailor and a harpooneer in his youth, but for many years past had
1920 dedicated his life to the ministry.  At the time I now write of,
1921 Father Mapple was in the hardy winter of a healthy old age; that sort
1922 of old age which seems merging into a second flowering youth, for
1923 among all the fissures of his wrinkles, there shone certain mild
1924 gleams of a newly developing bloom--the spring verdure peeping forth
1925 even beneath February's snow.  No one having previously heard his
1926 history, could for the first time behold Father Mapple without the
1927 utmost interest, because there were certain engrafted clerical
1928 peculiarities about him, imputable to that adventurous maritime life
1929 he had led.  When he entered I observed that he carried no umbrella,
1930 and certainly had not come in his carriage, for his tarpaulin hat ran
1931 down with melting sleet, and his great pilot cloth jacket seemed
1932 almost to drag him to the floor with the weight of the water it had
1933 absorbed.  However, hat and coat and overshoes were one by one
1934 removed, and hung up in a little space in an adjacent corner; when,
1935 arrayed in a decent suit, he quietly approached the pulpit.
1936 
1937 Like most old fashioned pulpits, it was a very lofty one, and since a
1938 regular stairs to such a height would, by its long angle with the
1939 floor, seriously contract the already small area of the chapel, the
1940 architect, it seemed, had acted upon the hint of Father Mapple, and
1941 finished the pulpit without a stairs, substituting a perpendicular
1942 side ladder, like those used in mounting a ship from a boat at sea.
1943 The wife of a whaling captain had provided the chapel with a handsome
1944 pair of red worsted man-ropes for this ladder, which, being itself
1945 nicely headed, and stained with a mahogany colour, the whole
1946 contrivance, considering what manner of chapel it was, seemed by no
1947 means in bad taste.  Halting for an instant at the foot of the
1948 ladder, and with both hands grasping the ornamental knobs of the
1949 man-ropes, Father Mapple cast a look upwards, and then with a truly
1950 sailor-like but still reverential dexterity, hand over hand, mounted
1951 the steps as if ascending the main-top of his vessel.
1952 
1953 The perpendicular parts of this side ladder, as is usually the case
1954 with swinging ones, were of cloth-covered rope, only the rounds were
1955 of wood, so that at every step there was a joint.  At my first
1956 glimpse of the pulpit, it had not escaped me that however convenient
1957 for a ship, these joints in the present instance seemed unnecessary.
1958 For I was not prepared to see Father Mapple after gaining the height,
1959 slowly turn round, and stooping over the pulpit, deliberately drag up
1960 the ladder step by step, till the whole was deposited within, leaving
1961 him impregnable in his little Quebec.
1962 
1963 I pondered some time without fully comprehending the reason for this.
1964 Father Mapple enjoyed such a wide reputation for sincerity and
1965 sanctity, that I could not suspect him of courting notoriety by any
1966 mere tricks of the stage.  No, thought I, there must be some sober
1967 reason for this thing; furthermore, it must symbolize something
1968 unseen.  Can it be, then, that by that act of physical isolation, he
1969 signifies his spiritual withdrawal for the time, from all outward
1970 worldly ties and connexions?  Yes, for replenished with the meat and
1971 wine of the word, to the faithful man of God, this pulpit, I see, is
1972 a self-containing stronghold--a lofty Ehrenbreitstein, with a
1973 perennial well of water within the walls.
1974 
1975 But the side ladder was not the only strange feature of the place,
