2355 CHAPTER 10
2356 
2357 A Bosom Friend.
2358 
2359 
2360 Returning to the Spouter-Inn from the Chapel, I found Queequeg there
2361 quite alone; he having left the Chapel before the benediction some
2362 time.  He was sitting on a bench before the fire, with his feet on
2363 the stove hearth, and in one hand was holding close up to his face
2364 that little negro idol of his; peering hard into its face, and with a
2365 jack-knife gently whittling away at its nose, meanwhile humming to
2366 himself in his heathenish way.
2367 
2368 But being now interrupted, he put up the image; and pretty soon,
2369 going to the table, took up a large book there, and placing it on his
2370 lap began counting the pages with deliberate regularity; at every
2371 fiftieth page--as I fancied--stopping a moment, looking vacantly
2372 around him, and giving utterance to a long-drawn gurgling whistle of
2373 astonishment.  He would then begin again at the next fifty; seeming
2374 to commence at number one each time, as though he could not count
2375 more than fifty, and it was only by such a large number of fifties
2376 being found together, that his astonishment at the multitude of pages
2377 was excited.
2378 
2379 With much interest I sat watching him.  Savage though he was, and
2380 hideously marred about the face--at least to my taste--his
2381 countenance yet had a something in it which was by no means
2382 disagreeable.  You cannot hide the soul.  Through all his unearthly
2383 tattooings, I thought I saw the traces of a simple honest heart; and
2384 in his large, deep eyes, fiery black and bold, there seemed tokens of
2385 a spirit that would dare a thousand devils.  And besides all this,
2386 there was a certain lofty bearing about the Pagan, which even his
2387 uncouthness could not altogether maim.  He looked like a man who had
2388 never cringed and never had had a creditor.  Whether it was, too,
2389 that his head being shaved, his forehead was drawn out in freer and
2390 brighter relief, and looked more expansive than it otherwise would,
2391 this I will not venture to decide; but certain it was his head was
2392 phrenologically an excellent one.  It may seem ridiculous, but it
2393 reminded me of General Washington's head, as seen in the popular
2394 busts of him.  It had the same long regularly graded retreating slope
2395 from above the brows, which were likewise very projecting, like two
2396 long promontories thickly wooded on top.  Queequeg was George
2397 Washington cannibalistically developed.
2398 
2399 Whilst I was thus closely scanning him, half-pretending meanwhile to
2400 be looking out at the storm from the casement, he never heeded my
2401 presence, never troubled himself with so much as a single glance; but
2402 appeared wholly occupied with counting the pages of the marvellous
2403 book.  Considering how sociably we had been sleeping together the
2404 night previous, and especially considering the affectionate arm I had
2405 found thrown over me upon waking in the morning, I thought this
2406 indifference of his very strange.  But savages are strange beings; at
2407 times you do not know exactly how to take them.  At first they are
2408 overawing; their calm self-collectedness of simplicity seems a
2409 Socratic wisdom.  I had noticed also that Queequeg never consorted at
2410 all, or but very little, with the other seamen in the inn.  He made
2411 no advances whatever; appeared to have no desire to enlarge the
2412 circle of his acquaintances.  All this struck me as mighty singular;
2413 yet, upon second thoughts, there was something almost sublime in it.
2414 Here was a man some twenty thousand miles from home, by the way of
2415 Cape Horn, that is--which was the only way he could get there--thrown
2416 among people as strange to him as though he were in the planet
2417 Jupiter; and yet he seemed entirely at his ease; preserving the
2418 utmost serenity; content with his own companionship; always equal to
2419 himself.  Surely this was a touch of fine philosophy; though no doubt
2420 he had never heard there was such a thing as that.  But, perhaps, to
2421 be true philosophers, we mortals should not be conscious of so living
2422 or so striving.  So soon as I hear that such or such a man gives
2423 himself out for a philosopher, I conclude that, like the dyspeptic
2424 old woman, he must have "broken his digester."
2425 
2426 As I sat there in that now lonely room; the fire burning low, in that
2427 mild stage when, after its first intensity has warmed the air, it
2428 then only glows to be looked at; the evening shades and phantoms
2429 gathering round the casements, and peering in upon us silent,
2430 solitary twain; the storm booming without in solemn swells; I began
2431 to be sensible of strange feelings.  I felt a melting in me.  No more
2432 my splintered heart and maddened hand were turned against the wolfish
2433 world.  This soothing savage had redeemed it.  There he sat, his very
2434 indifference speaking a nature in which there lurked no civilized
2435 hypocrisies and bland deceits.  Wild he was; a very sight of sights
2436 to see; yet I began to feel myself mysteriously drawn towards him.
2437 And those same things that would have repelled most others, they were
2438 the very magnets that thus drew me.  I'll try a pagan friend, thought
2439 I, since Christian kindness has proved but hollow courtesy.  I drew
2440 my bench near him, and made some friendly signs and hints, doing my
2441 best to talk with him meanwhile.  At first he little noticed these
2442 advances; but presently, upon my referring to his last night's
2443 hospitalities, he made out to ask me whether we were again to be
2444 bedfellows.  I told him yes; whereat I thought he looked pleased,
2445 perhaps a little complimented.
2446 
2447 We then turned over the book together, and I endeavored to explain to
2448 him the purpose of the printing, and the meaning of the few pictures
2449 that were in it.  Thus I soon engaged his interest; and from that we
2450 went to jabbering the best we could about the various outer sights to
2451 be seen in this famous town.  Soon I proposed a social smoke; and,
2452 producing his pouch and tomahawk, he quietly offered me a puff.  And
2453 then we sat exchanging puffs from that wild pipe of his, and keeping
2454 it regularly passing between us.
2455 
2456 If there yet lurked any ice of indifference towards me in the Pagan's
2457 breast, this pleasant, genial smoke we had, soon thawed it out, and
2458 left us cronies.  He seemed to take to me quite as naturally and
2459 unbiddenly as I to him; and when our smoke was over, he pressed his
2460 forehead against mine, clasped me round the waist, and said that
2461 henceforth we were married; meaning, in his country's phrase, that we
2462 were bosom friends; he would gladly die for me, if need should be.
2463 In a countryman, this sudden flame of friendship would have seemed
2464 far too premature, a thing to be much distrusted; but in this simple
2465 savage those old rules would not apply.
2466 
2467 After supper, and another social chat and smoke, we went to our room
2468 together.  He made me a present of his embalmed head; took out his
2469 enormous tobacco wallet, and groping under the tobacco, drew out some
2470 thirty dollars in silver; then spreading them on the table, and
2471 mechanically dividing them into two equal portions, pushed one of
2472 them towards me, and said it was mine.  I was going to remonstrate;
2473 but he silenced me by pouring them into my trowsers' pockets.  I let
2474 them stay.  He then went about his evening prayers, took out his
2475 idol, and removed the paper fireboard.  By certain signs and
2476 symptoms, I thought he seemed anxious for me to join him; but well
2477 knowing what was to follow, I deliberated a moment whether, in case
2478 he invited me, I would comply or otherwise.
2479 
2480 I was a good Christian; born and bred in the bosom of the infallible
2481 Presbyterian Church.  How then could I unite with this wild idolator
2482 in worshipping his piece of wood?  But what is worship? thought I.
2483 Do you suppose now, Ishmael, that the magnanimous God of heaven and
2484 earth--pagans and all included--can possibly be jealous of an
2485 insignificant bit of black wood?  Impossible!  But what is
2486 worship?--to do the will of God--THAT is worship.  And what is the
2487 will of God?--to do to my fellow man what I would have my fellow man
2488 to do to me--THAT is the will of God.  Now, Queequeg is my fellow
2489 man.  And what do I wish that this Queequeg would do to me?  Why,
2490 unite with me in my particular Presbyterian form of worship.
2491 Consequently, I must then unite with him in his; ergo, I must turn
2492 idolator.  So I kindled the shavings; helped prop up the innocent
2493 little idol; offered him burnt biscuit with Queequeg; salamed before
2494 him twice or thrice; kissed his nose; and that done, we undressed and
2495 went to bed, at peace with our own consciences and all the world.
2496 But we did not go to sleep without some little chat.
2497 
2498 How it is I know not; but there is no place like a bed for
2499 confidential disclosures between friends.  Man and wife, they say,
2500 there open the very bottom of their souls to each other; and some old
2501 couples often lie and chat over old times till nearly morning.  Thus,
2502 then, in our hearts' honeymoon, lay I and Queequeg--a cosy, loving
2503 pair.
