2508 
2509 Nightgown.
2510 
2511 
2512 We had lain thus in bed, chatting and napping at short intervals, and
2513 Queequeg now and then affectionately throwing his brown tattooed legs
2514 over mine, and then drawing them back; so entirely sociable and free
2515 and easy were we; when, at last, by reason of our confabulations,
2516 what little nappishness remained in us altogether departed, and we
2517 felt like getting up again, though day-break was yet some way down
2518 the future.
2519 
2520 Yes, we became very wakeful; so much so that our recumbent position
2521 began to grow wearisome, and by little and little we found ourselves
2522 sitting up; the clothes well tucked around us, leaning against the
2523 head-board with our four knees drawn up close together, and our two
2524 noses bending over them, as if our kneepans were warming-pans.  We
2525 felt very nice and snug, the more so since it was so chilly out of
2526 doors; indeed out of bed-clothes too, seeing that there was no fire
2527 in the room.  The more so, I say, because truly to enjoy bodily
2528 warmth, some small part of you must be cold, for there is no quality
2529 in this world that is not what it is merely by contrast.  Nothing
2530 exists in itself.  If you flatter yourself that you are all over
2531 comfortable, and have been so a long time, then you cannot be said to
2532 be comfortable any more.  But if, like Queequeg and me in the bed,
2533 the tip of your nose or the crown of your head be slightly chilled,
2534 why then, indeed, in the general consciousness you feel most
2535 delightfully and unmistakably warm.  For this reason a sleeping
2536 apartment should never be furnished with a fire, which is one of the
2537 luxurious discomforts of the rich.  For the height of this sort of
2538 deliciousness is to have nothing but the blanket between you and
2539 your snugness and the cold of the outer air.  Then there you lie like
2540 the one warm spark in the heart of an arctic crystal.
2541 
2542 We had been sitting in this crouching manner for some time, when all
2543 at once I thought I would open my eyes; for when between sheets,
2544 whether by day or by night, and whether asleep or awake, I have a way
2545 of always keeping my eyes shut, in order the more to concentrate the
2546 snugness of being in bed.  Because no man can ever feel his own
2547 identity aright except his eyes be closed; as if darkness were
2548 indeed the proper element of our essences, though light be more
2549 congenial to our clayey part.  Upon opening my eyes then, and coming
2550 out of my own pleasant and self-created darkness into the imposed and
2551 coarse outer gloom of the unilluminated twelve-o'clock-at-night, I
2552 experienced a disagreeable revulsion.  Nor did I at all object to the
2553 hint from Queequeg that perhaps it were best to strike a light,
2554 seeing that we were so wide awake; and besides he felt a strong
2555 desire to have a few quiet puffs from his Tomahawk.  Be it said, that
2556 though I had felt such a strong repugnance to his smoking in the bed
2557 the night before, yet see how elastic our stiff prejudices grow when
2558 love once comes to bend them.  For now I liked nothing better than
2559 to have Queequeg smoking by me, even in bed, because he seemed to be
2560 full of such serene household joy then.  I no more felt unduly
2561 concerned for the landlord's policy of insurance.  I was only alive
2562 to the condensed confidential comfortableness of sharing a pipe and a
2563 blanket with a real friend.  With our shaggy jackets drawn about our
2564 shoulders, we now passed the Tomahawk from one to the other, till
2565 slowly there grew over us a blue hanging tester of smoke, illuminated
2566 by the flame of the new-lit lamp.
2567 
2568 Whether it was that this undulating tester rolled the savage away to
2569 far distant scenes, I know not, but he now spoke of his native
2570 island; and, eager to hear his history, I begged him to go on and
2571 tell it.  He gladly complied.  Though at the time I but ill
2572 comprehended not a few of his words, yet subsequent disclosures, when
2573 I had become more familiar with his broken phraseology, now enable me
2574 to present the whole story such as it may prove in the mere skeleton
2575 I give.
