2581 Biographical.
2582 
2583 
2584 Queequeg was a native of Rokovoko, an island far away to the West
2585 and South.  It is not down in any map; true places never are.
2586 
2587 When a new-hatched savage running wild about his native woodlands in
2588 a grass clout, followed by the nibbling goats, as if he were a green
2589 sapling; even then, in Queequeg's ambitious soul, lurked a strong
2590 desire to see something more of Christendom than a specimen whaler or
2591 two.  His father was a High Chief, a King; his uncle a High Priest;
2592 and on the maternal side he boasted aunts who were the wives of
2593 unconquerable warriors.  There was excellent blood in his
2594 veins--royal stuff; though sadly vitiated, I fear, by the cannibal
2595 propensity he nourished in his untutored youth.
2596 
2597 A Sag Harbor ship visited his father's bay, and Queequeg sought a
2598 passage to Christian lands.  But the ship, having her full complement
2599 of seamen, spurned his suit; and not all the King his father's
2600 influence could prevail.  But Queequeg vowed a vow.  Alone in his
2601 canoe, he paddled off to a distant strait, which he knew the ship
2602 must pass through when she quitted the island.  On one side was a
2603 coral reef; on the other a low tongue of land, covered with mangrove
2604 thickets that grew out into the water.  Hiding his canoe, still
2605 afloat, among these thickets, with its prow seaward, he sat down in
2606 the stern, paddle low in hand; and when the ship was gliding by, like
2607 a flash he darted out; gained her side; with one backward dash of his
2608 foot capsized and sank his canoe; climbed up the chains; and throwing
2609 himself at full length upon the deck, grappled a ring-bolt there, and
2610 swore not to let it go, though hacked in pieces.
2611 
2612 In vain the captain threatened to throw him overboard; suspended a
2613 cutlass over his naked wrists; Queequeg was the son of a King, and
2614 Queequeg budged not.  Struck by his desperate dauntlessness, and his
2615 wild desire to visit Christendom, the captain at last relented, and
2616 told him he might make himself at home.  But this fine young
2617 savage--this sea Prince of Wales, never saw the Captain's cabin.
2618 They put him down among the sailors, and made a whaleman of him.  But
2619 like Czar Peter content to toil in the shipyards of foreign cities,
2620 Queequeg disdained no seeming ignominy, if thereby he might happily
2621 gain the power of enlightening his untutored countrymen.  For at
2622 bottom--so he told me--he was actuated by a profound desire to learn
2623 among the Christians, the arts whereby to make his people still
2624 happier than they were; and more than that, still better than they
2625 were.  But, alas! the practices of whalemen soon convinced him that
2626 even Christians could be both miserable and wicked; infinitely more
2627 so, than all his father's heathens.  Arrived at last in old Sag
2628 Harbor; and seeing what the sailors did there; and then going on to
2629 Nantucket, and seeing how they spent their wages in that place also,
2630 poor Queequeg gave it up for lost.  Thought he, it's a wicked world
2631 in all meridians; I'll die a pagan.
2632 
2633 And thus an old idolator at heart, he yet lived among these
2634 Christians, wore their clothes, and tried to talk their gibberish.
2635 Hence the queer ways about him, though now some time from home.
2636 
2637 By hints, I asked him whether he did not propose going back, and
2638 having a coronation; since he might now consider his father dead and
2639 gone, he being very old and feeble at the last accounts.  He answered
2640 no, not yet; and added that he was fearful Christianity, or rather
2641 Christians, had unfitted him for ascending the pure and undefiled
2642 throne of thirty pagan Kings before him.  But by and by, he said, he
2643 would return,--as soon as he felt himself baptized again.  For the
2644 nonce, however, he proposed to sail about, and sow his wild oats in
2645 all four oceans.  They had made a harpooneer of him, and that barbed
2646 iron was in lieu of a sceptre now.
2647 
2648 I asked him what might be his immediate purpose, touching his future
2649 movements.  He answered, to go to sea again, in his old vocation.
2650 Upon this, I told him that whaling was my own design, and informed
