2848 
2849 Nantucket!  Take out your map and look at it.  See what a real corner
2850 of the world it occupies; how it stands there, away off shore, more
2851 lonely than the Eddystone lighthouse.  Look at it--a mere hillock,
2852 and elbow of sand; all beach, without a background.  There is more
2853 sand there than you would use in twenty years as a substitute for
2854 blotting paper.  Some gamesome wights will tell you that they have to
2855 plant weeds there, they don't grow naturally; that they import Canada
2856 thistles; that they have to send beyond seas for a spile to stop a
2857 leak in an oil cask; that pieces of wood in Nantucket are carried
2858 about like bits of the true cross in Rome; that people there plant
2859 toadstools before their houses, to get under the shade in summer
2860 time; that one blade of grass makes an oasis, three blades in a day's
2861 walk a prairie; that they wear quicksand shoes, something like
2862 Laplander snow-shoes; that they are so shut up, belted about, every
2863 way inclosed, surrounded, and made an utter island of by the ocean,
2864 that to their very chairs and tables small clams will sometimes be
2865 found adhering, as to the backs of sea turtles.  But these
2866 extravaganzas only show that Nantucket is no Illinois.
2867 
2868 Look now at the wondrous traditional story of how this island was
2869 settled by the red-men.  Thus goes the legend.  In olden times an
2870 eagle swooped down upon the New England coast, and carried off an
2871 infant Indian in his talons.  With loud lament the parents saw their
2872 child borne out of sight over the wide waters.  They resolved to
2873 follow in the same direction.  Setting out in their canoes, after a
2874 perilous passage they discovered the island, and there they found an
2875 empty ivory casket,--the poor little Indian's skeleton.
2876 
2877 What wonder, then, that these Nantucketers, born on a beach, should
2878 take to the sea for a livelihood!  They first caught crabs and
2879 quohogs in the sand; grown bolder, they waded out with nets for
2880 mackerel; more experienced, they pushed off in boats and captured
2881 cod; and at last, launching a navy of great ships on the sea,
2882 explored this watery world; put an incessant belt of
2883 circumnavigations round it; peeped in at Behring's Straits; and in
2884 all seasons and all oceans declared everlasting war with the
2885 mightiest animated mass that has survived the flood; most monstrous
2886 and most mountainous!  That Himmalehan, salt-sea Mastodon, clothed
2887 with such portentousness of unconscious power, that his very panics
2888 are more to be dreaded than his most fearless and malicious assaults!
2889 
2890 And thus have these naked Nantucketers, these sea hermits, issuing
2891 from their ant-hill in the sea, overrun and conquered the watery
2892 world like so many Alexanders; parcelling out among them the
2893 Atlantic, Pacific, and Indian oceans, as the three pirate powers did
2894 Poland.  Let America add Mexico to Texas, and pile Cuba upon Canada;
2895 let the English overswarm all India, and hang out their blazing
2896 banner from the sun; two thirds of this terraqueous globe are the
2897 Nantucketer's.  For the sea is his; he owns it, as Emperors own
2898 empires; other seamen having but a right of way through it.  Merchant
2899 ships are but extension bridges; armed ones but floating forts; even
2900 pirates and privateers, though following the sea as highwaymen the
2901 road, they but plunder other ships, other fragments of the land like
2902 themselves, without seeking to draw their living from the bottomless
2903 deep itself.  The Nantucketer, he alone resides and riots on the sea;
2904 he alone, in Bible language, goes down to it in ships; to and fro
2905 ploughing it as his own special plantation.  THERE is his home; THERE
2906 lies his business, which a Noah's flood would not interrupt, though
2907 it overwhelmed all the millions in China.  He lives on the sea, as
2908 prairie cocks in the prairie; he hides among the waves, he climbs
2909 them as chamois hunters climb the Alps.  For years he knows not the
2910 land; so that when he comes to it at last, it smells like another
2911 world, more strangely than the moon would to an Earthsman.  With the
2912 landless gull, that at sunset folds her wings and is rocked to sleep
2913 between billows; so at nightfall, the Nantucketer, out of sight of
2914 land, furls his sails, and lays him to his rest, while under his very
2915 pillow rush herds of walruses and whales.
