2921 Chowder.
2922 
2923 
2924 It was quite late in the evening when the little Moss came snugly to
2925 anchor, and Queequeg and I went ashore; so we could attend to no
2926 business that day, at least none but a supper and a bed.  The
2927 landlord of the Spouter-Inn had recommended us to his cousin Hosea
2928 Hussey of the Try Pots, whom he asserted to be the proprietor of one
2929 of the best kept hotels in all Nantucket, and moreover he had assured
2930 us that Cousin Hosea, as he called him, was famous for his chowders.
2931 In short, he plainly hinted that we could not possibly do better than
2932 try pot-luck at the Try Pots.  But the directions he had given us
2933 about keeping a yellow warehouse on our starboard hand till we opened
2934 a white church to the larboard, and then keeping that on the larboard
2935 hand till we made a corner three points to the starboard, and that
2936 done, then ask the first man we met where the place was: these
2937 crooked directions of his very much puzzled us at first, especially
2938 as, at the outset, Queequeg insisted that the yellow warehouse--our
2939 first point of departure--must be left on the larboard hand, whereas
2940 I had understood Peter Coffin to say it was on the starboard.
2941 However, by dint of beating about a little in the dark, and now and
2942 then knocking up a peaceable inhabitant to inquire the way, we at
2943 last came to something which there was no mistaking.
2944 
2945 Two enormous wooden pots painted black, and suspended by asses' ears,
2946 swung from the cross-trees of an old top-mast, planted in front of an
2947 old doorway.  The horns of the cross-trees were sawed off on the
2948 other side, so that this old top-mast looked not a little like a
2949 gallows.  Perhaps I was over sensitive to such impressions at the
2950 time, but I could not help staring at this gallows with a vague
2951 misgiving.  A sort of crick was in my neck as I gazed up to the two
2952 remaining horns; yes, TWO of them, one for Queequeg, and one for me.
2953 It's ominous, thinks I.  A Coffin my Innkeeper upon landing in my
2954 first whaling port; tombstones staring at me in the whalemen's
2955 chapel; and here a gallows! and a pair of prodigious black pots too!
2956 Are these last throwing out oblique hints touching Tophet?
2957 
2958 I was called from these reflections by the sight of a freckled woman
2959 with yellow hair and a yellow gown, standing in the porch of the inn,
2960 under a dull red lamp swinging there, that looked much like an
