3048 The Ship.
3049 
3050 
3051 In bed we concocted our plans for the morrow.  But to my surprise and
3052 no small concern, Queequeg now gave me to understand, that he had
3053 been diligently consulting Yojo--the name of his black little
3054 god--and Yojo had told him two or three times over, and strongly
3055 insisted upon it everyway, that instead of our going together among
3056 the whaling-fleet in harbor, and in concert selecting our craft;
3057 instead of this, I say, Yojo earnestly enjoined that the selection of
3058 the ship should rest wholly with me, inasmuch as Yojo purposed
3059 befriending us; and, in order to do so, had already pitched upon a
3060 vessel, which, if left to myself, I, Ishmael, should infallibly light
3061 upon, for all the world as though it had turned out by chance; and in
3062 that vessel I must immediately ship myself, for the present
3063 irrespective of Queequeg.
3064 
3065 I have forgotten to mention that, in many things, Queequeg placed
3066 great confidence in the excellence of Yojo's judgment and surprising
3067 forecast of things; and cherished Yojo with considerable esteem, as a
3068 rather good sort of god, who perhaps meant well enough upon the
3069 whole, but in all cases did not succeed in his benevolent designs.
3070 
3071 Now, this plan of Queequeg's, or rather Yojo's, touching the
3072 selection of our craft; I did not like that plan at all.  I had not a
3073 little relied upon Queequeg's sagacity to point out the whaler best
3074 fitted to carry us and our fortunes securely.  But as all my
3075 remonstrances produced no effect upon Queequeg, I was obliged to
3076 acquiesce; and accordingly prepared to set about this business with a
3077 determined rushing sort of energy and vigor, that should quickly
3078 settle that trifling little affair.  Next morning early, leaving
3079 Queequeg shut up with Yojo in our little bedroom--for it seemed that
3080 it was some sort of Lent or Ramadan, or day of fasting, humiliation,
3081 and prayer with Queequeg and Yojo that day; HOW it was I never could
3082 find out, for, though I applied myself to it several times, I never
3083 could master his liturgies and XXXIX Articles--leaving Queequeg,
3084 then, fasting on his tomahawk pipe, and Yojo warming himself at his
3085 sacrificial fire of shavings, I sallied out among the shipping.
3086 After much prolonged sauntering and many random inquiries, I learnt
3087 that there were three ships up for three-years' voyages--The
3088 Devil-dam, the Tit-bit, and the Pequod.  DEVIL-DAM, I do not know
3089 the origin of; TIT-BIT is obvious; PEQUOD, you will no doubt
3090 remember, was the name of a celebrated tribe of Massachusetts
3091 Indians; now extinct as the ancient Medes.  I peered and pryed about
3092 the Devil-dam; from her, hopped over to the Tit-bit; and finally,
3093 going on board the Pequod, looked around her for a moment, and then
3094 decided that this was the very ship for us.
3095 
3096 You may have seen many a quaint craft in your day, for aught I
3097 know;--square-toed luggers; mountainous Japanese junks; butter-box
3098 galliots, and what not; but take my word for it, you never saw such a
3099 rare old craft as this same rare old Pequod.  She was a ship of the
3100 old school, rather small if anything; with an old-fashioned
3101 claw-footed look about her.  Long seasoned and weather-stained in the
3102 typhoons and calms of all four oceans, her old hull's complexion was
3103 darkened like a French grenadier's, who has alike fought in Egypt and
3104 Siberia.  Her venerable bows looked bearded.  Her masts--cut
3105 somewhere on the coast of Japan, where her original ones were lost
3106 overboard in a gale--her masts stood stiffly up like the spines of
3107 the three old kings of Cologne.  Her ancient decks were worn and
3108 wrinkled, like the pilgrim-worshipped flag-stone in Canterbury
3109 Cathedral where Becket bled.  But to all these her old antiquities,
3110 were added new and marvellous features, pertaining to the wild
3111 business that for more than half a century she had followed.  Old
3112 Captain Peleg, many years her chief-mate, before he commanded another
3113 vessel of his own, and now a retired seaman, and one of the principal
3114 owners of the Pequod,--this old Peleg, during the term of his
3115 chief-mateship, had built upon her original grotesqueness, and inlaid
3116 it, all over, with a quaintness both of material and device,
3117 unmatched by anything except it be Thorkill-Hake's carved buckler or
3118 bedstead.  She was apparelled like any barbaric Ethiopian emperor,
3119 his neck heavy with pendants of polished ivory.  She was a thing of
3120 trophies.  A cannibal of a craft, tricking herself forth in the
3121 chased bones of her enemies.  All round, her unpanelled, open
3122 bulwarks were garnished like one continuous jaw, with the long sharp
3123 teeth of the sperm whale, inserted there for pins, to fasten her old
3124 hempen thews and tendons to.  Those thews ran not through base blocks
3125 of land wood, but deftly travelled over sheaves of sea-ivory.
3126 Scorning a turnstile wheel at her reverend helm, she sported there a
3127 tiller; and that tiller was in one mass, curiously carved from the
3128 long narrow lower jaw of her hereditary foe.  The helmsman who
3129 steered by that tiller in a tempest, felt like the Tartar, when he
3130 holds back his fiery steed by clutching its jaw.  A noble craft, but
3131 somehow a most melancholy!  All noble things are touched with that.
3132 
3133 Now when I looked about the quarter-deck, for some one having
3134 authority, in order to propose myself as a candidate for the voyage,
