3300 approved state stocks bringing in good interest.
3301 
3302 Now, Bildad, like Peleg, and indeed many other Nantucketers, was a
3303 Quaker, the island having been originally settled by that sect; and
3304 to this day its inhabitants in general retain in an uncommon measure
3305 the peculiarities of the Quaker, only variously and anomalously
3306 modified by things altogether alien and heterogeneous.  For some of
3307 these same Quakers are the most sanguinary of all sailors and
3308 whale-hunters.  They are fighting Quakers; they are Quakers with a
3309 vengeance.
3310 
3311 So that there are instances among them of men, who, named with
3312 Scripture names--a singularly common fashion on the island--and in
3313 childhood naturally imbibing the stately dramatic thee and thou of
3314 the Quaker idiom; still, from the audacious, daring, and boundless
3315 adventure of their subsequent lives, strangely blend with these
3316 unoutgrown peculiarities, a thousand bold dashes of character, not
3317 unworthy a Scandinavian sea-king, or a poetical Pagan Roman.  And
3318 when these things unite in a man of greatly superior natural force,
3319 with a globular brain and a ponderous heart; who has also by the
3320 stillness and seclusion of many long night-watches in the remotest
3321 waters, and beneath constellations never seen here at the north, been
3322 led to think untraditionally and independently; receiving all
3323 nature's sweet or savage impressions fresh from her own virgin
3324 voluntary and confiding breast, and thereby chiefly, but with some
3325 help from accidental advantages, to learn a bold and nervous lofty
3326 language--that man makes one in a whole nation's census--a mighty
3327 pageant creature, formed for noble tragedies.  Nor will it at all
3328 detract from him, dramatically regarded, if either by birth or other
3329 circumstances, he have what seems a half wilful overruling morbidness
3330 at the bottom of his nature.  For all men tragically great are made
3331 so through a certain morbidness.  Be sure of this, O young ambition,
3332 all mortal greatness is but disease.  But, as yet we have not to do
3333 with such an one, but with quite another; and still a man, who, if
3334 indeed peculiar, it only results again from another phase of the
3335 Quaker, modified by individual circumstances.
3336 
3337 Like Captain Peleg, Captain Bildad was a well-to-do, retired
3338 whaleman.  But unlike Captain Peleg--who cared not a rush for what
3339 are called serious things, and indeed deemed those self-same serious
3340 things the veriest of all trifles--Captain Bildad had not only been
3341 originally educated according to the strictest sect of Nantucket
3342 Quakerism, but all his subsequent ocean life, and the sight of many
3343 unclad, lovely island creatures, round the Horn--all that had not
3344 moved this native born Quaker one single jot, had not so much as
3345 altered one angle of his vest.  Still, for all this immutableness,
3346 was there some lack of common consistency about worthy Captain
3347 Peleg.  Though refusing, from conscientious scruples, to bear arms
3348 against land invaders, yet himself had illimitably invaded the
3349 Atlantic and Pacific; and though a sworn foe to human bloodshed, yet
3350 had he in his straight-bodied coat, spilled tuns upon tuns of
3351 leviathan gore.  How now in the contemplative evening of his days,
3352 the pious Bildad reconciled these things in the reminiscence, I do
3353 not know; but it did not seem to concern him much, and very probably
3354 he had long since come to the sage and sensible conclusion that a
3355 man's religion is one thing, and this practical world quite another.
3356 This world pays dividends.  Rising from a little cabin-boy in short
3357 clothes of the drabbest drab, to a harpooneer in a broad shad-bellied
3358 waistcoat; from that becoming boat-header, chief-mate, and captain,
3359 and finally a ship owner; Bildad, as I hinted before, had concluded
3360 his adventurous career by wholly retiring from active life at the
3361 goodly age of sixty, and dedicating his remaining days to the quiet
3362 receiving of his well-earned income.
3363 
3364 Now, Bildad, I am sorry to say, had the reputation of being an
3365 incorrigible old hunks, and in his sea-going days, a bitter, hard
3366 task-master.  They told me in Nantucket, though it certainly seems a
3367 curious story, that when he sailed the old Categut whaleman, his
3368 crew, upon arriving home, were mostly all carried ashore to the
3369 hospital, sore exhausted and worn out.  For a pious man, especially
3370 for a Quaker, he was certainly rather hard-hearted, to say the
3371 least.  He never used to swear, though, at his men, they said; but
3372 somehow he got an inordinate quantity of cruel, unmitigated hard work
3373 out of them.  When Bildad was a chief-mate, to have his drab-coloured
3374 eye intently looking at you, made you feel completely nervous, till
3375 you could clutch something--a hammer or a marling-spike, and go to
3376 work like mad, at something or other, never mind what.  Indolence and
3377 idleness perished before him.  His own person was the exact
3378 embodiment of his utilitarian character.  On his long, gaunt body, he
3379 carried no spare flesh, no superfluous beard, his chin having a soft,
3380 economical nap to it, like the worn nap of his broad-brimmed hat.
3381 
3382 Such, then, was the person that I saw seated on the transom when I
3383 followed Captain Peleg down into the cabin.  The space between the
3384 decks was small; and there, bolt-upright, sat old Bildad, who always
3385 sat so, and never leaned, and this to save his coat tails.  His
3386 broad-brim was placed beside him; his legs were stiffly crossed; his
3387 drab vesture was buttoned up to his chin; and spectacles on nose, he
3388 seemed absorbed in reading from a ponderous volume.
3389 
3390 "Bildad," cried Captain Peleg, "at it again, Bildad, eh?  Ye have
3391 been studying those Scriptures, now, for the last thirty years, to my
3392 certain knowledge.  How far ye got, Bildad?"
3393 
3394 As if long habituated to such profane talk from his old shipmate,
3395 Bildad, without noticing his present irreverence, quietly looked up,
3396 and seeing me, glanced again inquiringly towards Peleg.
3397 
3398 "He says he's our man, Bildad," said Peleg, "he wants to ship."
3399 
3400 "Dost thee?" said Bildad, in a hollow tone, and turning round to me.
3401 
3402 "I dost," said I unconsciously, he was so intense a Quaker.
3403 
3404 "What do ye think of him, Bildad?" said Peleg.
3405 
3406 "He'll do," said Bildad, eyeing me, and then went on spelling away at
3407 his book in a mumbling tone quite audible.
3408 
3409 I thought him the queerest old Quaker I ever saw, especially as
3410 Peleg, his friend and old shipmate, seemed such a blusterer.  But I
3411 said nothing, only looking round me sharply.  Peleg now threw open a
3412 chest, and drawing forth the ship's articles, placed pen and ink
3413 before him, and seated himself at a little table.  I began to think
3414 it was high time to settle with myself at what terms I would be
3415 willing to engage for the voyage.  I was already aware that in the
3416 whaling business they paid no wages; but all hands, including the
3417 captain, received certain shares of the profits called lays, and that
3418 these lays were proportioned to the degree of importance pertaining
3419 to the respective duties of the ship's company.  I was also aware
3420 that being a green hand at whaling, my own lay would not be very
3421 large; but considering that I was used to the sea, could steer a
3422 ship, splice a rope, and all that, I made no doubt that from all I
3423 had heard I should be offered at least the 275th lay--that is, the
3424 275th part of the clear net proceeds of the voyage, whatever that
3425 might eventually amount to.  And though the 275th lay was what they
3426 call a rather LONG LAY, yet it was better than nothing; and if we had
3427 a lucky voyage, might pretty nearly pay for the clothing I would wear
3428 out on it, not to speak of my three years' beef and board, for which
3429 I would not have to pay one stiver.
3430 
3431 It might be thought that this was a poor way to accumulate a princely
3432 fortune--and so it was, a very poor way indeed.  But I am one of
3433 those that never take on about princely fortunes, and am quite
3434 content if the world is ready to board and lodge me, while I am
3435 putting up at this grim sign of the Thunder Cloud.  Upon the whole, I
3436 thought that the 275th lay would be about the fair thing, but would not
3437 have been surprised had I been offered the 200th, considering I was
3438 of a broad-shouldered make.
3439 
3440 But one thing, nevertheless, that made me a little distrustful about
3441 receiving a generous share of the profits was this: Ashore, I had
3442 heard something of both Captain Peleg and his unaccountable old crony
3443 Bildad; how that they being the principal proprietors of the Pequod,
3444 therefore the other and more inconsiderable and scattered owners,
3445 left nearly the whole management of the ship's affairs to these two.
3446 And I did not know but what the stingy old Bildad might have a mighty
3447 deal to say about shipping hands, especially as I now found him on
3448 board the Pequod, quite at home there in the cabin, and reading his
3449 Bible as if at his own fireside.  Now while Peleg was vainly trying
3450 to mend a pen with his jack-knife, old Bildad, to my no small
3451 surprise, considering that he was such an interested party in these
3452 proceedings; Bildad never heeded us, but went on mumbling to himself
3453 out of his book, "LAY not up for yourselves treasures upon earth,
3454 where moth--"
3455 
3456 "Well, Captain Bildad," interrupted Peleg, "what d'ye say, what lay
3457 shall we give this young man?"
3458 
3459 "Thou knowest best," was the sepulchral reply, "the seven hundred and
3460 seventy-seventh wouldn't be too much, would it?--'where moth and rust
3461 do corrupt, but LAY--'"
3462 
3463 LAY, indeed, thought I, and such a lay! the seven hundred and
3464 seventy-seventh!  Well, old Bildad, you are determined that I, for
3465 one, shall not LAY up many LAYS here below, where moth and rust do
3466 corrupt.  It was an exceedingly LONG LAY that, indeed; and though
3467 from the magnitude of the figure it might at first deceive a
3468 landsman, yet the slightest consideration will show that though seven
3469 hundred and seventy-seven is a pretty large number, yet, when you
3470 come to make a TEENTH of it, you will then see, I say, that the seven
3471 hundred and seventy-seventh part of a farthing is a good deal less
3472 than seven hundred and seventy-seven gold doubloons; and so I thought
3473 at the time.
3474 
3475 "Why, blast your eyes, Bildad," cried Peleg, "thou dost not want to
3476 swindle this young man! he must have more than that."
3477 
3478 "Seven hundred and seventy-seventh," again said Bildad, without
3479 lifting his eyes; and then went on mumbling--"for where your treasure
3480 is, there will your heart be also."
3481 
3482 "I am going to put him down for the three hundredth," said Peleg, "do
3483 ye hear that, Bildad!  The three hundredth lay, I say."
3484 
3485 Bildad laid down his book, and turning solemnly towards him said,
3486 "Captain Peleg, thou hast a generous heart; but thou must consider
3487 the duty thou owest to the other owners of this ship--widows and
3488 orphans, many of them--and that if we too abundantly reward the
3489 labors of this young man, we may be taking the bread from those
3490 widows and those orphans.  The seven hundred and seventy-seventh lay,
3491 Captain Peleg."
3492 
3493 "Thou Bildad!" roared Peleg, starting up and clattering about the
3494 cabin.  "Blast ye, Captain Bildad, if I had followed thy advice in
3495 these matters, I would afore now had a conscience to lug about that
3496 would be heavy enough to founder the largest ship that ever sailed
3497 round Cape Horn."
3498 
3499 "Captain Peleg," said Bildad steadily, "thy conscience may be drawing
3500 ten inches of water, or ten fathoms, I can't tell; but as thou art
3501 still an impenitent man, Captain Peleg, I greatly fear lest thy
3502 conscience be but a leaky one; and will in the end sink thee
3503 foundering down to the fiery pit, Captain Peleg."
3504 
3505 "Fiery pit! fiery pit! ye insult me, man; past all natural bearing,
3506 ye insult me.  It's an all-fired outrage to tell any human creature
3507 that he's bound to hell.  Flukes and flames!  Bildad, say that again
3508 to me, and start my soul-bolts, but I'll--I'll--yes, I'll swallow a
3509 live goat with all his hair and horns on.  Out of the cabin, ye
3510 canting, drab-coloured son of a wooden gun--a straight wake with ye!"
3511 
3512 As he thundered out this he made a rush at Bildad, but with a
3513 marvellous oblique, sliding celerity, Bildad for that time eluded
3514 him.
3515 
3516 Alarmed at this terrible outburst between the two principal and
3517 responsible owners of the ship, and feeling half a mind to give up
3518 all idea of sailing in a vessel so questionably owned and temporarily
3519 commanded, I stepped aside from the door to give egress to Bildad,
3520 who, I made no doubt, was all eagerness to vanish from before the
3521 awakened wrath of Peleg.  But to my astonishment, he sat down again
3522 on the transom very quietly, and seemed to have not the slightest
3523 intention of withdrawing.  He seemed quite used to impenitent Peleg
3524 and his ways.  As for Peleg, after letting off his rage as he had,
3525 there seemed no more left in him, and he, too, sat down like a lamb,
3526 though he twitched a little as if still nervously agitated.  "Whew!"
3527 he whistled at last--"the squall's gone off to leeward, I think.
3528 Bildad, thou used to be good at sharpening a lance, mend that pen,
3529 will ye.  My jack-knife here needs the grindstone.  That's he; thank
3530 ye, Bildad.  Now then, my young man, Ishmael's thy name, didn't ye
3531 say?  Well then, down ye go here, Ishmael, for the three hundredth
3532 lay."
3533 
3534 "Captain Peleg," said I, "I have a friend with me who wants to ship
3535 too--shall I bring him down to-morrow?"
3536 
3537 "To be sure," said Peleg.  "Fetch him along, and we'll look at him."
3538 
3539 "What lay does he want?" groaned Bildad, glancing up from the book
3540 in which he had again been burying himself.
3541 
3542 "Oh! never thee mind about that, Bildad," said Peleg.  "Has he ever
3543 whaled it any?" turning to me.
3544 
3545 "Killed more whales than I can count, Captain Peleg."
3546 
3547 "Well, bring him along then."
3548 
3549 And, after signing the papers, off I went; nothing doubting but that
3550 I had done a good morning's work, and that the Pequod was the
3551 identical ship that Yojo had provided to carry Queequeg and me round
3552 the Cape.
3553 
3554 But I had not proceeded far, when I began to bethink me that the
3555 Captain with whom I was to sail yet remained unseen by me; though,
3556 indeed, in many cases, a whale-ship will be completely fitted out,
3557 and receive all her crew on board, ere the captain makes himself
3558 visible by arriving to take command; for sometimes these voyages are
3559 so prolonged, and the shore intervals at home so exceedingly brief,
3560 that if the captain have a family, or any absorbing concernment of
3561 that sort, he does not trouble himself much about his ship in port,
3562 but leaves her to the owners till all is ready for sea.  However, it
3563 is always as well to have a look at him before irrevocably committing
3564 yourself into his hands.  Turning back I accosted Captain Peleg,
3565 inquiring where Captain Ahab was to be found.
3566 
3567 "And what dost thou want of Captain Ahab?  It's all right enough;
3568 thou art shipped."
3569 
3570 "Yes, but I should like to see him."
3571 
3572 "But I don't think thou wilt be able to at present.  I don't know
3573 exactly what's the matter with him; but he keeps close inside the
3574 house; a sort of sick, and yet he don't look so.  In fact, he ain't
3575 sick; but no, he isn't well either.  Any how, young man, he won't
3576 always see me, so I don't suppose he will thee.  He's a queer man,
3577 Captain Ahab--so some think--but a good one.  Oh, thou'lt like him
3578 well enough; no fear, no fear.  He's a grand, ungodly, god-like man,
3579 Captain Ahab; doesn't speak much; but, when he does speak, then you
3580 may well listen.  Mark ye, be forewarned; Ahab's above the common;
3581 Ahab's been in colleges, as well as 'mong the cannibals; been used to
3582 deeper wonders than the waves; fixed his fiery lance in mightier,
3583 stranger foes than whales.  His lance! aye, the keenest and the surest
3584 that out of all our isle!  Oh! he ain't Captain Bildad; no, and he
3585 ain't Captain Peleg; HE'S AHAB, boy; and Ahab of old, thou knowest,
3586 was a crowned king!"
3587 
3588 "And a very vile one.  When that wicked king was slain, the dogs, did
3589 they not lick his blood?"
3590 
3591 "Come hither to me--hither, hither," said Peleg, with a significance
3592 in his eye that almost startled me.  "Look ye, lad; never say that on
3593 board the Pequod.  Never say it anywhere.  Captain Ahab did not name
3594 himself.  'Twas a foolish, ignorant whim of his crazy, widowed
3595 mother, who died when he was only a twelvemonth old.  And yet the old
3596 squaw Tistig, at Gayhead, said that the name would somehow prove
3597 prophetic.  And, perhaps, other fools like her may tell thee the
3598 same.  I wish to warn thee.  It's a lie.  I know Captain Ahab well;
3599 I've sailed with him as mate years ago; I know what he is--a good
3600 man--not a pious, good man, like Bildad, but a swearing good
3601 man--something like me--only there's a good deal more of him.  Aye,
3602 aye, I know that he was never very jolly; and I know that on the
3603 passage home, he was a little out of his mind for a spell; but it was
3604 the sharp shooting pains in his bleeding stump that brought that
3605 about, as any one might see.  I know, too, that ever since he lost
3606 his leg last voyage by that accursed whale, he's been a kind of
3607 moody--desperate moody, and savage sometimes; but that will all pass
3608 off.  And once for all, let me tell thee and assure thee, young man,
3609 it's better to sail with a moody good captain than a laughing bad
3610 one.  So good-bye to thee--and wrong not Captain Ahab, because he
3611 happens to have a wicked name.  Besides, my boy, he has a wife--not
3612 three voyages wedded--a sweet, resigned girl.  Think of that; by that
3613 sweet girl that old man has a child: hold ye then there can be any
3614 utter, hopeless harm in Ahab?  No, no, my lad; stricken, blasted, if
3615 he be, Ahab has his humanities!"
3616 
3617 As I walked away, I was full of thoughtfulness; what had been
3618 incidentally revealed to me of Captain Ahab, filled me with a certain
3619 wild vagueness of painfulness concerning him.  And somehow, at the
3620 time, I felt a sympathy and a sorrow for him, but for I don't know
3621 what, unless it was the cruel loss of his leg.  And yet I also felt a
3622 strange awe of him; but that sort of awe, which I cannot at all
3623 describe, was not exactly awe; I do not know what it was.  But I felt
3624 it; and it did not disincline me towards him; though I felt
3625 impatience at what seemed like mystery in him, so imperfectly as he
3626 was known to me then.  However, my thoughts were at length carried in
3627 other directions, so that for the present dark Ahab slipped my mind.
