3631 CHAPTER 17
3632 
3633 The Ramadan.
3634 
3635 
3636 As Queequeg's Ramadan, or Fasting and Humiliation, was to continue
3637 all day, I did not choose to disturb him till towards night-fall; for
3638 I cherish the greatest respect towards everybody's religious
3639 obligations, never mind how comical, and could not find it in my
3640 heart to undervalue even a congregation of ants worshipping a
3641 toad-stool; or those other creatures in certain parts of our earth,
3642 who with a degree of footmanism quite unprecedented in other planets,
3643 bow down before the torso of a deceased landed proprietor merely on
3644 account of the inordinate possessions yet owned and rented in his
3645 name.
3646 
3647 I say, we good Presbyterian Christians should be charitable in these
3648 things, and not fancy ourselves so vastly superior to other mortals,
3649 pagans and what not, because of their half-crazy conceits on these
3650 subjects.  There was Queequeg, now, certainly entertaining the most
3651 absurd notions about Yojo and his Ramadan;--but what of that?
3652 Queequeg thought he knew what he was about, I suppose; he seemed to
3653 be content; and there let him rest.  All our arguing with him would
3654 not avail; let him be, I say: and Heaven have mercy on us
3655 all--Presbyterians and Pagans alike--for we are all somehow
3656 dreadfully cracked about the head, and sadly need mending.
3657 
3658 Towards evening, when I felt assured that all his performances and
3659 rituals must be over, I went up to his room and knocked at the door;
3660 but no answer.  I tried to open it, but it was fastened inside.
3661 "Queequeg," said I softly through the key-hole:--all silent.  "I say,
3662 Queequeg! why don't you speak?  It's I--Ishmael."  But all remained
3663 still as before.  I began to grow alarmed.  I had allowed him such
3664 abundant time; I thought he might have had an apoplectic fit.  I
3665 looked through the key-hole; but the door opening into an odd corner
3666 of the room, the key-hole prospect was but a crooked and sinister
3667 one.  I could only see part of the foot-board of the bed and a line
3668 of the wall, but nothing more.  I was surprised to behold resting
3669 against the wall the wooden shaft of Queequeg's harpoon, which the
3670 landlady the evening previous had taken from him, before our mounting
3671 to the chamber.  That's strange, thought I; but at any rate, since
3672 the harpoon stands yonder, and he seldom or never goes abroad without
3673 it, therefore he must be inside here, and no possible mistake.
3674 
3675 "Queequeg!--Queequeg!"--all still.  Something must have happened.
3676 Apoplexy!  I tried to burst open the door; but it stubbornly
3677 resisted.  Running down stairs, I quickly stated my suspicions to the
3678 first person I met--the chamber-maid.  "La! la!" she cried, "I
3679 thought something must be the matter.  I went to make the bed after
3680 breakfast, and the door was locked; and not a mouse to be heard; and
3681 it's been just so silent ever since.  But I thought, may be, you had
3682 both gone off and locked your baggage in for safe keeping.  La! la,
3683 ma'am!--Mistress! murder!  Mrs. Hussey! apoplexy!"--and with these
3684 cries, she ran towards the kitchen, I following.
3685 
3686 Mrs. Hussey soon appeared, with a mustard-pot in one hand and a
3687 vinegar-cruet in the other, having just broken away from the
3688 occupation of attending to the castors, and scolding her little black
3689 boy meantime.
3690 
3691 "Wood-house!" cried I, "which way to it?  Run for God's sake, and
3692 fetch something to pry open the door--the axe!--the axe! he's had a
3693 stroke; depend upon it!"--and so saying I was unmethodically rushing
3694 up stairs again empty-handed, when Mrs. Hussey interposed the
3695 mustard-pot and vinegar-cruet, and the entire castor of her
3696 countenance.
3697 
3698 "What's the matter with you, young man?"
3699 
3700 "Get the axe!  For God's sake, run for the doctor, some one, while I
3701 pry it open!"
3702 
3703 "Look here," said the landlady, quickly putting down the
3704 vinegar-cruet, so as to have one hand free; "look here; are you
3705 talking about prying open any of my doors?"--and with that she seized
3706 my arm.  "What's the matter with you?  What's the matter with you,
3707 shipmate?"
3708 
3709 In as calm, but rapid a manner as possible, I gave her to understand
3710 the whole case.  Unconsciously clapping the vinegar-cruet to one side
3711 of her nose, she ruminated for an instant; then exclaimed--"No!  I
3712 haven't seen it since I put it there."  Running to a little closet
3713 under the landing of the stairs, she glanced in, and returning, told
3714 me that Queequeg's harpoon was missing.  "He's killed himself," she
3715 cried.  "It's unfort'nate Stiggs done over again there goes another
3716 counterpane--God pity his poor mother!--it will be the ruin of my
3717 house.  Has the poor lad a sister?  Where's that girl?--there, Betty,
3718 go to Snarles the Painter, and tell him to paint me a sign, with--"no
3719 suicides permitted here, and no smoking in the parlor;"--might as
3720 well kill both birds at once.  Kill?  The Lord be merciful to his
3721 ghost!  What's that noise there?  You, young man, avast there!"
3722 
3723 And running up after me, she caught me as I was again trying to force
3724 open the door.
3725 
3726 "I don't allow it; I won't have my premises spoiled.  Go for the
3727 locksmith, there's one about a mile from here.  But avast!" putting
3728 her hand in her side-pocket, "here's a key that'll fit, I guess;
3729 let's see."  And with that, she turned it in the lock; but, alas!
3730 Queequeg's supplemental bolt remained unwithdrawn within.
3731 
3732 "Have to burst it open," said I, and was running down the entry a
3733 little, for a good start, when the landlady caught at me, again
3734 vowing I should not break down her premises; but I tore from her, and
3735 with a sudden bodily rush dashed myself full against the mark.
3736 
3737 With a prodigious noise the door flew open, and the knob slamming
3738 against the wall, sent the plaster to the ceiling; and there, good
3739 heavens! there sat Queequeg, altogether cool and self-collected;
3740 right in the middle of the room; squatting on his hams, and holding
3741 Yojo on top of his head.  He looked neither one way nor the other
3742 way, but sat like a carved image with scarce a sign of active life.
3743 
3744 "Queequeg," said I, going up to him, "Queequeg, what's the matter
3745 with you?"
3746 
3747 "He hain't been a sittin' so all day, has he?" said the landlady.
3748 
3749 But all we said, not a word could we drag out of him; I almost felt
3750 like pushing him over, so as to change his position, for it was
3751 almost intolerable, it seemed so painfully and unnaturally
3752 constrained; especially, as in all probability he had been sitting so
3753 for upwards of eight or ten hours, going too without his regular
3754 meals.
3755 
3756 "Mrs. Hussey," said I, "he's ALIVE at all events; so leave us, if you
3757 please, and I will see to this strange affair myself."
3758 
3759 Closing the door upon the landlady, I endeavored to prevail upon
3760 Queequeg to take a chair; but in vain.  There he sat; and all he
3761 could do--for all my polite arts and blandishments--he would not move
3762 a peg, nor say a single word, nor even look at me, nor notice my
3763 presence in the slightest way.
3764 
3765 I wonder, thought I, if this can possibly be a part of his Ramadan;
3766 do they fast on their hams that way in his native island.  It must be
3767 so; yes, it's part of his creed, I suppose; well, then, let him
3768 rest; he'll get up sooner or later, no doubt.  It can't last for
3769 ever, thank God, and his Ramadan only comes once a year; and I don't
3770 believe it's very punctual then.
3771 
3772 I went down to supper.  After sitting a long time listening to the
3773 long stories of some sailors who had just come from a plum-pudding
3774 voyage, as they called it (that is, a short whaling-voyage in a
3775 schooner or brig, confined to the north of the line, in the Atlantic
3776 Ocean only); after listening to these plum-puddingers till nearly
3777 eleven o'clock, I went up stairs to go to bed, feeling quite sure by
3778 this time Queequeg must certainly have brought his Ramadan to a
3779 termination.  But no; there he was just where I had left him; he had
3780 not stirred an inch.  I began to grow vexed with him; it seemed so
3781 downright senseless and insane to be sitting there all day and half
3782 the night on his hams in a cold room, holding a piece of wood on his
3783 head.
3784 
3785 "For heaven's sake, Queequeg, get up and shake yourself; get up and
3786 have some supper.  You'll starve; you'll kill yourself, Queequeg."
3787 But not a word did he reply.
3788 
3789 Despairing of him, therefore, I determined to go to bed and to sleep;
3790 and no doubt, before a great while, he would follow me.  But previous
3791 to turning in, I took my heavy bearskin jacket, and threw it over
3792 him, as it promised to be a very cold night; and he had nothing but
3793 his ordinary round jacket on.  For some time, do all I would, I could
3794 not get into the faintest doze.  I had blown out the candle; and the
3795 mere thought of Queequeg--not four feet off--sitting there in that
3796 uneasy position, stark alone in the cold and dark; this made me
3797 really wretched.  Think of it; sleeping all night in the same room
3798 with a wide awake pagan on his hams in this dreary, unaccountable
3799 Ramadan!
3800 
3801 But somehow I dropped off at last, and knew nothing more till break
3802 of day; when, looking over the bedside, there squatted Queequeg, as
3803 if he had been screwed down to the floor.  But as soon as the first
3804 glimpse of sun entered the window, up he got, with stiff and grating
3805 joints, but with a cheerful look; limped towards me where I lay;
3806 pressed his forehead again against mine; and said his Ramadan was
3807 over.
3808 
3809 Now, as I before hinted, I have no objection to any person's
3810 religion, be it what it may, so long as that person does not kill or
3811 insult any other person, because that other person don't believe it
3812 also.  But when a man's religion becomes really frantic; when it is a
3813 positive torment to him; and, in fine, makes this earth of ours an
3814 uncomfortable inn to lodge in; then I think it high time to take that
3815 individual aside and argue the point with him.
3816 
3817 And just so I now did with Queequeg.  "Queequeg," said I, "get into
3818 bed now, and lie and listen to me."  I then went on, beginning with
3819 the rise and progress of the primitive religions, and coming down to
3820 the various religions of the present time, during which time I
3821 labored to show Queequeg that all these Lents, Ramadans, and
3822 prolonged ham-squattings in cold, cheerless rooms were stark
3823 nonsense; bad for the health; useless for the soul; opposed, in
3824 short, to the obvious laws of Hygiene and common sense.  I told him,
3825 too, that he being in other things such an extremely sensible and
3826 sagacious savage, it pained me, very badly pained me, to see him now
3827 so deplorably foolish about this ridiculous Ramadan of his.  Besides,
3828 argued I, fasting makes the body cave in; hence the spirit caves in;
3829 and all thoughts born of a fast must necessarily be half-starved.
3830 This is the reason why most dyspeptic religionists cherish such
3831 melancholy notions about their hereafters.  In one word, Queequeg,
3832 said I, rather digressively; hell is an idea first born on an
3833 undigested apple-dumpling; and since then perpetuated through the
