4192 All Astir.
4193 
4194 
4195 A day or two passed, and there was great activity aboard the Pequod.
4196 Not only were the old sails being mended, but new sails were coming
4197 on board, and bolts of canvas, and coils of rigging; in short,
4198 everything betokened that the ship's preparations were hurrying to a
4199 close.  Captain Peleg seldom or never went ashore, but sat in his
4200 wigwam keeping a sharp look-out upon the hands: Bildad did all the
4201 purchasing and providing at the stores; and the men employed in the
4202 hold and on the rigging were working till long after night-fall.
4203 
4204 On the day following Queequeg's signing the articles, word was given
4205 at all the inns where the ship's company were stopping, that their
4206 chests must be on board before night, for there was no telling how
4207 soon the vessel might be sailing.  So Queequeg and I got down our
4208 traps, resolving, however, to sleep ashore till the last.  But it
4209 seems they always give very long notice in these cases, and the ship
4210 did not sail for several days.  But no wonder; there was a good deal
4211 to be done, and there is no telling how many things to be thought of,
4212 before the Pequod was fully equipped.
4213 
4214 Every one knows what a multitude of things--beds, sauce-pans, knives
4215 and forks, shovels and tongs, napkins, nut-crackers, and what not,
4216 are indispensable to the business of housekeeping.  Just so with
4217 whaling, which necessitates a three-years' housekeeping upon the wide
4218 ocean, far from all grocers, costermongers, doctors, bakers, and
4219 bankers.  And though this also holds true of merchant vessels, yet
4220 not by any means to the same extent as with whalemen.  For besides
4221 the great length of the whaling voyage, the numerous articles
4222 peculiar to the prosecution of the fishery, and the impossibility of
4223 replacing them at the remote harbors usually frequented, it must be
4224 remembered, that of all ships, whaling vessels are the most exposed
4225 to accidents of all kinds, and especially to the destruction and loss
4226 of the very things upon which the success of the voyage most depends.
4227 Hence, the spare boats, spare spars, and spare lines and harpoons,
4228 and spare everythings, almost, but a spare Captain and duplicate
4229 ship.
4230 
4231 At the period of our arrival at the Island, the heaviest storage of
4232 the Pequod had been almost completed; comprising her beef, bread,
4233 water, fuel, and iron hoops and staves.  But, as before hinted, for
4234 some time there was a continual fetching and carrying on board of
4235 divers odds and ends of things, both large and small.
4236 
4237 Chief among those who did this fetching and carrying was Captain
4238 Bildad's sister, a lean old lady of a most determined and
4239 indefatigable spirit, but withal very kindhearted, who seemed
4240 resolved that, if SHE could help it, nothing should be found wanting
4241 in the Pequod, after once fairly getting to sea.  At one time she
4242 would come on board with a jar of pickles for the steward's pantry;
4243 another time with a bunch of quills for the chief mate's desk, where
4244 he kept his log; a third time with a roll of flannel for the small of
4245 some one's rheumatic back.  Never did any woman better deserve her
4246 name, which was Charity--Aunt Charity, as everybody called her.  And
4247 like a sister of charity did this charitable Aunt Charity bustle
4248 about hither and thither, ready to turn her hand and heart to
4249 anything that promised to yield safety, comfort, and consolation to
4250 all on board a ship in which her beloved brother Bildad was
4251 concerned, and in which she herself owned a score or two of
4252 well-saved dollars.
