5584 Thus speak of the whale, the great Cuvier, and John Hunter, and
5585 Lesson, those lights of zoology and anatomy.  Nevertheless, though of
5586 real knowledge there be little, yet of books there are a plenty; and
5587 so in some small degree, with cetology, or the science of whales.
5588 Many are the men, small and great, old and new, landsmen and seamen,
5589 who have at large or in little, written of the whale.  Run over a
5590 few:--The Authors of the Bible; Aristotle; Pliny; Aldrovandi; Sir
5591 Thomas Browne; Gesner; Ray; Linnaeus; Rondeletius; Willoughby; Green;
5592 Artedi; Sibbald; Brisson; Marten; Lacepede; Bonneterre; Desmarest;
5593 Baron Cuvier; Frederick Cuvier; John Hunter; Owen; Scoresby; Beale;
5594 Bennett; J.  Ross Browne; the Author of Miriam Coffin; Olmstead; and
5595 the Rev.  T.  Cheever.  But to what ultimate generalizing purpose all
5596 these have written, the above cited extracts will show.
5597 
5598 Of the names in this list of whale authors, only those following Owen
5599 ever saw living whales; and but one of them was a real professional
5600 harpooneer and whaleman.  I mean Captain Scoresby.  On the separate
5601 subject of the Greenland or right-whale, he is the best existing
5602 authority.  But Scoresby knew nothing and says nothing of the great
