5652 
5653 First: The uncertain, unsettled condition of this science of Cetology
5654 is in the very vestibule attested by the fact, that in some quarters
5655 it still remains a moot point whether a whale be a fish.  In his
5656 System of Nature, A.D. 1776, Linnaeus declares, "I hereby separate
5657 the whales from the fish."  But of my own knowledge, I know that down
5658 to the year 1850, sharks and shad, alewives and herring, against
5659 Linnaeus's express edict, were still found dividing the possession of
5660 the same seas with the Leviathan.
5661 
5662 The grounds upon which Linnaeus would fain have banished the whales
5663 from the waters, he states as follows: "On account of their warm
5664 bilocular heart, their lungs, their movable eyelids, their hollow
5665 ears, penem intrantem feminam mammis lactantem," and finally, "ex
5666 lege naturae jure meritoque."  I submitted all this to my friends
5667 Simeon Macey and Charley Coffin, of Nantucket, both messmates of mine
5668 in a certain voyage, and they united in the opinion that the reasons
5669 set forth were altogether insufficient.  Charley profanely hinted
5670 they were humbug.
