5746 dealers; no doubt to enhance its value by a notion so strangely
5747 significant of its scarcity.  And so the appellation must at last
5748 have come to be bestowed upon the whale from which this spermaceti
5749 was really derived.
5750 
5751 BOOK I. (FOLIO), CHAPTER II. (RIGHT WHALE).--In one respect this is
5752 the most venerable of the leviathans, being the one first regularly
5753 hunted by man.  It yields the article commonly known as whalebone or
5754 baleen; and the oil specially known as "whale oil," an inferior
5755 article in commerce.  Among the fishermen, he is indiscriminately
5756 designated by all the following titles: The Whale; the Greenland
5757 Whale; the Black Whale; the Great Whale; the True Whale; the Right
5758 Whale.  There is a deal of obscurity concerning the identity of the
5759 species thus multitudinously baptised.  What then is the whale, which
5760 I include in the second species of my Folios?  It is the Great
5761 Mysticetus of the English naturalists; the Greenland Whale of the
5762 English whalemen; the Baliene Ordinaire of the French whalemen; the
5763 Growlands Walfish of the Swedes.  It is the whale which for more than
5764 two centuries past has been hunted by the Dutch and English in the
5765 Arctic seas; it is the whale which the American fishermen have long
5766 pursued in the Indian ocean, on the Brazil Banks, on the Nor' West
5767 Coast, and various other parts of the world, designated by them Right
5768 Whale Cruising Grounds.
5769 
5770 Some pretend to see a difference between the Greenland whale of the
5771 English and the right whale of the Americans.  But they precisely
5772 agree in all their grand features; nor has there yet been presented a
5773 single determinate fact upon which to ground a radical distinction.
5774 It is by endless subdivisions based upon the most inconclusive
5775 differences, that some departments of natural history become so
5776 repellingly intricate.  The right whale will be elsewhere treated of
5777 at some length, with reference to elucidating the sperm whale.
5778 
5779 BOOK I. (FOLIO), CHAPTER III. (FIN-BACK).--Under this head I reckon a
5780 monster which, by the various names of Fin-Back, Tall-Spout, and
5781 Long-John, has been seen almost in every sea and is commonly the
5782 whale whose distant jet is so often descried by passengers crossing
5783 the Atlantic, in the New York packet-tracks.  In the length he
5784 attains, and in his baleen, the Fin-back resembles the right whale,
5785 but is of a less portly girth, and a lighter colour, approaching to
5786 olive.  His great lips present a cable-like aspect, formed by the
5787 intertwisting, slanting folds of large wrinkles.  His grand
5788 distinguishing feature, the fin, from which he derives his name, is
5789 often a conspicuous object.  This fin is some three or four feet
5790 long, growing vertically from the hinder part of the back, of an
5791 angular shape, and with a very sharp pointed end.  Even if not the
5792 slightest other part of the creature be visible, this isolated fin
5793 will, at times, be seen plainly projecting from the surface.  When
5794 the sea is moderately calm, and slightly marked with spherical
5795 ripples, and this gnomon-like fin stands up and casts shadows upon
5796 the wrinkled surface, it may well be supposed that the watery circle
5797 surrounding it somewhat resembles a dial, with its style and wavy
5798 hour-lines graved on it.  On that Ahaz-dial the shadow often goes
5799 back.  The Fin-Back is not gregarious.  He seems a whale-hater, as
5800 some men are man-haters.  Very shy; always going solitary;
5801 unexpectedly rising to the surface in the remotest and most sullen
5802 waters; his straight and single lofty jet rising like a tall
5803 misanthropic spear upon a barren plain; gifted with such wondrous
5804 power and velocity in swimming, as to defy all present pursuit from
5805 man; this leviathan seems the banished and unconquerable Cain of his
5806 race, bearing for his mark that style upon his back.  From having the
5807 baleen in his mouth, the Fin-Back is sometimes included with the
5808 right whale, among a theoretic species denominated WHALEBONE WHALES,
5809 that is, whales with baleen.  Of these so called Whalebone whales,
5810 there would seem to be several varieties, most of which, however, are
5811 little known.  Broad-nosed whales and beaked whales; pike-headed
5812 whales; bunched whales; under-jawed whales and rostrated whales, are
5813 the fishermen's names for a few sorts.
5814 
5815 In connection with this appellative of "Whalebone whales," it is of
5816 great importance to mention, that however such a nomenclature may be
5817 convenient in facilitating allusions to some kind of whales, yet it
5818 is in vain to attempt a clear classification of the Leviathan,
5819 founded upon either his baleen, or hump, or fin, or teeth;
5820 notwithstanding that those marked parts or features very obviously
5821 seem better adapted to afford the basis for a regular system of
5822 Cetology than any other detached bodily distinctions, which the
5823 whale, in his kinds, presents.  How then?  The baleen, hump,
5824 back-fin, and teeth; these are things whose peculiarities are
5825 indiscriminately dispersed among all sorts of whales, without any
5826 regard to what may be the nature of their structure in other and
5827 more essential particulars.  Thus, the sperm whale and the humpbacked
5828 whale, each has a hump; but there the similitude ceases.  Then, this
5829 same humpbacked whale and the Greenland whale, each of these has
5830 baleen; but there again the similitude ceases.  And it is just the
5831 same with the other parts above mentioned.  In various sorts of
5832 whales, they form such irregular combinations; or, in the case of any
5833 one of them detached, such an irregular isolation; as utterly to defy
5834 all general methodization formed upon such a basis.  On this rock
5835 every one of the whale-naturalists has split.
5836 
5837 But it may possibly be conceived that, in the internal parts of the
5838 whale, in his anatomy--there, at least, we shall be able to hit the
5839 right classification.  Nay; what thing, for example, is there in the
5840 Greenland whale's anatomy more striking than his baleen?  Yet we have
5841 seen that by his baleen it is impossible correctly to classify the
5842 Greenland whale.  And if you descend into the bowels of the various
5843 leviathans, why there you will not find distinctions a fiftieth part
5844 as available to the systematizer as those external ones already
5845 enumerated.  What then remains? nothing but to take hold of the
5846 whales bodily, in their entire liberal volume, and boldly sort them
5847 that way.  And this is the Bibliographical system here adopted; and
5848 it is the only one that can possibly succeed, for it alone is
5849 practicable.  To proceed.
5850 
5851 BOOK I. (FOLIO) CHAPTER IV. (HUMP-BACK).--This whale is often seen on
5852 the northern American coast.  He has been frequently captured there,
5853 and towed into harbor.  He has a great pack on him like a peddler; or
5854 you might call him the Elephant and Castle whale.  At any rate, the
5855 popular name for him does not sufficiently distinguish him, since the
5856 sperm whale also has a hump though a smaller one.  His oil is not
5857 very valuable.  He has baleen.  He is the most gamesome and
5858 light-hearted of all the whales, making more gay foam and white water
5859 generally than any other of them.
5860 
5861 BOOK I. (FOLIO), CHAPTER V. (RAZOR-BACK).--Of this whale little is
5862 known but his name.  I have seen him at a distance off Cape Horn.  Of
5863 a retiring nature, he eludes both hunters and philosophers.  Though
5864 no coward, he has never yet shown any part of him but his back, which
5865 rises in a long sharp ridge.  Let him go.  I know little more of him,
5866 nor does anybody else.
5867 
5868 BOOK I. (FOLIO), CHAPTER VI. (SULPHUR-BOTTOM).--Another retiring
5869 gentleman, with a brimstone belly, doubtless got by scraping along
5870 the Tartarian tiles in some of his profounder divings.  He is seldom
5871 seen; at least I have never seen him except in the remoter southern
5872 seas, and then always at too great a distance to study his
5873 countenance.  He is never chased; he would run away with rope-walks
5874 of line.  Prodigies are told of him.  Adieu, Sulphur Bottom!  I can
5875 say nothing more that is true of ye, nor can the oldest Nantucketer.
5876 
5877 Thus ends BOOK I. (FOLIO), and now begins BOOK II. (OCTAVO).
5878 
5879 OCTAVOES.*--These embrace the whales of middling magnitude, among
5880 which present may be numbered:--I., the GRAMPUS; II., the BLACK FISH;
5881 III., the NARWHALE; IV., the THRASHER; V., the KILLER.
5882 
5883 
5884 *Why this book of whales is not denominated the Quarto is very plain.
5885 Because, while the whales of this order, though smaller than those
5886 of the former order, nevertheless retain a proportionate likeness to
5887 them in figure, yet the bookbinder's Quarto volume in its dimensioned
5888 form does not preserve the shape of the Folio volume, but the Octavo
5889 volume does.
5890 
5891 
5892 BOOK II. (OCTAVO), CHAPTER I. (GRAMPUS).--Though this fish, whose
5893 loud sonorous breathing, or rather blowing, has furnished a proverb
5894 to landsmen, is so well known a denizen of the deep, yet is he not
5895 popularly classed among whales.  But possessing all the grand
5896 distinctive features of the leviathan, most naturalists have
5897 recognised him for one.  He is of moderate octavo size, varying from
5898 fifteen to twenty-five feet in length, and of corresponding
5899 dimensions round the waist.  He swims in herds; he is never regularly
5900 hunted, though his oil is considerable in quantity, and pretty good
5901 for light.  By some fishermen his approach is regarded as premonitory
5902 of the advance of the great sperm whale.
5903 
5904 BOOK II. (OCTAVO), CHAPTER II. (BLACK FISH).--I give the popular
5905 fishermen's names for all these fish, for generally they are the
5906 best.  Where any name happens to be vague or inexpressive, I shall
5907 say so, and suggest another.  I do so now, touching the Black Fish,
5908 so-called, because blackness is the rule among almost all whales.
5909 So, call him the Hyena Whale, if you please.  His voracity is well
5910 known, and from the circumstance that the inner angles of his lips
5911 are curved upwards, he carries an everlasting Mephistophelean grin on
5912 his face.  This whale averages some sixteen or eighteen feet in
5913 length.  He is found in almost all latitudes.  He has a peculiar way
5914 of showing his dorsal hooked fin in swimming, which looks something
5915 like a Roman nose.  When not more profitably employed, the sperm
5916 whale hunters sometimes capture the Hyena whale, to keep up the
5917 supply of cheap oil for domestic employment--as some frugal
5918 housekeepers, in the absence of company, and quite alone by
5919 themselves, burn unsavory tallow instead of odorous wax.  Though
5920 their blubber is very thin, some of these whales will yield you
5921 upwards of thirty gallons of oil.
5922 
5923 BOOK II. (OCTAVO), CHAPTER III. (NARWHALE), that is, NOSTRIL
5924 WHALE.--Another instance of a curiously named whale, so named I
5925 suppose from his peculiar horn being originally mistaken for a peaked
5926 nose.  The creature is some sixteen feet in length, while its horn
5927 averages five feet, though some exceed ten, and even attain to
5928 fifteen feet.  Strictly speaking, this horn is but a lengthened tusk,
5929 growing out from the jaw in a line a little depressed from the
5930 horizontal.  But it is only found on the sinister side, which has an
5931 ill effect, giving its owner something analogous to the aspect of a
5932 clumsy left-handed man.  What precise purpose this ivory horn or
5933 lance answers, it would be hard to say.  It does not seem to be used
5934 like the blade of the sword-fish and bill-fish; though some sailors
5935 tell me that the Narwhale employs it for a rake in turning over the
5936 bottom of the sea for food.  Charley Coffin said it was used for an
5937 ice-piercer; for the Narwhale, rising to the surface of the Polar
5938 Sea, and finding it sheeted with ice, thrusts his horn up, and so
5939 breaks through.  But you cannot prove either of these surmises to be
5940 correct.  My own opinion is, that however this one-sided horn may
5941 really be used by the Narwhale--however that may be--it would
5942 certainly be very convenient to him for a folder in reading
5943 pamphlets.  The Narwhale I have heard called the Tusked whale, the
5944 Horned whale, and the Unicorn whale.  He is certainly a curious
5945 example of the Unicornism to be found in almost every kingdom of
5946 animated nature.  From certain cloistered old authors I have gathered
5947 that this same sea-unicorn's horn was in ancient days regarded as the
5948 great antidote against poison, and as such, preparations of it
5949 brought immense prices.  It was also distilled to a volatile salts
5950 for fainting ladies, the same way that the horns of the male deer are
5951 manufactured into hartshorn.  Originally it was in itself accounted
5952 an object of great curiosity.  Black Letter tells me that Sir Martin
5953 Frobisher on his return from that voyage, when Queen Bess did
5954 gallantly wave her jewelled hand to him from a window of Greenwich
5955 Palace, as his bold ship sailed down the Thames; "when Sir Martin
5956 returned from that voyage," saith Black Letter, "on bended knees he
5957 presented to her highness a prodigious long horn of the Narwhale,
5958 which for a long period after hung in the castle at Windsor."  An
5959 Irish author avers that the Earl of Leicester, on bended knees, did
5960 likewise present to her highness another horn, pertaining to a land
5961 beast of the unicorn nature.
5962 
5963 The Narwhale has a very picturesque, leopard-like look, being of a
5964 milk-white ground colour, dotted with round and oblong spots of black.
5965 His oil is very superior, clear and fine; but there is little of it,
5966 and he is seldom hunted.  He is mostly found in the circumpolar seas.
5967 
5968 BOOK II. (OCTAVO), CHAPTER IV. (KILLER).--Of this whale little is
5969 precisely known to the Nantucketer, and nothing at all to the
5970 professed naturalist.  From what I have seen of him at a distance,
5971 I should say that he was about the bigness of a grampus.  He is very
5972 savage--a sort of Feegee fish.  He sometimes takes the great Folio
5973 whales by the lip, and hangs there like a leech, till the mighty
5974 brute is worried to death.  The Killer is never hunted.  I never
5975 heard what sort of oil he has.  Exception might be taken to the name
5976 bestowed upon this whale, on the ground of its indistinctness.  For
5977 we are all killers, on land and on sea; Bonapartes and Sharks
5978 included.
5979 
5980 BOOK II. (OCTAVO), CHAPTER V. (THRASHER).--This gentleman is famous
5981 for his tail, which he uses for a ferule in thrashing his foes.  He
5982 mounts the Folio whale's back, and as he swims, he works his passage
5983 by flogging him; as some schoolmasters get along in the world by a
5984 similar process.  Still less is known of the Thrasher than of the
5985 Killer.  Both are outlaws, even in the lawless seas.
5986 
5987 Thus ends BOOK II. (OCTAVO), and begins BOOK III. (DUODECIMO).
5988 
5989 DUODECIMOES.--These include the smaller whales.  I. The Huzza
5990 Porpoise.  II. The Algerine Porpoise.  III. The Mealy-mouthed
5991 Porpoise.
5992 
5993 To those who have not chanced specially to study the subject, it may
5994 possibly seem strange, that fishes not commonly exceeding four or
5995 five feet should be marshalled among WHALES--a word, which, in the
5996 popular sense, always conveys an idea of hugeness.  But the creatures
5997 set down above as Duodecimoes are infallibly whales, by the terms of
5998 my definition of what a whale is--i.e. a spouting fish, with a
5999 horizontal tail.
6000 
6001 BOOK III. (DUODECIMO), CHAPTER 1. (HUZZA PORPOISE).--This is the
6002 common porpoise found almost all over the globe.  The name is of my
6003 own bestowal; for there are more than one sort of porpoises, and
6004 something must be done to distinguish them.  I call him thus, because
6005 he always swims in hilarious shoals, which upon the broad sea keep
6006 tossing themselves to heaven like caps in a Fourth-of-July crowd.
6007 Their appearance is generally hailed with delight by the mariner.
6008 Full of fine spirits, they invariably come from the breezy billows to
6009 windward.  They are the lads that always live before the wind.  They
6010 are accounted a lucky omen.  If you yourself can withstand three
6011 cheers at beholding these vivacious fish, then heaven help ye; the
6012 spirit of godly gamesomeness is not in ye.  A well-fed, plump Huzza
6013 Porpoise will yield you one good gallon of good oil.  But the fine
6014 and delicate fluid extracted from his jaws is exceedingly valuable.
6015 It is in request among jewellers and watchmakers.  Sailors put it on
6016 their hones.  Porpoise meat is good eating, you know.  It may never
6017 have occurred to you that a porpoise spouts.  Indeed, his spout is so
6018 small that it is not very readily discernible.  But the next time you
6019 have a chance, watch him; and you will then see the great Sperm whale
6020 himself in miniature.
6021 
6022 BOOK III. (DUODECIMO), CHAPTER II. (ALGERINE PORPOISE).--A pirate.
6023 Very savage.  He is only found, I think, in the Pacific.  He is
6024 somewhat larger than the Huzza Porpoise, but much of the same general
6025 make.  Provoke him, and he will buckle to a shark.  I have lowered
6026 for him many times, but never yet saw him captured.
6027 
6028 BOOK III. (DUODECIMO), CHAPTER III. (MEALY-MOUTHED PORPOISE).--The
6029 largest kind of Porpoise; and only found in the Pacific, so far as it
6030 is known.  The only English name, by which he has hitherto been
6031 designated, is that of the fishers--Right-Whale Porpoise, from the
6032 circumstance that he is chiefly found in the vicinity of that Folio.
6033 In shape, he differs in some degree from the Huzza Porpoise, being of
6034 a less rotund and jolly girth; indeed, he is of quite a neat and
6035 gentleman-like figure.  He has no fins on his back (most other
6036 porpoises have), he has a lovely tail, and sentimental Indian eyes of
6037 a hazel hue.  But his mealy-mouth spoils all.  Though his entire
6038 back down to his side fins is of a deep sable, yet a boundary line,
6039 distinct as the mark in a ship's hull, called the "bright waist,"
6040 that line streaks him from stem to stern, with two separate colours,
6041 black above and white below.  The white comprises part of his head,
6042 and the whole of his mouth, which makes him look as if he had just
6043 escaped from a felonious visit to a meal-bag.  A most mean and mealy
6044 aspect!  His oil is much like that of the common porpoise.
6045 
