6079 CHAPTER 33
6080 
6081 The Specksynder.
6082 
6083 
6084 Concerning the officers of the whale-craft, this seems as good a
6085 place as any to set down a little domestic peculiarity on ship-board,
6086 arising from the existence of the harpooneer class of officers, a
6087 class unknown of course in any other marine than the whale-fleet.
6088 
6089 The large importance attached to the harpooneer's vocation is evinced
6090 by the fact, that originally in the old Dutch Fishery, two centuries
6091 and more ago, the command of a whale ship was not wholly lodged in
6092 the person now called the captain, but was divided between him and an
6093 officer called the Specksynder.  Literally this word means
6094 Fat-Cutter; usage, however, in time made it equivalent to Chief
6095 Harpooneer.  In those days, the captain's authority was restricted to
6096 the navigation and general management of the vessel; while over the
6097 whale-hunting department and all its concerns, the Specksynder or
6098 Chief Harpooneer reigned supreme.  In the British Greenland Fishery,
6099 under the corrupted title of Specksioneer, this old Dutch official is
6100 still retained, but his former dignity is sadly abridged.  At present
6101 he ranks simply as senior Harpooneer; and as such, is but one of the
6102 captain's more inferior subalterns.  Nevertheless, as upon the good
6103 conduct of the harpooneers the success of a whaling voyage largely
6104 depends, and since in the American Fishery he is not only an
6105 important officer in the boat, but under certain circumstances (night
6106 watches on a whaling ground) the command of the ship's deck is also
6107 his; therefore the grand political maxim of the sea demands, that he
6108 should nominally live apart from the men before the mast, and be in
6109 some way distinguished as their professional superior; though always,
6110 by them, familiarly regarded as their social equal.
6111 
6112 Now, the grand distinction drawn between officer and man at sea, is
6113 this--the first lives aft, the last forward.  Hence, in whale-ships
6114 and merchantmen alike, the mates have their quarters with the
6115 captain; and so, too, in most of the American whalers the harpooneers
6116 are lodged in the after part of the ship.  That is to say, they take
6117 their meals in the captain's cabin, and sleep in a place indirectly
6118 communicating with it.
6119 
6120 Though the long period of a Southern whaling voyage (by far the
6121 longest of all voyages now or ever made by man), the peculiar perils
6122 of it, and the community of interest prevailing among a company, all
6123 of whom, high or low, depend for their profits, not upon fixed wages,
6124 but upon their common luck, together with their common vigilance,
6125 intrepidity, and hard work; though all these things do in some cases
6126 tend to beget a less rigorous discipline than in merchantmen
6127 generally; yet, never mind how much like an old Mesopotamian family
6128 these whalemen may, in some primitive instances, live together; for
6129 all that, the punctilious externals, at least, of the quarter-deck
6130 are seldom materially relaxed, and in no instance done away.  Indeed,
6131 many are the Nantucket ships in which you will see the skipper
6132 parading his quarter-deck with an elated grandeur not surpassed in
6133 any military navy; nay, extorting almost as much outward homage as if
6134 he wore the imperial purple, and not the shabbiest of pilot-cloth.
6135 
6136 And though of all men the moody captain of the Pequod was the least
6137 given to that sort of shallowest assumption; and though the only
6138 homage he ever exacted, was implicit, instantaneous obedience; though
6139 he required no man to remove the shoes from his feet ere stepping
6140 upon the quarter-deck; and though there were times when, owing to
6141 peculiar circumstances connected with events hereafter to be
6142 detailed, he addressed them in unusual terms, whether of
6143 condescension or IN TERROREM, or otherwise; yet even Captain Ahab was
6144 by no means unobservant of the paramount forms and usages of the sea.
6145 
6146 Nor, perhaps, will it fail to be eventually perceived, that behind
6147 those forms and usages, as it were, he sometimes masked himself;
6148 incidentally making use of them for other and more private ends than
6149 they were legitimately intended to subserve.  That certain sultanism
6150 of his brain, which had otherwise in a good degree remained
6151 unmanifested; through those forms that same sultanism became
6152 incarnate in an irresistible dictatorship.  For be a man's
6153 intellectual superiority what it will, it can never assume the
6154 practical, available supremacy over other men, without the aid of
6155 some sort of external arts and entrenchments, always, in themselves,
6156 more or less paltry and base.  This it is, that for ever keeps God's
6157 true princes of the Empire from the world's hustings; and leaves the
6158 highest honours that this air can give, to those men who become famous
6159 more through their infinite inferiority to the choice hidden handful
6160 of the Divine Inert, than through their undoubted superiority over
6161 the dead level of the mass.  Such large virtue lurks in these small
6162 things when extreme political superstitions invest them, that in some
6163 royal instances even to idiot imbecility they have imparted potency.
6164 But when, as in the case of Nicholas the Czar, the ringed crown of
6165 geographical empire encircles an imperial brain; then, the plebeian
6166 herds crouch abased before the tremendous centralization.  Nor, will
6167 the tragic dramatist who would depict mortal indomitableness in its
6168 fullest sweep and direct swing, ever forget a hint, incidentally so
6169 important in his art, as the one now alluded to.
6170 
6171 But Ahab, my Captain, still moves before me in all his Nantucket
6172 grimness and shagginess; and in this episode touching Emperors and
6173 Kings, I must not conceal that I have only to do with a poor old
6174 whale-hunter like him; and, therefore, all outward majestical
6175 trappings and housings are denied me.  Oh, Ahab! what shall be grand
6176 in thee, it must needs be plucked at from the skies, and dived for in
6177 the deep, and featured in the unbodied air!
