6181 CHAPTER 34
6182 
6183 The Cabin-Table.
6184 
6185 
6186 It is noon; and Dough-Boy, the steward, thrusting his pale
6187 loaf-of-bread face from the cabin-scuttle, announces dinner to his
6188 lord and master; who, sitting in the lee quarter-boat, has just been
6189 taking an observation of the sun; and is now mutely reckoning the
6190 latitude on the smooth, medallion-shaped tablet, reserved for that
6191 daily purpose on the upper part of his ivory leg.  From his complete
6192 inattention to the tidings, you would think that moody Ahab had not
6193 heard his menial.  But presently, catching hold of the mizen shrouds,
6194 he swings himself to the deck, and in an even, unexhilarated voice,
6195 saying, "Dinner, Mr. Starbuck," disappears into the cabin.
6196 
6197 When the last echo of his sultan's step has died away, and Starbuck,
6198 the first Emir, has every reason to suppose that he is seated, then
6199 Starbuck rouses from his quietude, takes a few turns along the
6200 planks, and, after a grave peep into the binnacle, says, with some
6201 touch of pleasantness, "Dinner, Mr. Stubb," and descends the scuttle.
6202 The second Emir lounges about the rigging awhile, and then slightly
6203 shaking the main brace, to see whether it will be all right with
6204 that important rope, he likewise takes up the old burden, and with a
6205 rapid "Dinner, Mr. Flask," follows after his predecessors.
6206 
6207 But the third Emir, now seeing himself all alone on the quarter-deck,
6208 seems to feel relieved from some curious restraint; for, tipping all
6209 sorts of knowing winks in all sorts of directions, and kicking off
6210 his shoes, he strikes into a sharp but noiseless squall of a hornpipe
6211 right over the Grand Turk's head; and then, by a dexterous sleight,
6212 pitching his cap up into the mizentop for a shelf, he goes down
6213 rollicking so far at least as he remains visible from the deck,
6214 reversing all other processions, by bringing up the rear with music.
6215 But ere stepping into the cabin doorway below, he pauses, ships a new
6216 face altogether, and, then, independent, hilarious little Flask
6217 enters King Ahab's presence, in the character of Abjectus, or the
6218 Slave.
6219 
6220 It is not the least among the strange things bred by the intense
6221 artificialness of sea-usages, that while in the open air of the deck
6222 some officers will, upon provocation, bear themselves boldly and
6223 defyingly enough towards their commander; yet, ten to one, let those
6224 very officers the next moment go down to their customary dinner in
6225 that same commander's cabin, and straightway their inoffensive, not
6226 to say deprecatory and humble air towards him, as he sits at the head
6227 of the table; this is marvellous, sometimes most comical.  Wherefore
6228 this difference?  A problem?  Perhaps not.  To have been Belshazzar,
6229 King of Babylon; and to have been Belshazzar, not haughtily but
6230 courteously, therein certainly must have been some touch of mundane
6231 grandeur.  But he who in the rightly regal and intelligent spirit
6232 presides over his own private dinner-table of invited guests, that
6233 man's unchallenged power and dominion of individual influence for the
6234 time; that man's royalty of state transcends Belshazzar's, for
6235 Belshazzar was not the greatest.  Who has but once dined his friends,
6236 has tasted what it is to be Caesar.  It is a witchery of social
6237 czarship which there is no withstanding.  Now, if to this
6238 consideration you superadd the official supremacy of a ship-master,
6239 then, by inference, you will derive the cause of that peculiarity of
6240 sea-life just mentioned.
6241 
6242 Over his ivory-inlaid table, Ahab presided like a mute, maned
6243 sea-lion on the white coral beach, surrounded by his warlike but
6244 still deferential cubs.  In his own proper turn, each officer waited
6245 to be served.  They were as little children before Ahab; and yet, in
6246 Ahab, there seemed not to lurk the smallest social arrogance.  With
6247 one mind, their intent eyes all fastened upon the old man's knife, as
6248 he carved the chief dish before him.  I do not suppose that for the
6249 world they would have profaned that moment with the slightest
6250 observation, even upon so neutral a topic as the weather.  No!  And
6251 when reaching out his knife and fork, between which the slice of beef
6252 was locked, Ahab thereby motioned Starbuck's plate towards him, the
6253 mate received his meat as though receiving alms; and cut it tenderly;
6254 and a little started if, perchance, the knife grazed against the
6255 plate; and chewed it noiselessly; and swallowed it, not without
6256 circumspection.  For, like the Coronation banquet at Frankfort, where
6257 the German Emperor profoundly dines with the seven Imperial
6258 Electors, so these cabin meals were somehow solemn meals, eaten in
6259 awful silence; and yet at table old Ahab forbade not conversation;
6260 only he himself was dumb.  What a relief it was to choking Stubb,
6261 when a rat made a sudden racket in the hold below.  And poor little
6262 Flask, he was the youngest son, and little boy of this weary family
6263 party.  His were the shinbones of the saline beef; his would have
6264 been the drumsticks.  For Flask to have presumed to help himself,
6265 this must have seemed to him tantamount to larceny in the first
6266 degree.  Had he helped himself at that table, doubtless, never more
6267 would he have been able to hold his head up in this honest world;
6268 nevertheless, strange to say, Ahab never forbade him.  And had Flask
6269 helped himself, the chances were Ahab had never so much as noticed
6270 it.  Least of all, did Flask presume to help himself to butter.
6271 Whether he thought the owners of the ship denied it to him, on
6272 account of its clotting his clear, sunny complexion; or whether he
6273 deemed that, on so long a voyage in such marketless waters, butter
6274 was at a premium, and therefore was not for him, a subaltern; however
6275 it was, Flask, alas! was a butterless man!
6276 
6277 Another thing.  Flask was the last person down at the dinner, and
6278 Flask is the first man up.  Consider!  For hereby Flask's dinner was
6279 badly jammed in point of time.  Starbuck and Stubb both had the start
6280 of him; and yet they also have the privilege of lounging in the rear.
6281 If Stubb even, who is but a peg higher than Flask, happens to have
6282 but a small appetite, and soon shows symptoms of concluding his
6283 repast, then Flask must bestir himself, he will not get more than
6284 three mouthfuls that day; for it is against holy usage for Stubb to
6285 precede Flask to the deck.  Therefore it was that Flask once admitted
6286 in private, that ever since he had arisen to the dignity of an
6287 officer, from that moment he had never known what it was to be
6288 otherwise than hungry, more or less.  For what he ate did not so much
6289 relieve his hunger, as keep it immortal in him.  Peace and
6290 satisfaction, thought Flask, have for ever departed from my stomach.
6291 I am an officer; but, how I wish I could fish a bit of old-fashioned
6292 beef in the forecastle, as I used to when I was before the mast.
6293 There's the fruits of promotion now; there's the vanity of glory:
6294 there's the insanity of life!  Besides, if it were so that any mere
6295 sailor of the Pequod had a grudge against Flask in Flask's official
6296 capacity, all that sailor had to do, in order to obtain ample
6297 vengeance, was to go aft at dinner-time, and get a peep at Flask
6298 through the cabin sky-light, sitting silly and dumfoundered before
6299 awful Ahab.
6300 
6301 Now, Ahab and his three mates formed what may be called the first
6302 table in the Pequod's cabin.  After their departure, taking place in
6303 inverted order to their arrival, the canvas cloth was cleared, or
6304 rather was restored to some hurried order by the pallid steward.  And
6305 then the three harpooneers were bidden to the feast, they being its
6306 residuary legatees.  They made a sort of temporary servants' hall of
6307 the high and mighty cabin.
6308 
6309 In strange contrast to the hardly tolerable constraint and nameless
6310 invisible domineerings of the captain's table, was the entire
6311 care-free license and ease, the almost frantic democracy of those
6312 inferior fellows the harpooneers.  While their masters, the mates,
6313 seemed afraid of the sound of the hinges of their own jaws, the
6314 harpooneers chewed their food with such a relish that there was a
6315 report to it.  They dined like lords; they filled their bellies like
6316 Indian ships all day loading with spices.  Such portentous appetites
6317 had Queequeg and Tashtego, that to fill out the vacancies made by the
6318 previous repast, often the pale Dough-Boy was fain to bring on a
6319 great baron of salt-junk, seemingly quarried out of the solid ox.
6320 And if he were not lively about it, if he did not go with a nimble
6321 hop-skip-and-jump, then Tashtego had an ungentlemanly way of
6322 accelerating him by darting a fork at his back, harpoon-wise.  And
6323 once Daggoo, seized with a sudden humor, assisted Dough-Boy's memory
6324 by snatching him up bodily, and thrusting his head into a great empty
6325 wooden trencher, while Tashtego, knife in hand, began laying out the
6326 circle preliminary to scalping him.  He was naturally a very nervous,
6327 shuddering sort of little fellow, this bread-faced steward; the
6328 progeny of a bankrupt baker and a hospital nurse.  And what with the
6329 standing spectacle of the black terrific Ahab, and the periodical
6330 tumultuous visitations of these three savages, Dough-Boy's whole life
6331 was one continual lip-quiver.  Commonly, after seeing the harpooneers
6332 furnished with all things they demanded, he would escape from their
6333 clutches into his little pantry adjoining, and fearfully peep out at
6334 them through the blinds of its door, till all was over.
6335 
6336 It was a sight to see Queequeg seated over against Tashtego, opposing
6337 his filed teeth to the Indian's: crosswise to them, Daggoo seated on
6338 the floor, for a bench would have brought his hearse-plumed head to
6339 the low carlines; at every motion of his colossal limbs, making the
6340 low cabin framework to shake, as when an African elephant goes
6341 passenger in a ship.  But for all this, the great negro was
6342 wonderfully abstemious, not to say dainty.  It seemed hardly possible
6343 that by such comparatively small mouthfuls he could keep up the
6344 vitality diffused through so broad, baronial, and superb a person.
6345 But, doubtless, this noble savage fed strong and drank deep of the
6346 abounding element of air; and through his dilated nostrils snuffed in
6347 the sublime life of the worlds.  Not by beef or by bread, are giants
6348 made or nourished.  But Queequeg, he had a mortal, barbaric smack of
6349 the lip in eating--an ugly sound enough--so much so, that the
6350 trembling Dough-Boy almost looked to see whether any marks of teeth
6351 lurked in his own lean arms.  And when he would hear Tashtego singing
6352 out for him to produce himself, that his bones might be picked, the
6353 simple-witted steward all but shattered the crockery hanging round
6354 him in the pantry, by his sudden fits of the palsy.  Nor did the
6355 whetstone which the harpooneers carried in their pockets, for their
6356 lances and other weapons; and with which whetstones, at dinner, they
6357 would ostentatiously sharpen their knives; that grating sound did not
6358 at all tend to tranquillize poor Dough-Boy.  How could he forget that
6359 in his Island days, Queequeg, for one, must certainly have been
6360 guilty of some murderous, convivial indiscretions.  Alas!  Dough-Boy!
6361 hard fares the white waiter who waits upon cannibals.  Not a napkin
6362 should he carry on his arm, but a buckler.  In good time, though, to
6363 his great delight, the three salt-sea warriors would rise and depart;
6364 to his credulous, fable-mongering ears, all their martial bones
6365 jingling in them at every step, like Moorish scimetars in scabbards.
6366 
6367 But, though these barbarians dined in the cabin, and nominally lived
6368 there; still, being anything but sedentary in their habits, they were
6369 scarcely ever in it except at mealtimes, and just before
6370 sleeping-time, when they passed through it to their own peculiar
6371 quarters.
6372 
6373 In this one matter, Ahab seemed no exception to most American whale
6374 captains, who, as a set, rather incline to the opinion that by rights
6375 the ship's cabin belongs to them; and that it is by courtesy alone
6376 that anybody else is, at any time, permitted there.  So that, in real
6377 truth, the mates and harpooneers of the Pequod might more properly be
6378 said to have lived out of the cabin than in it.  For when they did
6379 enter it, it was something as a street-door enters a house; turning
6380 inwards for a moment, only to be turned out the next; and, as a
6381 permanent thing, residing in the open air.  Nor did they lose much
6382 hereby; in the cabin was no companionship; socially, Ahab was
6383 inaccessible.  Though nominally included in the census of
6384 Christendom, he was still an alien to it.  He lived in the world, as
6385 the last of the Grisly Bears lived in settled Missouri.  And as when
6386 Spring and Summer had departed, that wild Logan of the woods, burying
6387 himself in the hollow of a tree, lived out the winter there, sucking
6388 his own paws; so, in his inclement, howling old age, Ahab's soul,
6389 shut up in the caved trunk of his body, there fed upon the sullen
6390 paws of its gloom!
