6394 CHAPTER 35
6395 
6396 The Mast-Head.
6397 
6398 
6399 It was during the more pleasant weather, that in due rotation with
6400 the other seamen my first mast-head came round.
6401 
6402 In most American whalemen the mast-heads are manned almost
6403 simultaneously with the vessel's leaving her port; even though she
6404 may have fifteen thousand miles, and more, to sail ere reaching her
6405 proper cruising ground.  And if, after a three, four, or five years'
6406 voyage she is drawing nigh home with anything empty in her--say, an
6407 empty vial even--then, her mast-heads are kept manned to the last;
6408 and not till her skysail-poles sail in among the spires of the port,
6409 does she altogether relinquish the hope of capturing one whale more.
6410 
6411 Now, as the business of standing mast-heads, ashore or afloat, is a
6412 very ancient and interesting one, let us in some measure expatiate
6413 here.  I take it, that the earliest standers of mast-heads were the
6414 old Egyptians; because, in all my researches, I find none prior to
6415 them.  For though their progenitors, the builders of Babel, must
6416 doubtless, by their tower, have intended to rear the loftiest
6417 mast-head in all Asia, or Africa either; yet (ere the final truck was
6418 put to it) as that great stone mast of theirs may be said to have
6419 gone by the board, in the dread gale of God's wrath; therefore, we
6420 cannot give these Babel builders priority over the Egyptians.  And
6421 that the Egyptians were a nation of mast-head standers, is an
6422 assertion based upon the general belief among archaeologists, that
6423 the first pyramids were founded for astronomical purposes: a theory
6424 singularly supported by the peculiar stair-like formation of all four
6425 sides of those edifices; whereby, with prodigious long upliftings of
6426 their legs, those old astronomers were wont to mount to the apex, and
6427 sing out for new stars; even as the look-outs of a modern ship sing
6428 out for a sail, or a whale just bearing in sight.  In Saint Stylites,
6429 the famous Christian hermit of old times, who built him a lofty stone
6430 pillar in the desert and spent the whole latter portion of his life
6431 on its summit, hoisting his food from the ground with a tackle; in
6432 him we have a remarkable instance of a dauntless
6433 stander-of-mast-heads; who was not to be driven from his place by
6434 fogs or frosts, rain, hail, or sleet; but valiantly facing everything
6435 out to the last, literally died at his post.  Of modern
6436 standers-of-mast-heads we have but a lifeless set; mere stone, iron,
6437 and bronze men; who, though well capable of facing out a stiff gale,
6438 are still entirely incompetent to the business of singing out upon
6439 discovering any strange sight.  There is Napoleon; who, upon the top
6440 of the column of Vendome, stands with arms folded, some one hundred
6441 and fifty feet in the air; careless, now, who rules the decks below;
6442 whether Louis Philippe, Louis Blanc, or Louis the Devil.  Great
6443 Washington, too, stands high aloft on his towering main-mast in
6444 Baltimore, and like one of Hercules' pillars, his column marks that
6445 point of human grandeur beyond which few mortals will go.  Admiral
6446 Nelson, also, on a capstan of gun-metal, stands his mast-head in
6447 Trafalgar Square; and ever when most obscured by that London smoke,
6448 token is yet given that a hidden hero is there; for where there is
6449 smoke, must be fire.  But neither great Washington, nor Napoleon, nor
6450 Nelson, will answer a single hail from below, however madly invoked
6451 to befriend by their counsels the distracted decks upon which they
6452 gaze; however it may be surmised, that their spirits penetrate
6453 through the thick haze of the future, and descry what shoals and what
6454 rocks must be shunned.
6455 
6456 It may seem unwarrantable to couple in any respect the mast-head
6457 standers of the land with those of the sea; but that in truth it is
6458 not so, is plainly evinced by an item for which Obed Macy, the sole
6459 historian of Nantucket, stands accountable.  The worthy Obed tells
6460 us, that in the early times of the whale fishery, ere ships were
6461 regularly launched in pursuit of the game, the people of that island
6462 erected lofty spars along the sea-coast, to which the look-outs
6463 ascended by means of nailed cleats, something as fowls go upstairs in
6464 a hen-house.  A few years ago this same plan was adopted by the Bay
6465 whalemen of New Zealand, who, upon descrying the game, gave notice to
6466 the ready-manned boats nigh the beach.  But this custom has now
6467 become obsolete; turn we then to the one proper mast-head, that of a
6468 whale-ship at sea.  The three mast-heads are kept manned from
6469 sun-rise to sun-set; the seamen taking their regular turns (as at the
6470 helm), and relieving each other every two hours.  In the serene
6471 weather of the tropics it is exceedingly pleasant the mast-head; nay,
6472 to a dreamy meditative man it is delightful.  There you stand, a
6473 hundred feet above the silent decks, striding along the deep, as if
6474 the masts were gigantic stilts, while beneath you and between your
6475 legs, as it were, swim the hugest monsters of the sea, even as ships
6476 once sailed between the boots of the famous Colossus at old Rhodes.
6477 There you stand, lost in the infinite series of the sea, with nothing
6478 ruffled but the waves.  The tranced ship indolently rolls; the drowsy
6479 trade winds blow; everything resolves you into languor.  For the most
6480 part, in this tropic whaling life, a sublime uneventfulness invests
6481 you; you hear no news; read no gazettes; extras with startling
6482 accounts of commonplaces never delude you into unnecessary
6483 excitements; you hear of no domestic afflictions; bankrupt
6484 securities; fall of stocks; are never troubled with the thought of
6485 what you shall have for dinner--for all your meals for three years
6486 and more are snugly stowed in casks, and your bill of fare is
6487 immutable.
6488 
6489 In one of those southern whalesmen, on a long three or four years'
6490 voyage, as often happens, the sum of the various hours you spend at
6491 the mast-head would amount to several entire months.  And it is much
6492 to be deplored that the place to which you devote so considerable a
6493 portion of the whole term of your natural life, should be so sadly
6494 destitute of anything approaching to a cosy inhabitiveness, or
6495 adapted to breed a comfortable localness of feeling, such as pertains
6496 to a bed, a hammock, a hearse, a sentry box, a pulpit, a coach, or
6497 any other of those small and snug contrivances in which men
6498 temporarily isolate themselves.  Your most usual point of perch is
6499 the head of the t' gallant-mast, where you stand upon two thin
6500 parallel sticks (almost peculiar to whalemen) called the t' gallant
6501 cross-trees.  Here, tossed about by the sea, the beginner feels about
6502 as cosy as he would standing on a bull's horns.  To be sure, in cold
6503 weather you may carry your house aloft with you, in the shape of a
6504 watch-coat; but properly speaking the thickest watch-coat is no more
6505 of a house than the unclad body; for as the soul is glued inside of
6506 its fleshy tabernacle, and cannot freely move about in it, nor even
6507 move out of it, without running great risk of perishing (like an
6508 ignorant pilgrim crossing the snowy Alps in winter); so a watch-coat
6509 is not so much of a house as it is a mere envelope, or additional
6510 skin encasing you.  You cannot put a shelf or chest of drawers in
6511 your body, and no more can you make a convenient closet of your
6512 watch-coat.
6513 
6514 Concerning all this, it is much to be deplored that the mast-heads of
6515 a southern whale ship are unprovided with those enviable little tents
6516 or pulpits, called CROW'S-NESTS, in which the look-outs of a
6517 Greenland whaler are protected from the inclement weather of the
6518 frozen seas.  In the fireside narrative of Captain Sleet, entitled
6519 "A Voyage among the Icebergs, in quest of the Greenland Whale, and
6520 incidentally for the re-discovery of the Lost Icelandic Colonies of
6521 Old Greenland;" in this admirable volume, all standers of mast-heads
6522 are furnished with a charmingly circumstantial account of the then
6523 recently invented CROW'S-NEST of the Glacier, which was the name of
6524 Captain Sleet's good craft.  He called it the SLEET'S CROW'S-NEST, in
6525 honour of himself; he being the original inventor and patentee, and
6526 free from all ridiculous false delicacy, and holding that if we call
6527 our own children after our own names (we fathers being the original
6528 inventors and patentees), so likewise should we denominate after
6529 ourselves any other apparatus we may beget.  In shape, the Sleet's
6530 crow's-nest is something like a large tierce or pipe; it is open
6531 above, however, where it is furnished with a movable side-screen to
6532 keep to windward of your head in a hard gale.  Being fixed on the
6533 summit of the mast, you ascend into it through a little trap-hatch in
6534 the bottom.  On the after side, or side next the stern of the ship,
6535 is a comfortable seat, with a locker underneath for umbrellas,
6536 comforters, and coats.  In front is a leather rack, in which to keep
6537 your speaking trumpet, pipe, telescope, and other nautical
6538 conveniences.  When Captain Sleet in person stood his mast-head in
6539 this crow's-nest of his, he tells us that he always had a rifle with
6540 him (also fixed in the rack), together with a powder flask and shot,
6541 for the purpose of popping off the stray narwhales, or vagrant sea
6542 unicorns infesting those waters; for you cannot successfully shoot at
6543 them from the deck owing to the resistance of the water, but to shoot
6544 down upon them is a very different thing.  Now, it was plainly a
6545 labor of love for Captain Sleet to describe, as he does, all the
6546 little detailed conveniences of his crow's-nest; but though he so
6547 enlarges upon many of these, and though he treats us to a very
6548 scientific account of his experiments in this crow's-nest, with a
6549 small compass he kept there for the purpose of counteracting the
6550 errors resulting from what is called the "local attraction" of all
6551 binnacle magnets; an error ascribable to the horizontal vicinity of
6552 the iron in the ship's planks, and in the Glacier's case, perhaps, to
6553 there having been so many broken-down blacksmiths among her crew; I
6554 say, that though the Captain is very discreet and scientific here,
6555 yet, for all his learned "binnacle deviations," "azimuth compass
6556 observations," and "approximate errors," he knows very well, Captain
6557 Sleet, that he was not so much immersed in those profound magnetic
6558 meditations, as to fail being attracted occasionally towards that
6559 well replenished little case-bottle, so nicely tucked in on one side
6560 of his crow's nest, within easy reach of his hand.  Though, upon the
6561 whole, I greatly admire and even love the brave, the honest, and
6562 learned Captain; yet I take it very ill of him that he should so
6563 utterly ignore that case-bottle, seeing what a faithful friend and
6564 comforter it must have been, while with mittened fingers and hooded
6565 head he was studying the mathematics aloft there in that bird's nest
6566 within three or four perches of the pole.
6567 
6568 But if we Southern whale-fishers are not so snugly housed aloft as
6569 Captain Sleet and his Greenlandmen were; yet that disadvantage is
6570 greatly counter-balanced by the widely contrasting serenity of those
6571 seductive seas in which we South fishers mostly float.  For one, I
6572 used to lounge up the rigging very leisurely, resting in the top to
6573 have a chat with Queequeg, or any one else off duty whom I might find
6574 there; then ascending a little way further, and throwing a lazy leg
6575 over the top-sail yard, take a preliminary view of the watery
6576 pastures, and so at last mount to my ultimate destination.
6577 
6578 Let me make a clean breast of it here, and frankly admit that I kept
6579 but sorry guard.  With the problem of the universe revolving in me,
6580 how could I--being left completely to myself at such a
6581 thought-engendering altitude--how could I but lightly hold my
6582 obligations to observe all whale-ships' standing orders, "Keep your
6583 weather eye open, and sing out every time."
6584 
6585 And let me in this place movingly admonish you, ye ship-owners of
6586 Nantucket!  Beware of enlisting in your vigilant fisheries any lad
6587 with lean brow and hollow eye; given to unseasonable meditativeness;
6588 and who offers to ship with the Phaedon instead of Bowditch in his
6589 head.  Beware of such an one, I say; your whales must be seen before
6590 they can be killed; and this sunken-eyed young Platonist will tow you
6591 ten wakes round the world, and never make you one pint of sperm the
6592 richer.  Nor are these monitions at all unneeded.  For nowadays, the
6593 whale-fishery furnishes an asylum for many romantic, melancholy, and
6594 absent-minded young men, disgusted with the carking cares of earth,
6595 and seeking sentiment in tar and blubber.  Childe Harold not
6596 unfrequently perches himself upon the mast-head of some luckless
6597 disappointed whale-ship, and in moody phrase ejaculates:--
6598 
6599 "Roll on, thou deep and dark blue ocean, roll!  Ten thousand
6600 blubber-hunters sweep over thee in vain."
6601 
6602 Very often do the captains of such ships take those absent-minded
6603 young philosophers to task, upbraiding them with not feeling
6604 sufficient "interest" in the voyage; half-hinting that they are so
6605 hopelessly lost to all honourable ambition, as that in their secret
6606 souls they would rather not see whales than otherwise.  But all in
6607 vain; those young Platonists have a notion that their vision is
6608 imperfect; they are short-sighted; what use, then, to strain the
6609 visual nerve?  They have left their opera-glasses at home.
6610 
6611 "Why, thou monkey," said a harpooneer to one of these lads, "we've
6612 been cruising now hard upon three years, and thou hast not raised a
6613 whale yet.  Whales are scarce as hen's teeth whenever thou art up
6614 here."  Perhaps they were; or perhaps there might have been shoals of
6615 them in the far horizon; but lulled into such an opium-like
6616 listlessness of vacant, unconscious reverie is this absent-minded
6617 youth by the blending cadence of waves with thoughts, that at last he
6618 loses his identity; takes the mystic ocean at his feet for the
6619 visible image of that deep, blue, bottomless soul, pervading mankind
6620 and nature; and every strange, half-seen, gliding, beautiful thing
6621 that eludes him; every dimly-discovered, uprising fin of some
6622 undiscernible form, seems to him the embodiment of those elusive
6623 thoughts that only people the soul by continually flitting through
6624 it.  In this enchanted mood, thy spirit ebbs away to whence it came;
6625 becomes diffused through time and space; like Crammer's sprinkled
6626 Pantheistic ashes, forming at last a part of every shore the round
6627 globe over.
6628 
6629 There is no life in thee, now, except that rocking life imparted by a
6630 gently rolling ship; by her, borrowed from the sea; by the sea, from
6631 the inscrutable tides of God.  But while this sleep, this dream is on
6632 ye, move your foot or hand an inch; slip your hold at all; and your
6633 identity comes back in horror.  Over Descartian vortices you hover.
6634 And perhaps, at mid-day, in the fairest weather, with one
6635 half-throttled shriek you drop through that transparent air into the
