7362 I, Ishmael, was one of that crew; my shouts had gone up with the
7363 rest; my oath had been welded with theirs; and stronger I shouted,
7364 and more did I hammer and clinch my oath, because of the dread in my
7365 soul.  A wild, mystical, sympathetical feeling was in me; Ahab's
7366 quenchless feud seemed mine.  With greedy ears I learned the history
7367 of that murderous monster against whom I and all the others had taken
7368 our oaths of violence and revenge.
7369 
7370 For some time past, though at intervals only, the unaccompanied,
7371 secluded White Whale had haunted those uncivilized seas mostly
7372 frequented by the Sperm Whale fishermen.  But not all of them knew of
7373 his existence; only a few of them, comparatively, had knowingly seen
7374 him; while the number who as yet had actually and knowingly given
7375 battle to him, was small indeed.  For, owing to the large number of
7376 whale-cruisers; the disorderly way they were sprinkled over the
7377 entire watery circumference, many of them adventurously pushing their
7378 quest along solitary latitudes, so as seldom or never for a whole
7379 twelvemonth or more on a stretch, to encounter a single news-telling
7380 sail of any sort; the inordinate length of each separate voyage; the
7381 irregularity of the times of sailing from home; all these, with other
7382 circumstances, direct and indirect, long obstructed the spread
7383 through the whole world-wide whaling-fleet of the special
7384 individualizing tidings concerning Moby Dick.  It was hardly to be
7385 doubted, that several vessels reported to have encountered, at such
7386 or such a time, or on such or such a meridian, a Sperm Whale of
7387 uncommon magnitude and malignity, which whale, after doing great
7388 mischief to his assailants, had completely escaped them; to some
7389 minds it was not an unfair presumption, I say, that the whale in
7390 question must have been no other than Moby Dick.  Yet as of late the
7391 Sperm Whale fishery had been marked by various and not unfrequent
7392 instances of great ferocity, cunning, and malice in the monster
7393 attacked; therefore it was, that those who by accident ignorantly
7394 gave battle to Moby Dick; such hunters, perhaps, for the most part,
7395 were content to ascribe the peculiar terror he bred, more, as it
7396 were, to the perils of the Sperm Whale fishery at large, than to the
7397 individual cause.  In that way, mostly, the disastrous encounter
7398 between Ahab and the whale had hitherto been popularly regarded.
7399 
7400 And as for those who, previously hearing of the White Whale, by
7401 chance caught sight of him; in the beginning of the thing they had
7402 every one of them, almost, as boldly and fearlessly lowered for him,
7403 as for any other whale of that species.  But at length, such
7404 calamities did ensue in these assaults--not restricted to sprained
7405 wrists and ankles, broken limbs, or devouring amputations--but fatal
7406 to the last degree of fatality; those repeated disastrous repulses,
7407 all accumulating and piling their terrors upon Moby Dick; those
7408 things had gone far to shake the fortitude of many brave hunters, to
7409 whom the story of the White Whale had eventually come.
7410 
7411 Nor did wild rumors of all sorts fail to exaggerate, and still the
7412 more horrify the true histories of these deadly encounters.  For not
7413 only do fabulous rumors naturally grow out of the very body of all
7414 surprising terrible events,--as the smitten tree gives birth to its
7415 fungi; but, in maritime life, far more than in that of terra firma,
7416 wild rumors abound, wherever there is any adequate reality for them
7417 to cling to.  And as the sea surpasses the land in this matter, so
7418 the whale fishery surpasses every other sort of maritime life, in the
7419 wonderfulness and fearfulness of the rumors which sometimes circulate
7420 there.  For not only are whalemen as a body unexempt from that
7421 ignorance and superstitiousness hereditary to all sailors; but of all
7422 sailors, they are by all odds the most directly brought into contact
7423 with whatever is appallingly astonishing in the sea; face to face
7424 they not only eye its greatest marvels, but, hand to jaw, give battle
7425 to them.  Alone, in such remotest waters, that though you sailed a
7426 thousand miles, and passed a thousand shores, you would not come to
7427 any chiseled hearth-stone, or aught hospitable beneath that part of
7428 the sun; in such latitudes and longitudes, pursuing too such a
7429 calling as he does, the whaleman is wrapped by influences all tending
7430 to make his fancy pregnant with many a mighty birth.
7431 
7432 No wonder, then, that ever gathering volume from the mere transit
7433 over the widest watery spaces, the outblown rumors of the White Whale
7434 did in the end incorporate with themselves all manner of morbid
7435 hints, and half-formed foetal suggestions of supernatural agencies,
7436 which eventually invested Moby Dick with new terrors unborrowed from
7437 anything that visibly appears.  So that in many cases such a panic
7438 did he finally strike, that few who by those rumors, at least, had
7439 heard of the White Whale, few of those hunters were willing to
7440 encounter the perils of his jaw.
7441 
7442 But there were still other and more vital practical influences at
7443 work.  Not even at the present day has the original prestige of the
7444 Sperm Whale, as fearfully distinguished from all other species of the
7445 leviathan, died out of the minds of the whalemen as a body.  There
7446 are those this day among them, who, though intelligent and courageous
7447 enough in offering battle to the Greenland or Right whale, would
7448 perhaps--either from professional inexperience, or incompetency, or
7449 timidity, decline a contest with the Sperm Whale; at any rate, there
7450 are plenty of whalemen, especially among those whaling nations not
7451 sailing under the American flag, who have never hostilely encountered
7452 the Sperm Whale, but whose sole knowledge of the leviathan is
7453 restricted to the ignoble monster primitively pursued in the North;
7454 seated on their hatches, these men will hearken with a childish
7455 fireside interest and awe, to the wild, strange tales of Southern
7456 whaling.  Nor is the pre-eminent tremendousness of the great Sperm
7457 Whale anywhere more feelingly comprehended, than on board of those
7458 prows which stem him.
7459 
7460 And as if the now tested reality of his might had in former legendary
7461 times thrown its shadow before it; we find some book
7462 naturalists--Olassen and Povelson--declaring the Sperm Whale not only
7463 to be a consternation to every other creature in the sea, but also to
7464 be so incredibly ferocious as continually to be athirst for human
7465 blood.  Nor even down to so late a time as Cuvier's, were these or
7466 almost similar impressions effaced.  For in his Natural History, the
7467 Baron himself affirms that at sight of the Sperm Whale, all fish
7468 (sharks included) are "struck with the most lively terrors," and
7469 "often in the precipitancy of their flight dash themselves against
7470 the rocks with such violence as to cause instantaneous death."  And
7471 however the general experiences in the fishery may amend such reports
7472 as these; yet in their full terribleness, even to the bloodthirsty
7473 item of Povelson, the superstitious belief in them is, in some
7474 vicissitudes of their vocation, revived in the minds of the hunters.
