7612 It is not probable that this monomania in him took its instant rise
7613 at the precise time of his bodily dismemberment.  Then, in darting at
7614 the monster, knife in hand, he had but given loose to a sudden,
7615 passionate, corporal animosity; and when he received the stroke that
7616 tore him, he probably but felt the agonizing bodily laceration, but
7617 nothing more.  Yet, when by this collision forced to turn towards
7618 home, and for long months of days and weeks, Ahab and anguish lay
7619 stretched together in one hammock, rounding in mid winter that
7620 dreary, howling Patagonian Cape; then it was, that his torn body and
7621 gashed soul bled into one another; and so interfusing, made him mad.
7622 That it was only then, on the homeward voyage, after the encounter,
7623 that the final monomania seized him, seems all but certain from the
7624 fact that, at intervals during the passage, he was a raving lunatic;
7625 and, though unlimbed of a leg, yet such vital strength yet lurked in
7626 his Egyptian chest, and was moreover intensified by his delirium,
7627 that his mates were forced to lace him fast, even there, as he
7628 sailed, raving in his hammock.  In a strait-jacket, he swung to the
7629 mad rockings of the gales.  And, when running into more sufferable
7630 latitudes, the ship, with mild stun'sails spread, floated across the
7631 tranquil tropics, and, to all appearances, the old man's delirium
7632 seemed left behind him with the Cape Horn swells, and he came forth
7633 from his dark den into the blessed light and air; even then, when he
7634 bore that firm, collected front, however pale, and issued his calm
7635 orders once again; and his mates thanked God the direful madness was
7636 now gone; even then, Ahab, in his hidden self, raved on.  Human
7637 madness is oftentimes a cunning and most feline thing.  When you
7638 think it fled, it may have but become transfigured into some still
7639 subtler form.  Ahab's full lunacy subsided not, but deepeningly
7640 contracted; like the unabated Hudson, when that noble Northman flows
7641 narrowly, but unfathomably through the Highland gorge.  But, as in
7642 his narrow-flowing monomania, not one jot of Ahab's broad madness had
7643 been left behind; so in that broad madness, not one jot of his great
7644 natural intellect had perished.  That before living agent, now became
7645 the living instrument.  If such a furious trope may stand, his
7646 special lunacy stormed his general sanity, and carried it, and turned
7647 all its concentred cannon upon its own mad mark; so that far from
7648 having lost his strength, Ahab, to that one end, did now possess a
7649 thousand fold more potency than ever he had sanely brought to bear
7650 upon any one reasonable object.
7651 
7652 This is much; yet Ahab's larger, darker, deeper part remains
7653 unhinted.  But vain to popularize profundities, and all truth is
7654 profound.  Winding far down from within the very heart of this spiked
7655 Hotel de Cluny where we here stand--however grand and wonderful, now
7656 quit it;--and take your way, ye nobler, sadder souls, to those vast
7657 Roman halls of Thermes; where far beneath the fantastic towers of
7658 man's upper earth, his root of grandeur, his whole awful essence sits
7659 in bearded state; an antique buried beneath antiquities, and throned
7660 on torsoes!  So with a broken throne, the great gods mock that
7661 captive king; so like a Caryatid, he patient sits, upholding on his
7662 frozen brow the piled entablatures of ages.  Wind ye down there, ye
7663 prouder, sadder souls! question that proud, sad king!  A family
7664 likeness! aye, he did beget ye, ye young exiled royalties; and from
7665 your grim sire only will the old State-secret come.
7666 
7667 Now, in his heart, Ahab had some glimpse of this, namely: all my
7668 means are sane, my motive and my object mad.  Yet without power to
7669 kill, or change, or shun the fact; he likewise knew that to mankind
7670 he did long dissemble; in some sort, did still.  But that thing of
7671 his dissembling was only subject to his perceptibility, not to his
7672 will determinate.  Nevertheless, so well did he succeed in that
7673 dissembling, that when with ivory leg he stepped ashore at last, no
7674 Nantucketer thought him otherwise than but naturally grieved, and
7675 that to the quick, with the terrible casualty which had overtaken
7676 him.
7677 
7678 The report of his undeniable delirium at sea was likewise popularly
7679 ascribed to a kindred cause.  And so too, all the added moodiness
7680 which always afterwards, to the very day of sailing in the Pequod on
7681 the present voyage, sat brooding on his brow.  Nor is it so very
7682 unlikely, that far from distrusting his fitness for another whaling
7683 voyage, on account of such dark symptoms, the calculating people of
7684 that prudent isle were inclined to harbor the conceit, that for those
7685 very reasons he was all the better qualified and set on edge, for a
7686 pursuit so full of rage and wildness as the bloody hunt of whales.
7687 Gnawed within and scorched without, with the infixed, unrelenting
7688 fangs of some incurable idea; such an one, could he be found, would
7689 seem the very man to dart his iron and lift his lance against the
7690 most appalling of all brutes.  Or, if for any reason thought to be
7691 corporeally incapacitated for that, yet such an one would seem
7692 superlatively competent to cheer and howl on his underlings to the
7693 attack.  But be all this as it may, certain it is, that with the mad
7694 secret of his unabated rage bolted up and keyed in him, Ahab had
7695 purposely sailed upon the present voyage with the one only and
7696 all-engrossing object of hunting the White Whale.  Had any one of his
7697 old acquaintances on shore but half dreamed of what was lurking in
7698 him then, how soon would their aghast and righteous souls have
7699 wrenched the ship from such a fiendish man!  They were bent on
7700 profitable cruises, the profit to be counted down in dollars from the
7701 mint.  He was intent on an audacious, immitigable, and supernatural
7702 revenge.
7703 
7704 Here, then, was this grey-headed, ungodly old man, chasing with
7705 curses a Job's whale round the world, at the head of a crew, too,
7706 chiefly made up of mongrel renegades, and castaways, and
7707 cannibals--morally enfeebled also, by the incompetence of mere
7708 unaided virtue or right-mindedness in Starbuck, the invunerable
7709 jollity of indifference and recklessness in Stubb, and the pervading
7710 mediocrity in Flask.  Such a crew, so officered, seemed specially
7711 picked and packed by some infernal fatality to help him to his
7712 monomaniac revenge.  How it was that they so aboundingly responded to
7713 the old man's ire--by what evil magic their souls were possessed,
7714 that at times his hate seemed almost theirs; the White Whale as much
7715 their insufferable foe as his; how all this came to be--what the
7716 White Whale was to them, or how to their unconscious understandings,
7717 also, in some dim, unsuspected way, he might have seemed the gliding
7718 great demon of the seas of life,--all this to explain, would be to
7719 dive deeper than Ishmael can go.  The subterranean miner that works
7720 in us all, how can one tell whither leads his shaft by the ever
7721 shifting, muffled sound of his pick?  Who does not feel the
7722 irresistible arm drag?  What skiff in tow of a seventy-four can stand
7723 still?  For one, I gave myself up to the abandonment of the time and
7724 the place; but while yet all a-rush to encounter the whale, could see
7725 naught in that brute but the deadliest ill.
