7729 CHAPTER 42
7730 
7731 The Whiteness of The Whale.
7732 
7733 
7734 What the white whale was to Ahab, has been hinted; what, at times, he
7735 was to me, as yet remains unsaid.
7736 
7737 Aside from those more obvious considerations touching Moby Dick,
7738 which could not but occasionally awaken in any man's soul some alarm,
7739 there was another thought, or rather vague, nameless horror
7740 concerning him, which at times by its intensity completely
7741 overpowered all the rest; and yet so mystical and well nigh ineffable
7742 was it, that I almost despair of putting it in a comprehensible form.
7743 It was the whiteness of the whale that above all things appalled me.
7744 But how can I hope to explain myself here; and yet, in some dim,
7745 random way, explain myself I must, else all these chapters might be
7746 naught.
7747 
7748 Though in many natural objects, whiteness refiningly enhances beauty,
7749 as if imparting some special virtue of its own, as in marbles,
7750 japonicas, and pearls; and though various nations have in some way
7751 recognised a certain royal preeminence in this hue; even the
7752 barbaric, grand old kings of Pegu placing the title "Lord of the
7753 White Elephants" above all their other magniloquent ascriptions of
7754 dominion; and the modern kings of Siam unfurling the same snow-white
7755 quadruped in the royal standard; and the Hanoverian flag bearing the
7756 one figure of a snow-white charger; and the great Austrian Empire,
7757 Caesarian, heir to overlording Rome, having for the imperial colour
7758 the same imperial hue; and though this pre-eminence in it applies to
7759 the human race itself, giving the white man ideal mastership over
7760 every dusky tribe; and though, besides, all this, whiteness has been
7761 even made significant of gladness, for among the Romans a white stone
7762 marked a joyful day; and though in other mortal sympathies and
7763 symbolizings, this same hue is made the emblem of many touching,
7764 noble things--the innocence of brides, the benignity of age; though
7765 among the Red Men of America the giving of the white belt of wampum
7766 was the deepest pledge of honour; though in many climes, whiteness
7767 typifies the majesty of Justice in the ermine of the Judge, and
7768 contributes to the daily state of kings and queens drawn by
7769 milk-white steeds; though even in the higher mysteries of the most
7770 august religions it has been made the symbol of the divine
7771 spotlessness and power; by the Persian fire worshippers, the white
7772 forked flame being held the holiest on the altar; and in the Greek
7773 mythologies, Great Jove himself being made incarnate in a snow-white
7774 bull; and though to the noble Iroquois, the midwinter sacrifice of
7775 the sacred White Dog was by far the holiest festival of their
7776 theology, that spotless, faithful creature being held the purest
7777 envoy they could send to the Great Spirit with the annual tidings of
7778 their own fidelity; and though directly from the Latin word for
7779 white, all Christian priests derive the name of one part of their
7780 sacred vesture, the alb or tunic, worn beneath the cassock; and
7781 though among the holy pomps of the Romish faith, white is specially
7782 employed in the celebration of the Passion of our Lord; though in the
7783 Vision of St. John, white robes are given to the redeemed, and the
7784 four-and-twenty elders stand clothed in white before the great-white
7785 throne, and the Holy One that sitteth there white like wool; yet for
7786 all these accumulated associations, with whatever is sweet, and
7787 honourable, and sublime, there yet lurks an elusive something in the
7788 innermost idea of this hue, which strikes more of panic to the soul
7789 than that redness which affrights in blood.
7790 
7791 This elusive quality it is, which causes the thought of whiteness,
7792 when divorced from more kindly associations, and coupled with any
7793 object terrible in itself, to heighten that terror to the furthest
7794 bounds.  Witness the white bear of the poles, and the white shark of
7795 the tropics; what but their smooth, flaky whiteness makes them the
7796 transcendent horrors they are?  That ghastly whiteness it is which
7797 imparts such an abhorrent mildness, even more loathsome than
7798 terrific, to the dumb gloating of their aspect.  So that not the
7799 fierce-fanged tiger in his heraldic coat can so stagger courage as
7800 the white-shrouded bear or shark.*
7801 
7802 
7803 *With reference to the Polar bear, it may possibly be urged by him
7804 who would fain go still deeper into this matter, that it is not the
7805 whiteness, separately regarded, which heightens the intolerable
7806 hideousness of that brute; for, analysed, that heightened
7807 hideousness, it might be said, only rises from the circumstance, that
7808 the irresponsible ferociousness of the creature stands invested in
7809 the fleece of celestial innocence and love; and hence, by bringing
7810 together two such opposite emotions in our minds, the Polar bear
7811 frightens us with so unnatural a contrast.  But even assuming all
7812 this to be true; yet, were it not for the whiteness, you would not
7813 have that intensified terror.
7814 
7815 As for the white shark, the white gliding ghostliness of repose in
7816 that creature, when beheld in his ordinary moods, strangely tallies
7817 with the same quality in the Polar quadruped.  This peculiarity is
7818 most vividly hit by the French in the name they bestow upon that
7819 fish.  The Romish mass for the dead begins with "Requiem eternam"
7820 (eternal rest), whence REQUIEM denominating the mass itself, and any
7821 other funeral music.  Now, in allusion to the white, silent stillness
7822 of death in this shark, and the mild deadliness of his habits, the
7823 French call him REQUIN.
