7826 Bethink thee of the albatross, whence come those clouds of spiritual
7827 wonderment and pale dread, in which that white phantom sails in all
7828 imaginations?  Not Coleridge first threw that spell; but God's great,
7829 unflattering laureate, Nature.*
7830 
7831 
7832 *I remember the first albatross I ever saw.  It was during a
7833 prolonged gale, in waters hard upon the Antarctic seas.  From my
7834 forenoon watch below, I ascended to the overclouded deck; and there,
7835 dashed upon the main hatches, I saw a regal, feathery thing of
7836 unspotted whiteness, and with a hooked, Roman bill sublime.  At
7837 intervals, it arched forth its vast archangel wings, as if to embrace
7838 some holy ark.  Wondrous flutterings and throbbings shook it.  Though
7839 bodily unharmed, it uttered cries, as some king's ghost in
7840 supernatural distress.  Through its inexpressible, strange eyes,
7841 methought I peeped to secrets which took hold of God.  As Abraham
7842 before the angels, I bowed myself; the white thing was so white, its
7843 wings so wide, and in those for ever exiled waters, I had lost the
7844 miserable warping memories of traditions and of towns.  Long I gazed
7845 at that prodigy of plumage.  I cannot tell, can only hint, the things
7846 that darted through me then.  But at last I awoke; and turning, asked
7847 a sailor what bird was this.  A goney, he replied.  Goney! never had
7848 heard that name before; is it conceivable that this glorious thing is
7849 utterly unknown to men ashore! never!  But some time after, I learned
7850 that goney was some seaman's name for albatross.  So that by no
7851 possibility could Coleridge's wild Rhyme have had aught to do with
7852 those mystical impressions which were mine, when I saw that bird upon
7853 our deck.  For neither had I then read the Rhyme, nor knew the bird
7854 to be an albatross.  Yet, in saying this, I do but indirectly burnish
7855 a little brighter the noble merit of the poem and the poet.
7856 
7857 I assert, then, that in the wondrous bodily whiteness of the bird
7858 chiefly lurks the secret of the spell; a truth the more evinced in
7859 this, that by a solecism of terms there are birds called grey
7860 albatrosses; and these I have frequently seen, but never with such
7861 emotions as when I beheld the Antarctic fowl.
7862 
7863 But how had the mystic thing been caught?  Whisper it not, and I will
7864 tell; with a treacherous hook and line, as the fowl floated on the
7865 sea.  At last the Captain made a postman of it; tying a lettered,
7866 leathern tally round its neck, with the ship's time and place; and
7867 then letting it escape.  But I doubt not, that leathern tally, meant
7868 for man, was taken off in Heaven, when the white fowl flew to join
7869 the wing-folding, the invoking, and adoring cherubim!
7870 
7871 
7872 Most famous in our Western annals and Indian traditions is that of
7873 the White Steed of the Prairies; a magnificent milk-white charger,
7874 large-eyed, small-headed, bluff-chested, and with the dignity of a
7875 thousand monarchs in his lofty, overscorning carriage.  He was the
7876 elected Xerxes of vast herds of wild horses, whose pastures in those
7877 days were only fenced by the Rocky Mountains and the Alleghanies.  At
7878 their flaming head he westward trooped it like that chosen star which
7879 every evening leads on the hosts of light.  The flashing cascade of
7880 his mane, the curving comet of his tail, invested him with housings
7881 more resplendent than gold and silver-beaters could have furnished
7882 him.  A most imperial and archangelical apparition of that unfallen,
7883 western world, which to the eyes of the old trappers and hunters
7884 revived the glories of those primeval times when Adam walked majestic
7885 as a god, bluff-browed and fearless as this mighty steed.  Whether
7886 marching amid his aides and marshals in the van of countless cohorts
7887 that endlessly streamed it over the plains, like an Ohio; or whether
7888 with his circumambient subjects browsing all around at the horizon,
7889 the White Steed gallopingly reviewed them with warm nostrils
7890 reddening through his cool milkiness; in whatever aspect he presented
7891 himself, always to the bravest Indians he was the object of trembling
7892 reverence and awe.  Nor can it be questioned from what stands on
7893 legendary record of this noble horse, that it was his spiritual
7894 whiteness chiefly, which so clothed him with divineness; and that
7895 this divineness had that in it which, though commanding worship, at
7896 the same time enforced a certain nameless terror.
7897 
7898 But there are other instances where this whiteness loses all that
7899 accessory and strange glory which invests it in the White Steed and
7900 Albatross.
7901 
7902 What is it that in the Albino man so peculiarly repels and often
7903 shocks the eye, as that sometimes he is loathed by his own kith and
7904 kin!  It is that whiteness which invests him, a thing expressed by
7905 the name he bears.  The Albino is as well made as other men--has no
7906 substantive deformity--and yet this mere aspect of all-pervading
7907 whiteness makes him more strangely hideous than the ugliest abortion.
7908 Why should this be so?
7909 
7910 Nor, in quite other aspects, does Nature in her least palpable but
7911 not the less malicious agencies, fail to enlist among her forces this
7912 crowning attribute of the terrible.  From its snowy aspect, the
7913 gauntleted ghost of the Southern Seas has been denominated the White
7914 Squall.  Nor, in some historic instances, has the art of human malice
7915 omitted so potent an auxiliary.  How wildly it heightens the effect
7916 of that passage in Froissart, when, masked in the snowy symbol of
7917 their faction, the desperate White Hoods of Ghent murder their
7918 bailiff in the market-place!
7919 
7920 Nor, in some things, does the common, hereditary experience of all
7921 mankind fail to bear witness to the supernaturalism of this hue.  It
7922 cannot well be doubted, that the one visible quality in the aspect of
7923 the dead which most appals the gazer, is the marble pallor lingering
7924 there; as if indeed that pallor were as much like the badge of
7925 consternation in the other world, as of mortal trepidation here.  And
7926 from that pallor of the dead, we borrow the expressive hue of the
7927 shroud in which we wrap them.  Nor even in our superstitions do we
7928 fail to throw the same snowy mantle round our phantoms; all ghosts
7929 rising in a milk-white fog--Yea, while these terrors seize us, let us
7930 add, that even the king of terrors, when personified by the
7931 evangelist, rides on his pallid horse.
7932 
7933 Therefore, in his other moods, symbolize whatever grand or gracious
7934 thing he will by whiteness, no man can deny that in its profoundest
7935 idealized significance it calls up a peculiar apparition to the soul.
7936 
7937 But though without dissent this point be fixed, how is mortal man to
7938 account for it?  To analyse it, would seem impossible.  Can we,
7939 then, by the citation of some of those instances wherein this thing
7940 of whiteness--though for the time either wholly or in great part
7941 stripped of all direct associations calculated to impart to it aught
7942 fearful, but nevertheless, is found to exert over us the same
7943 sorcery, however modified;--can we thus hope to light upon some
7944 chance clue to conduct us to the hidden cause we seek?
7945 
7946 Let us try.  But in a matter like this, subtlety appeals to subtlety,
7947 and without imagination no man can follow another into these halls.
7948 And though, doubtless, some at least of the imaginative impressions
7949 about to be presented may have been shared by most men, yet few
7950 perhaps were entirely conscious of them at the time, and therefore
7951 may not be able to recall them now.
7952 
7953 Why to the man of untutored ideality, who happens to be but loosely
7954 acquainted with the peculiar character of the day, does the bare
7955 mention of Whitsuntide marshal in the fancy such long, dreary,
7956 speechless processions of slow-pacing pilgrims, down-cast and hooded
7957 with new-fallen snow?  Or, to the unread, unsophisticated Protestant
7958 of the Middle American States, why does the passing mention of a
7959 White Friar or a White Nun, evoke such an eyeless statue in the soul?
7960 
7961 Or what is there apart from the traditions of dungeoned warriors and
7962 kings (which will not wholly account for it) that makes the White
7963 Tower of London tell so much more strongly on the imagination of an
7964 untravelled American, than those other storied structures, its
7965 neighbors--the Byward Tower, or even the Bloody?  And those sublimer
7966 towers, the White Mountains of New Hampshire, whence, in peculiar
7967 moods, comes that gigantic ghostliness over the soul at the bare
7968 mention of that name, while the thought of Virginia's Blue Ridge is
7969 full of a soft, dewy, distant dreaminess?  Or why, irrespective of
7970 all latitudes and longitudes, does the name of the White Sea exert
7971 such a spectralness over the fancy, while that of the Yellow Sea
7972 lulls us with mortal thoughts of long lacquered mild afternoons on
7973 the waves, followed by the gaudiest and yet sleepiest of sunsets?
7974 Or, to choose a wholly unsubstantial instance, purely addressed to
7975 the fancy, why, in reading the old fairy tales of Central Europe,
7976 does "the tall pale man" of the Hartz forests, whose changeless
7977 pallor unrustlingly glides through the green of the groves--why is
7978 this phantom more terrible than all the whooping imps of the
7979 Blocksburg?
7980 
7981 Nor is it, altogether, the remembrance of her cathedral-toppling
7982 earthquakes; nor the stampedoes of her frantic seas; nor the
7983 tearlessness of arid skies that never rain; nor the sight of her
7984 wide field of leaning spires, wrenched cope-stones, and crosses all
7985 adroop (like canted yards of anchored fleets); and her suburban
7986 avenues of house-walls lying over upon each other, as a tossed pack
7987 of cards;--it is not these things alone which make tearless Lima, the
7988 strangest, saddest city thou can'st see.  For Lima has taken the
7989 white veil; and there is a higher horror in this whiteness of her
7990 woe.  Old as Pizarro, this whiteness keeps her ruins for ever new;
7991 admits not the cheerful greenness of complete decay; spreads over her
7992 broken ramparts the rigid pallor of an apoplexy that fixes its own
7993 distortions.
7994 
7995 I know that, to the common apprehension, this phenomenon of whiteness
7996 is not confessed to be the prime agent in exaggerating the terror of
7997 objects otherwise terrible; nor to the unimaginative mind is there
7998 aught of terror in those appearances whose awfulness to another mind
7999 almost solely consists in this one phenomenon, especially when
8000 exhibited under any form at all approaching to muteness or
8001 universality.  What I mean by these two statements may perhaps be
8002 respectively elucidated by the following examples.
8003 
8004 First: The mariner, when drawing nigh the coasts of foreign lands, if
8005 by night he hear the roar of breakers, starts to vigilance, and feels
8006 just enough of trepidation to sharpen all his faculties; but under
8007 precisely similar circumstances, let him be called from his hammock
8008 to view his ship sailing through a midnight sea of milky
8009 whiteness--as if from encircling headlands shoals of combed white
8010 bears were swimming round him, then he feels a silent, superstitious
8011 dread; the shrouded phantom of the whitened waters is horrible to him
8012 as a real ghost; in vain the lead assures him he is still off
8013 soundings; heart and helm they both go down; he never rests till blue
8014 water is under him again.  Yet where is the mariner who will tell
8015 thee, "Sir, it was not so much the fear of striking hidden rocks, as
8016 the fear of that hideous whiteness that so stirred me?"
8017 
8018 Second: To the native Indian of Peru, the continual sight of the
8019 snowhowdahed Andes conveys naught of dread, except, perhaps, in the
8020 mere fancying of the eternal frosted desolateness reigning at such
8021 vast altitudes, and the natural conceit of what a fearfulness it
8022 would be to lose oneself in such inhuman solitudes.  Much the same is
8023 it with the backwoodsman of the West, who with comparative
8024 indifference views an unbounded prairie sheeted with driven snow, no
8025 shadow of tree or twig to break the fixed trance of whiteness.  Not
8026 so the sailor, beholding the scenery of the Antarctic seas; where at
8027 times, by some infernal trick of legerdemain in the powers of frost
8028 and air, he, shivering and half shipwrecked, instead of rainbows
8029 speaking hope and solace to his misery, views what seems a boundless
8030 churchyard grinning upon him with its lean ice monuments and
8031 splintered crosses.
