8674 Now, in this history of his, Procopius mentions that, during the term
8675 of his prefecture at Constantinople, a great sea-monster was captured
8676 in the neighboring Propontis, or Sea of Marmora, after having
8677 destroyed vessels at intervals in those waters for a period of more
8678 than fifty years.  A fact thus set down in substantial history cannot
8679 easily be gainsaid.  Nor is there any reason it should be.  Of what
8680 precise species this sea-monster was, is not mentioned.  But as he
8681 destroyed ships, as well as for other reasons, he must have been a
8682 whale; and I am strongly inclined to think a sperm whale.  And I will
8683 tell you why.  For a long time I fancied that the sperm whale had
8684 been always unknown in the Mediterranean and the deep waters
8685 connecting with it.  Even now I am certain that those seas are not,
8686 and perhaps never can be, in the present constitution of things, a
8687 place for his habitual gregarious resort.  But further investigations
8688 have recently proved to me, that in modern times there have been
8689 isolated instances of the presence of the sperm whale in the
8690 Mediterranean.  I am told, on good authority, that on the Barbary
8691 coast, a Commodore Davis of the British navy found the skeleton of a
8692 sperm whale.  Now, as a vessel of war readily passes through the
8693 Dardanelles, hence a sperm whale could, by the same route, pass out
8694 of the Mediterranean into the Propontis.
