9350 There are certain queer times and occasions in this strange mixed
9351 affair we call life when a man takes this whole universe for a vast
9352 practical joke, though the wit thereof he but dimly discerns, and
9353 more than suspects that the joke is at nobody's expense but his own.
9354 However, nothing dispirits, and nothing seems worth while disputing.
9355 He bolts down all events, all creeds, and beliefs, and persuasions,
9356 all hard things visible and invisible, never mind how knobby; as an
9357 ostrich of potent digestion gobbles down bullets and gun flints.  And
9358 as for small difficulties and worryings, prospects of sudden
9359 disaster, peril of life and limb; all these, and death itself, seem
9360 to him only sly, good-natured hits, and jolly punches in the side
9361 bestowed by the unseen and unaccountable old joker.  That odd sort of
9362 wayward mood I am speaking of, comes over a man only in some time of
9363 extreme tribulation; it comes in the very midst of his earnestness,
9364 so that what just before might have seemed to him a thing most
9365 momentous, now seems but a part of the general joke.  There is
9366 nothing like the perils of whaling to breed this free and easy sort
9367 of genial, desperado philosophy; and with it I now regarded this
9368 whole voyage of the Pequod, and the great White Whale its object.
9369 
9370 "Queequeg," said I, when they had dragged me, the last man, to the
9371 deck, and I was still shaking myself in my jacket to fling off the
9372 water; "Queequeg, my fine friend, does this sort of thing often
9373 happen?"  Without much emotion, though soaked through just like me,
9374 he gave me to understand that such things did often happen.
9375 
9376 "Mr. Stubb," said I, turning to that worthy, who, buttoned up in his
9377 oil-jacket, was now calmly smoking his pipe in the rain; "Mr. Stubb,
9378 I think I have heard you say that of all whalemen you ever met, our
9379 chief mate, Mr. Starbuck, is by far the most careful and prudent.  I
9380 suppose then, that going plump on a flying whale with your sail set
9381 in a foggy squall is the height of a whaleman's discretion?"
9382 
9383 "Certain.  I've lowered for whales from a leaking ship in a gale off
9384 Cape Horn."
9385 
9386 "Mr. Flask," said I, turning to little King-Post, who was standing
9387 close by; "you are experienced in these things, and I am not.  Will
9388 you tell me whether it is an unalterable law in this fishery, Mr.
9389 Flask, for an oarsman to break his own back pulling himself
9390 back-foremost into death's jaws?"
9391 
9392 "Can't you twist that smaller?" said Flask.  "Yes, that's the law.  I
9393 should like to see a boat's crew backing water up to a whale face
