9790 especially on a common cruising-ground.
9791 
9792 If two strangers crossing the Pine Barrens in New York State, or the
9793 equally desolate Salisbury Plain in England; if casually encountering
9794 each other in such inhospitable wilds, these twain, for the life of
9795 them, cannot well avoid a mutual salutation; and stopping for a
9796 moment to interchange the news; and, perhaps, sitting down for a
9797 while and resting in concert: then, how much more natural that upon
9798 the illimitable Pine Barrens and Salisbury Plains of the sea, two
9799 whaling vessels descrying each other at the ends of the earth--off
9800 lone Fanning's Island, or the far away King's Mills; how much more
9801 natural, I say, that under such circumstances these ships should not
9802 only interchange hails, but come into still closer, more friendly and
9803 sociable contact.  And especially would this seem to be a matter of
9804 course, in the case of vessels owned in one seaport, and whose
9805 captains, officers, and not a few of the men are personally known to
9806 each other; and consequently, have all sorts of dear domestic things
9807 to talk about.
9808 
9809 For the long absent ship, the outward-bounder, perhaps, has letters
9810 on board; at any rate, she will be sure to let her have some papers
9811 of a date a year or two later than the last one on her blurred and
9812 thumb-worn files.  And in return for that courtesy, the outward-bound
9813 ship would receive the latest whaling intelligence from the
9814 cruising-ground to which she may be destined, a thing of the utmost
9815 importance to her.  And in degree, all this will hold true concerning
9816 whaling vessels crossing each other's track on the cruising-ground
9817 itself, even though they are equally long absent from home.  For one
9818 of them may have received a transfer of letters from some third, and
9819 now far remote vessel; and some of those letters may be for the
9820 people of the ship she now meets.  Besides, they would exchange the
9821 whaling news, and have an agreeable chat.  For not only would they
9822 meet with all the sympathies of sailors, but likewise with all the
9823 peculiar congenialities arising from a common pursuit and mutually
9824 shared privations and perils.
9825 
9826 Nor would difference of country make any very essential difference;
9827 that is, so long as both parties speak one language, as is the case
9828 with Americans and English.  Though, to be sure, from the small
9829 number of English whalers, such meetings do not very often occur, and
9830 when they do occur there is too apt to be a sort of shyness between
9831 them; for your Englishman is rather reserved, and your Yankee, he
9832 does not fancy that sort of thing in anybody but himself.  Besides,
9833 the English whalers sometimes affect a kind of metropolitan
9834 superiority over the American whalers; regarding the long, lean
9835 Nantucketer, with his nondescript provincialisms, as a sort of
9836 sea-peasant.  But where this superiority in the English whalemen
9837 does really consist, it would be hard to say, seeing that the Yankees
9838 in one day, collectively, kill more whales than all the English,
9839 collectively, in ten years.  But this is a harmless little foible in
