9881 But what is a GAM?  You might wear out your index-finger running up
9882 and down the columns of dictionaries, and never find the word.  Dr.
9883 Johnson never attained to that erudition; Noah Webster's ark does not
9884 hold it.  Nevertheless, this same expressive word has now for many
9885 years been in constant use among some fifteen thousand true born
9886 Yankees.  Certainly, it needs a definition, and should be
9887 incorporated into the Lexicon.  With that view, let me learnedly
9888 define it.
9889 
9890 GAM.  NOUN--A SOCIAL MEETING OF TWO (OR MORE) WHALESHIPS, GENERALLY
9891 ON A CRUISING-GROUND; WHEN, AFTER EXCHANGING HAILS, THEY EXCHANGE
9892 VISITS BY BOATS' CREWS; THE TWO CAPTAINS REMAINING, FOR THE TIME, ON
9893 BOARD OF ONE SHIP, AND THE TWO CHIEF MATES ON THE OTHER.
9894 
9895 There is another little item about Gamming which must not be
9896 forgotten here.  All professions have their own little peculiarities
9897 of detail; so has the whale fishery.  In a pirate, man-of-war, or
9898 slave ship, when the captain is rowed anywhere in his boat, he always
9899 sits in the stern sheets on a comfortable, sometimes cushioned seat
9900 there, and often steers himself with a pretty little milliner's
9901 tiller decorated with gay cords and ribbons.  But the whale-boat has
9902 no seat astern, no sofa of that sort whatever, and no tiller at all.
9903 High times indeed, if whaling captains were wheeled about the water
9904 on castors like gouty old aldermen in patent chairs.  And as for a
9905 tiller, the whale-boat never admits of any such effeminacy; and
9906 therefore as in gamming a complete boat's crew must leave the ship,
9907 and hence as the boat steerer or harpooneer is of the number, that
9908 subordinate is the steersman upon the occasion, and the captain,
9909 having no place to sit in, is pulled off to his visit all standing
9910 like a pine tree.  And often you will notice that being conscious of
9911 the eyes of the whole visible world resting on him from the sides of
9912 the two ships, this standing captain is all alive to the importance
9913 of sustaining his dignity by maintaining his legs.  Nor is this any
9914 very easy matter; for in his rear is the immense projecting steering
9915 oar hitting him now and then in the small of his back, the after-oar
9916 reciprocating by rapping his knees in front.  He is thus completely
9917 wedged before and behind, and can only expand himself sideways by
9918 settling down on his stretched legs; but a sudden, violent pitch of
9919 the boat will often go far to topple him, because length of
9920 foundation is nothing without corresponding breadth.  Merely make a
9921 spread angle of two poles, and you cannot stand them up.  Then,
9922 again, it would never do in plain sight of the world's riveted eyes,
9923 it would never do, I say, for this straddling captain to be seen
9924 steadying himself the slightest particle by catching hold of anything
9925 with his hands; indeed, as token of his entire, buoyant self-command,
9926 he generally carries his hands in his trowsers' pockets; but perhaps
9927 being generally very large, heavy hands, he carries them there for
9928 ballast.  Nevertheless there have occurred instances, well
9929 authenticated ones too, where the captain has been known for an
9930 uncommonly critical moment or two, in a sudden squall say--to seize
9931 hold of the nearest oarsman's hair, and hold on there like grim
