10002 sensibly increased.  So much so, that now taking some alarm, the
10003 captain, making all sail, stood away for the nearest harbor among the
10004 islands, there to have his hull hove out and repaired.
10005 
10006 "Though no small passage was before her, yet, if the commonest chance
10007 favoured, he did not at all fear that his ship would founder by the
10008 way, because his pumps were of the best, and being periodically
10009 relieved at them, those six-and-thirty men of his could easily keep
10010 the ship free; never mind if the leak should double on her.  In
10011 truth, well nigh the whole of this passage being attended by very
10012 prosperous breezes, the Town-Ho had all but certainly arrived in
10013 perfect safety at her port without the occurrence of the least
10014 fatality, had it not been for the brutal overbearing of Radney, the
10015 mate, a Vineyarder, and the bitterly provoked vengeance of Steelkilt,
10016 a Lakeman and desperado from Buffalo.
10017 
10018 "'Lakeman!--Buffalo!  Pray, what is a Lakeman, and where is Buffalo?'
10019 said Don Sebastian, rising in his swinging mat of grass.
10020 
10021 "On the eastern shore of our Lake Erie, Don; but--I crave your
10022 courtesy--may be, you shall soon hear further of all that.  Now,
10023 gentlemen, in square-sail brigs and three-masted ships, well-nigh as
10024 large and stout as any that ever sailed out of your old Callao to far
10025 Manilla; this Lakeman, in the land-locked heart of our America, had
10026 yet been nurtured by all those agrarian freebooting impressions
10027 popularly connected with the open ocean.  For in their interflowing
10028 aggregate, those grand fresh-water seas of ours,--Erie, and Ontario,
10029 and Huron, and Superior, and Michigan,--possess an ocean-like
10030 expansiveness, with many of the ocean's noblest traits; with many of
10031 its rimmed varieties of races and of climes.  They contain round
10032 archipelagoes of romantic isles, even as the Polynesian waters do; in
10033 large part, are shored by two great contrasting nations, as the
10034 Atlantic is; they furnish long maritime approaches to our numerous
10035 territorial colonies from the East, dotted all round their banks;
10036 here and there are frowned upon by batteries, and by the goat-like
10037 craggy guns of lofty Mackinaw; they have heard the fleet thunderings
10038 of naval victories; at intervals, they yield their beaches to wild
10039 barbarians, whose red painted faces flash from out their peltry
10040 wigwams; for leagues and leagues are flanked by ancient and unentered
10041 forests, where the gaunt pines stand like serried lines of kings in
10042 Gothic genealogies; those same woods harboring wild Afric beasts of
10043 prey, and silken creatures whose exported furs give robes to Tartar
10044 Emperors; they mirror the paved capitals of Buffalo and Cleveland, as
10045 well as Winnebago villages; they float alike the full-rigged merchant
10046 ship, the armed cruiser of the State, the steamer, and the beech
10047 canoe; they are swept by Borean and dismasting blasts as direful as
10048 any that lash the salted wave; they know what shipwrecks are, for out
10049 of sight of land, however inland, they have drowned full many a
10050 midnight ship with all its shrieking crew.  Thus, gentlemen, though
10051 an inlander, Steelkilt was wild-ocean born, and wild-ocean nurtured;
10052 as much of an audacious mariner as any.  And for Radney, though in
10053 his infancy he may have laid him down on the lone Nantucket beach, to
10054 nurse at his maternal sea; though in after life he had long followed
10055 our austere Atlantic and your contemplative Pacific; yet was he quite
10056 as vengeful and full of social quarrel as the backwoods seaman, fresh
10057 from the latitudes of buck-horn handled bowie-knives.  Yet was this
10058 Nantucketer a man with some good-hearted traits; and this Lakeman, a
10059 mariner, who though a sort of devil indeed, might yet by inflexible
10060 firmness, only tempered by that common decency of human recognition
10061 which is the meanest slave's right; thus treated, this Steelkilt had
10062 long been retained harmless and docile.  At all events, he had proved
10063 so thus far; but Radney was doomed and made mad, and Steelkilt--but,
10064 gentlemen, you shall hear.
10065 
10066 "It was not more than a day or two at the furthest after pointing her
10067 prow for her island haven, that the Town-Ho's leak seemed again
10068 increasing, but only so as to require an hour or more at the pumps
10069 every day.  You must know that in a settled and civilized ocean like
10070 our Atlantic, for example, some skippers think little of pumping
10071 their whole way across it; though of a still, sleepy night, should
10072 the officer of the deck happen to forget his duty in that respect,
10073 the probability would be that he and his shipmates would never again
10074 remember it, on account of all hands gently subsiding to the bottom.
10075 Nor in the solitary and savage seas far from you to the westward,
10076 gentlemen, is it altogether unusual for ships to keep clanging at
10077 their pump-handles in full chorus even for a voyage of considerable
10078 length; that is, if it lie along a tolerably accessible coast, or if
10079 any other reasonable retreat is afforded them.  It is only when a
10080 leaky vessel is in some very out of the way part of those waters,
10081 some really landless latitude, that her captain begins to feel a
10082 little anxious.
10083 
10084 "Much this way had it been with the Town-Ho; so when her leak was
10085 found gaining once more, there was in truth some small concern
10086 manifested by several of her company; especially by Radney the mate.
10087 He commanded the upper sails to be well hoisted, sheeted home anew,
10088 and every way expanded to the breeze.  Now this Radney, I suppose,
10089 was as little of a coward, and as little inclined to any sort of
10090 nervous apprehensiveness touching his own person as any fearless,
10091 unthinking creature on land or on sea that you can conveniently
10092 imagine, gentlemen.  Therefore when he betrayed this solicitude about
10093 the safety of the ship, some of the seamen declared that it was only
10094 on account of his being a part owner in her.  So when they were
10095 working that evening at the pumps, there was on this head no small
10096 gamesomeness slily going on among them, as they stood with their feet
10097 continually overflowed by the rippling clear water; clear as any
10098 mountain spring, gentlemen--that bubbling from the pumps ran across
10099 the deck, and poured itself out in steady spouts at the lee
10100 scupper-holes.
10101 
10102 "Now, as you well know, it is not seldom the case in this
10103 conventional world of ours--watery or otherwise; that when a person
10104 placed in command over his fellow-men finds one of them to be very
10105 significantly his superior in general pride of manhood, straightway
10106 against that man he conceives an unconquerable dislike and
10107 bitterness; and if he have a chance he will pull down and pulverize
10108 that subaltern's tower, and make a little heap of dust of it.  Be
10109 this conceit of mine as it may, gentlemen, at all events Steelkilt
10110 was a tall and noble animal with a head like a Roman, and a flowing
10111 golden beard like the tasseled housings of your last viceroy's
10112 snorting charger; and a brain, and a heart, and a soul in him,
10113 gentlemen, which had made Steelkilt Charlemagne, had he been born son
10114 to Charlemagne's father.  But Radney, the mate, was ugly as a mule;
10115 yet as hardy, as stubborn, as malicious.  He did not love Steelkilt,
10116 and Steelkilt knew it.
10117 
10118 "Espying the mate drawing near as he was toiling at the pump with the
10119 rest, the Lakeman affected not to notice him, but unawed, went on
10120 with his gay banterings.
10121 
10122 "'Aye, aye, my merry lads, it's a lively leak this; hold a cannikin,
10123 one of ye, and let's have a taste.  By the Lord, it's worth bottling!
10124 I tell ye what, men, old Rad's investment must go for it! he had
10125 best cut away his part of the hull and tow it home.  The fact is,
10126 boys, that sword-fish only began the job; he's come back again with a
10127 gang of ship-carpenters, saw-fish, and file-fish, and what not; and
10128 the whole posse of 'em are now hard at work cutting and slashing at
10129 the bottom; making improvements, I suppose.  If old Rad were here
10130 now, I'd tell him to jump overboard and scatter 'em.  They're playing
10131 the devil with his estate, I can tell him.  But he's a simple old
10132 soul,--Rad, and a beauty too.  Boys, they say the rest of his
10133 property is invested in looking-glasses.  I wonder if he'd give a
10134 poor devil like me the model of his nose.'
10135 
10136 "'Damn your eyes! what's that pump stopping for?' roared Radney,
10137 pretending not to have heard the sailors' talk.  'Thunder away at
10138 it!'
10139 
10140 'Aye, aye, sir,' said Steelkilt, merry as a cricket.  'Lively, boys,
10141 lively, now!'  And with that the pump clanged like fifty
10142 fire-engines; the men tossed their hats off to it, and ere long that
10143 peculiar gasping of the lungs was heard which denotes the fullest
10144 tension of life's utmost energies.
10145 
10146 "Quitting the pump at last, with the rest of his band, the Lakeman
10147 went forward all panting, and sat himself down on the windlass; his
10148 face fiery red, his eyes bloodshot, and wiping the profuse sweat from
10149 his brow.  Now what cozening fiend it was, gentlemen, that possessed
10150 Radney to meddle with such a man in that corporeally exasperated
10151 state, I know not; but so it happened.  Intolerably striding along
10152 the deck, the mate commanded him to get a broom and sweep down the
10153 planks, and also a shovel, and remove some offensive matters
10154 consequent upon allowing a pig to run at large.
10155 
10156 "Now, gentlemen, sweeping a ship's deck at sea is a piece of
10157 household work which in all times but raging gales is regularly
10158 attended to every evening; it has been known to be done in the case
10159 of ships actually foundering at the time.  Such, gentlemen, is the
10160 inflexibility of sea-usages and the instinctive love of neatness in
10161 seamen; some of whom would not willingly drown without first washing
10162 their faces.  But in all vessels this broom business is the
10163 prescriptive province of the boys, if boys there be aboard.  Besides,
10164 it was the stronger men in the Town-Ho that had been divided into
10165 gangs, taking turns at the pumps; and being the most athletic seaman
10166 of them all, Steelkilt had been regularly assigned captain of one of
10167 the gangs; consequently he should have been freed from any trivial
10168 business not connected with truly nautical duties, such being the
10169 case with his comrades.  I mention all these particulars so that you
10170 may understand exactly how this affair stood between the two men.
10171 
10172 "But there was more than this: the order about the shovel was almost
10173 as plainly meant to sting and insult Steelkilt, as though Radney had
10174 spat in his face.  Any man who has gone sailor in a whale-ship will
10175 understand this; and all this and doubtless much more, the Lakeman
10176 fully comprehended when the mate uttered his command.  But as he sat
10177 still for a moment, and as he steadfastly looked into the mate's
10178 malignant eye and perceived the stacks of powder-casks heaped up in
10179 him and the slow-match silently burning along towards them; as he
10180 instinctively saw all this, that strange forbearance and
10181 unwillingness to stir up the deeper passionateness in any already
10182 ireful being--a repugnance most felt, when felt at all, by really
10183 valiant men even when aggrieved--this nameless phantom feeling,
10184 gentlemen, stole over Steelkilt.
10185 
10186 "Therefore, in his ordinary tone, only a little broken by the bodily
10187 exhaustion he was temporarily in, he answered him saying that
10188 sweeping the deck was not his business, and he would not do it.  And
10189 then, without at all alluding to the shovel, he pointed to three
10190 lads as the customary sweepers; who, not being billeted at the
10191 pumps, had done little or nothing all day.  To this, Radney replied
10192 with an oath, in a most domineering and outrageous manner
10193 unconditionally reiterating his command; meanwhile advancing upon the
10194 still seated Lakeman, with an uplifted cooper's club hammer which he
10195 had snatched from a cask near by.
10196 
10197 "Heated and irritated as he was by his spasmodic toil at the pumps,
10198 for all his first nameless feeling of forbearance the sweating
10199 Steelkilt could but ill brook this bearing in the mate; but somehow
10200 still smothering the conflagration within him, without speaking he
10201 remained doggedly rooted to his seat, till at last the incensed
10202 Radney shook the hammer within a few inches of his face, furiously
10203 commanding him to do his bidding.
10204 
10205 "Steelkilt rose, and slowly retreating round the windlass, steadily
10206 followed by the mate with his menacing hammer, deliberately repeated
10207 his intention not to obey.  Seeing, however, that his forbearance had
10208 not the slightest effect, by an awful and unspeakable intimation with
10209 his twisted hand he warned off the foolish and infatuated man; but it
10210 was to no purpose.  And in this way the two went once slowly round
10211 the windlass; when, resolved at last no longer to retreat, bethinking
10212 him that he had now forborne as much as comported with his humor, the
10213 Lakeman paused on the hatches and thus spoke to the officer:
10214 
10215 "'Mr. Radney, I will not obey you.  Take that hammer away, or look to
10216 yourself.'  But the predestinated mate coming still closer to him,
10217 where the Lakeman stood fixed, now shook the heavy hammer within an
10218 inch of his teeth; meanwhile repeating a string of insufferable
10219 maledictions.  Retreating not the thousandth part of an inch;
10220 stabbing him in the eye with the unflinching poniard of his glance,
10221 Steelkilt, clenching his right hand behind him and creepingly drawing
10222 it back, told his persecutor that if the hammer but grazed his cheek
10223 he (Steelkilt) would murder him.  But, gentlemen, the fool had been
10224 branded for the slaughter by the gods.  Immediately the hammer
10225 touched the cheek; the next instant the lower jaw of the mate was
10226 stove in his head; he fell on the hatch spouting blood like a whale.
10227 
10228 "Ere the cry could go aft Steelkilt was shaking one of the backstays
10229 leading far aloft to where two of his comrades were standing their
10230 mastheads.  They were both Canallers.
10231 
10232 "'Canallers!' cried Don Pedro.  'We have seen many whale-ships in our
10233 harbours, but never heard of your Canallers.  Pardon: who and what are
10234 they?'
10235 
10236 "'Canallers, Don, are the boatmen belonging to our grand Erie Canal.
10237 You must have heard of it.'
10238 
10239 "'Nay, Senor; hereabouts in this dull, warm, most lazy, and
10240 hereditary land, we know but little of your vigorous North.'
10241 
10242 "'Aye?  Well then, Don, refill my cup.  Your chicha's very fine; and
10243 ere proceeding further I will tell ye what our Canallers are; for
10244 such information may throw side-light upon my story.'
10245 
10246 "For three hundred and sixty miles, gentlemen, through the entire
10247 breadth of the state of New York; through numerous populous cities
10248 and most thriving villages; through long, dismal, uninhabited swamps,
10249 and affluent, cultivated fields, unrivalled for fertility; by
10250 billiard-room and bar-room; through the holy-of-holies of great
10251 forests; on Roman arches over Indian rivers; through sun and shade;
10252 by happy hearts or broken; through all the wide contrasting scenery
10253 of those noble Mohawk counties; and especially, by rows of snow-white
10254 chapels, whose spires stand almost like milestones, flows one
10255 continual stream of Venetianly corrupt and often lawless life.
10256 There's your true Ashantee, gentlemen; there howl your pagans; where
10257 you ever find them, next door to you; under the long-flung shadow,
10258 and the snug patronising lee of churches.  For by some curious
10259 fatality, as it is often noted of your metropolitan freebooters that
10260 they ever encamp around the halls of justice, so sinners, gentlemen,
10261 most abound in holiest vicinities.
10262 
10263 "'Is that a friar passing?' said Don Pedro, looking downwards into
10264 the crowded plazza, with humorous concern.
10265 
10266 "'Well for our northern friend, Dame Isabella's Inquisition wanes in
10267 Lima,' laughed Don Sebastian.  'Proceed, Senor.'
10268 
10269 "'A moment!  Pardon!' cried another of the company.  'In the name of
10270 all us Limeese, I but desire to express to you, sir sailor, that we
10271 have by no means overlooked your delicacy in not substituting present
10272 Lima for distant Venice in your corrupt comparison.  Oh! do not bow
10273 and look surprised; you know the proverb all along this
10274 coast--"Corrupt as Lima."  It but bears out your saying, too;
10275 churches more plentiful than billiard-tables, and for ever open--and
10276 "Corrupt as Lima."  So, too, Venice; I have been there; the holy city
10277 of the blessed evangelist, St. Mark!--St. Dominic, purge it!  Your
10278 cup!  Thanks: here I refill; now, you pour out again.'
10279 
10280 "Freely depicted in his own vocation, gentlemen, the Canaller would
10281 make a fine dramatic hero, so abundantly and picturesquely wicked is
10282 he.  Like Mark Antony, for days and days along his green-turfed,
10283 flowery Nile, he indolently floats, openly toying with his
10284 red-cheeked Cleopatra, ripening his apricot thigh upon the sunny
10285 deck.  But ashore, all this effeminacy is dashed.  The brigandish
10286 guise which the Canaller so proudly sports; his slouched and
10287 gaily-ribboned hat betoken his grand features.  A terror to the
10288 smiling innocence of the villages through which he floats; his swart
10289 visage and bold swagger are not unshunned in cities.  Once a vagabond
10290 on his own canal, I have received good turns from one of these
10291 Canallers; I thank him heartily; would fain be not ungrateful; but it
10292 is often one of the prime redeeming qualities of your man of
10293 violence, that at times he has as stiff an arm to back a poor
10294 stranger in a strait, as to plunder a wealthy one.  In sum,
10295 gentlemen, what the wildness of this canal life is, is emphatically
10296 evinced by this; that our wild whale-fishery contains so many of its
10297 most finished graduates, and that scarce any race of mankind, except
10298 Sydney men, are so much distrusted by our whaling captains.  Nor does
10299 it at all diminish the curiousness of this matter, that to many
10300 thousands of our rural boys and young men born along its line, the
10301 probationary life of the Grand Canal furnishes the sole transition
10302 between quietly reaping in a Christian corn-field, and recklessly
10303 ploughing the waters of the most barbaric seas.
10304 
10305 "'I see!  I see!' impetuously exclaimed Don Pedro, spilling his
10306 chicha upon his silvery ruffles.  'No need to travel!  The world's
10307 one Lima.  I had thought, now, that at your temperate North the
10308 generations were cold and holy as the hills.--But the story.'
10309 
10310 "I left off, gentlemen, where the Lakeman shook the backstay.
10311 Hardly had he done so, when he was surrounded by the three junior
10312 mates and the four harpooneers, who all crowded him to the deck.  But
10313 sliding down the ropes like baleful comets, the two Canallers rushed
10314 into the uproar, and sought to drag their man out of it towards the
10315 forecastle.  Others of the sailors joined with them in this attempt,
10316 and a twisted turmoil ensued; while standing out of harm's way, the
10317 valiant captain danced up and down with a whale-pike, calling upon
10318 his officers to manhandle that atrocious scoundrel, and smoke him
10319 along to the quarter-deck.  At intervals, he ran close up to the
10320 revolving border of the confusion, and prying into the heart of it
10321 with his pike, sought to prick out the object of his resentment.  But
10322 Steelkilt and his desperadoes were too much for them all; they
10323 succeeded in gaining the forecastle deck, where, hastily slewing
10324 about three or four large casks in a line with the windlass, these
10325 sea-Parisians entrenched themselves behind the barricade.
10326 
10327 "'Come out of that, ye pirates!' roared the captain, now menacing
10328 them with a pistol in each hand, just brought to him by the steward.
10329 'Come out of that, ye cut-throats!'
10330 
10331 "Steelkilt leaped on the barricade, and striding up and down there,
10332 defied the worst the pistols could do; but gave the captain to
10333 understand distinctly, that his (Steelkilt's) death would be the
10334 signal for a murderous mutiny on the part of all hands.  Fearing in
10335 his heart lest this might prove but too true, the captain a little
10336 desisted, but still commanded the insurgents instantly to return to
10337 their duty.
10338 
10339 "'Will you promise not to touch us, if we do?' demanded their
10340 ringleader.
10341 
10342 "'Turn to! turn to!--I make no promise;--to your duty!  Do you want
10343 to sink the ship, by knocking off at a time like this?  Turn to!' and
10344 he once more raised a pistol.
10345 
10346 "'Sink the ship?' cried Steelkilt.  'Aye, let her sink.  Not a man of
10347 us turns to, unless you swear not to raise a rope-yarn against us.
10348 What say ye, men?' turning to his comrades.  A fierce cheer was their
10349 response.
10350 
10351 "The Lakeman now patrolled the barricade, all the while keeping his
10352 eye on the Captain, and jerking out such sentences as these:--'It's
10353 not our fault; we didn't want it; I told him to take his hammer away;
10354 it was boy's business; he might have known me before this; I told him
10355 not to prick the buffalo; I believe I have broken a finger here
10356 against his cursed jaw; ain't those mincing knives down in the
10357 forecastle there, men? look to those handspikes, my hearties.
10358 Captain, by God, look to yourself; say the word; don't be a fool;
10359 forget it all; we are ready to turn to; treat us decently, and we're
10360 your men; but we won't be flogged.'
10361 
10362 "'Turn to!  I make no promises, turn to, I say!'
10363 
10364 "'Look ye, now,' cried the Lakeman, flinging out his arm towards him,
10365 'there are a few of us here (and I am one of them) who have shipped
10366 for the cruise, d'ye see; now as you well know, sir, we can claim our
10367 discharge as soon as the anchor is down; so we don't want a row; it's
10368 not our interest; we want to be peaceable; we are ready to work, but
10369 we won't be flogged.'
10370 
10371 "'Turn to!' roared the Captain.
10372 
10373 "Steelkilt glanced round him a moment, and then said:--'I tell you
10374 what it is now, Captain, rather than kill ye, and be hung for such a
10375 shabby rascal, we won't lift a hand against ye unless ye attack us;
10376 but till you say the word about not flogging us, we don't do a hand's
10377 turn.'
10378 
10379 "'Down into the forecastle then, down with ye, I'll keep ye there
10380 till ye're sick of it.  Down ye go.'
10381 
10382 "'Shall we?' cried the ringleader to his men.  Most of them were
10383 against it; but at length, in obedience to Steelkilt, they preceded
10384 him down into their dark den, growlingly disappearing, like bears
10385 into a cave.
10386 
10387 "As the Lakeman's bare head was just level with the planks, the
10388 Captain and his posse leaped the barricade, and rapidly drawing over
10389 the slide of the scuttle, planted their group of hands upon it, and
10390 loudly called for the steward to bring the heavy brass padlock
10391 belonging to the companionway.
10392 
10393 Then opening the slide a little, the Captain whispered something down
10394 the crack, closed it, and turned the key upon them--ten in
10395 number--leaving on deck some twenty or more, who thus far had
