10398 "All night a wide-awake watch was kept by all the officers, forward
10399 and aft, especially about the forecastle scuttle and fore hatchway;
10400 at which last place it was feared the insurgents might emerge, after
10401 breaking through the bulkhead below.  But the hours of darkness
10402 passed in peace; the men who still remained at their duty toiling
10403 hard at the pumps, whose clinking and clanking at intervals through
10404 the dreary night dismally resounded through the ship.
10405 
10406 "At sunrise the Captain went forward, and knocking on the deck,
10407 summoned the prisoners to work; but with a yell they refused.  Water
10408 was then lowered down to them, and a couple of handfuls of biscuit
10409 were tossed after it; when again turning the key upon them and
10410 pocketing it, the Captain returned to the quarter-deck.  Twice every
10411 day for three days this was repeated; but on the fourth morning a
10412 confused wrangling, and then a scuffling was heard, as the customary
10413 summons was delivered; and suddenly four men burst up from the
10414 forecastle, saying they were ready to turn to.  The fetid closeness
10415 of the air, and a famishing diet, united perhaps to some fears of
10416 ultimate retribution, had constrained them to surrender at
10417 discretion.  Emboldened by this, the Captain reiterated his demand to
10418 the rest, but Steelkilt shouted up to him a terrific hint to stop his
10419 babbling and betake himself where he belonged.  On the fifth morning
10420 three others of the mutineers bolted up into the air from the
10421 desperate arms below that sought to restrain them.  Only three were
10422 left.
10423 
10424 "'Better turn to, now?' said the Captain with a heartless jeer.
10425 
10426 "'Shut us up again, will ye!' cried Steelkilt.
10427 
10428 "'Oh certainly,' the Captain, and the key clicked.
10429 
10430 "It was at this point, gentlemen, that enraged by the defection of
10431 seven of his former associates, and stung by the mocking voice that
10432 had last hailed him, and maddened by his long entombment in a place
10433 as black as the bowels of despair; it was then that Steelkilt
10434 proposed to the two Canallers, thus far apparently of one mind with
10435 him, to burst out of their hole at the next summoning of the
10436 garrison; and armed with their keen mincing knives (long, crescentic,
10437 heavy implements with a handle at each end) run amuck from the
10438 bowsprit to the taffrail; and if by any devilishness of desperation
10439 possible, seize the ship.  For himself, he would do this, he said,
10440 whether they joined him or not.  That was the last night he should
10441 spend in that den.  But the scheme met with no opposition on the part
10442 of the other two; they swore they were ready for that, or for any
10443 other mad thing, for anything in short but a surrender.  And what was
10444 more, they each insisted upon being the first man on deck, when the
10445 time to make the rush should come.  But to this their leader as
10446 fiercely objected, reserving that priority for himself; particularly
10447 as his two comrades would not yield, the one to the other, in the
10448 matter; and both of them could not be first, for the ladder would but
10449 admit one man at a time.  And here, gentlemen, the foul play of these
10450 miscreants must come out.
10451 
10452 "Upon hearing the frantic project of their leader, each in his own
10453 separate soul had suddenly lighted, it would seem, upon the same
10454 piece of treachery, namely: to be foremost in breaking out, in
10455 order to be the first of the three, though the last of the ten, to
10456 surrender; and thereby secure whatever small chance of pardon such
10457 conduct might merit.  But when Steelkilt made known his determination
10458 still to lead them to the last, they in some way, by some subtle
10459 chemistry of villany, mixed their before secret treacheries together;
10460 and when their leader fell into a doze, verbally opened their souls
10461 to each other in three sentences; and bound the sleeper with cords,
10462 and gagged him with cords; and shrieked out for the Captain at
10463 midnight.
