10781 
10782 
10783 CHAPTER 55
10784 
10785 Of the Monstrous Pictures of Whales.
10786 
10787 
10788 I shall ere long paint to you as well as one can without canvas,
10789 something like the true form of the whale as he actually appears to
10790 the eye of the whaleman when in his own absolute body the whale is
10791 moored alongside the whale-ship so that he can be fairly stepped upon
10792 there.  It may be worth while, therefore, previously to advert to
10793 those curious imaginary portraits of him which even down to the
10794 present day confidently challenge the faith of the landsman.  It is
10795 time to set the world right in this matter, by proving such pictures
10796 of the whale all wrong.
10797 
10798 It may be that the primal source of all those pictorial delusions
10799 will be found among the oldest Hindoo, Egyptian, and Grecian
10800 sculptures.  For ever since those inventive but unscrupulous times
10801 when on the marble panellings of temples, the pedestals of statues,
10802 and on shields, medallions, cups, and coins, the dolphin was drawn in
10803 scales of chain-armor like Saladin's, and a helmeted head like St.
10804 George's; ever since then has something of the same sort of license
10805 prevailed, not only in most popular pictures of the whale, but in
10806 many scientific presentations of him.
10807 
10808 Now, by all odds, the most ancient extant portrait anyways purporting
10809 to be the whale's, is to be found in the famous cavern-pagoda of
10810 Elephanta, in India.  The Brahmins maintain that in the almost
10811 endless sculptures of that immemorial pagoda, all the trades and
10812 pursuits, every conceivable avocation of man, were prefigured ages
10813 before any of them actually came into being.  No wonder then, that in
10814 some sort our noble profession of whaling should have been there
10815 shadowed forth.  The Hindoo whale referred to, occurs in a separate
10816 department of the wall, depicting the incarnation of Vishnu in the
10817 form of leviathan, learnedly known as the Matse Avatar.  But though
10818 this sculpture is half man and half whale, so as only to give the
10819 tail of the latter, yet that small section of him is all wrong.  It
10820 looks more like the tapering tail of an anaconda, than the broad palms
10821 of the true whale's majestic flukes.
10822 
10823 But go to the old Galleries, and look now at a great Christian
10824 painter's portrait of this fish; for he succeeds no better than the
10825 antediluvian Hindoo.  It is Guido's picture of Perseus rescuing
10826 Andromeda from the sea-monster or whale.  Where did Guido get the
10827 model of such a strange creature as that?  Nor does Hogarth, in
10828 painting the same scene in his own "Perseus Descending," make out one
10829 whit better.  The huge corpulence of that Hogarthian monster
10830 undulates on the surface, scarcely drawing one inch of water.  It has
10831 a sort of howdah on its back, and its distended tusked mouth into
10832 which the billows are rolling, might be taken for the Traitors' Gate
10833 leading from the Thames by water into the Tower.  Then, there are the
10834 Prodromus whales of old Scotch Sibbald, and Jonah's whale, as
10835 depicted in the prints of old Bibles and the cuts of old primers.
10836 What shall be said of these?  As for the book-binder's whale winding
10837 like a vine-stalk round the stock of a descending anchor--as stamped
10838 and gilded on the backs and title-pages of many books both old and
10839 new--that is a very picturesque but purely fabulous creature,
10840 imitated, I take it, from the like figures on antique vases.  Though
10841 universally denominated a dolphin, I nevertheless call this
10842 book-binder's fish an attempt at a whale; because it was so intended
10843 when the device was first introduced.  It was introduced by an old
10844 Italian publisher somewhere about the 15th century, during the
10845 Revival of Learning; and in those days, and even down to a
10846 comparatively late period, dolphins were popularly supposed to be a
10847 species of the Leviathan.
10848 
10849 In the vignettes and other embellishments of some ancient books you
10850 will at times meet with very curious touches at the whale, where all
10851 manner of spouts, jets d'eau, hot springs and cold, Saratoga and
10852 Baden-Baden, come bubbling up from his unexhausted brain.  In the
10853 title-page of the original edition of the "Advancement of Learning"
10854 you will find some curious whales.
10855 
10856 But quitting all these unprofessional attempts, let us glance at
10857 those pictures of leviathan purporting to be sober, scientific
10858 delineations, by those who know.  In old Harris's collection of
10859 voyages there are some plates of whales extracted from a Dutch book
10860 of voyages, A.D. 1671, entitled "A Whaling Voyage to Spitzbergen in
10861 the ship Jonas in the Whale, Peter Peterson of Friesland, master."
10862 In one of those plates the whales, like great rafts of logs, are
10863 represented lying among ice-isles, with white bears running over
10864 their living backs.  In another plate, the prodigious blunder is made
10865 of representing the whale with perpendicular flukes.
10866 
10867 Then again, there is an imposing quarto, written by one Captain
10868 Colnett, a Post Captain in the English navy, entitled "A Voyage round
10869 Cape Horn into the South Seas, for the purpose of extending the
10870 Spermaceti Whale Fisheries."  In this book is an outline purporting
10871 to be a "Picture of a Physeter or Spermaceti whale, drawn by scale
10872 from one killed on the coast of Mexico, August, 1793, and hoisted on
10873 deck."  I doubt not the captain had this veracious picture taken for
10874 the benefit of his marines.  To mention but one thing about it, let
10875 me say that it has an eye which applied, according to the
10876 accompanying scale, to a full grown sperm whale, would make the eye
10877 of that whale a bow-window some five feet long.  Ah, my gallant
10878 captain, why did ye not give us Jonah looking out of that eye!
10879 
10880 Nor are the most conscientious compilations of Natural History for
10881 the benefit of the young and tender, free from the same heinousness
10882 of mistake.  Look at that popular work "Goldsmith's Animated Nature."
10883 In the abridged London edition of 1807, there are plates of an
10884 alleged "whale" and a "narwhale."  I do not wish to seem inelegant,
10885 but this unsightly whale looks much like an amputated sow; and, as
10886 for the narwhale, one glimpse at it is enough to amaze one, that in
10887 this nineteenth century such a hippogriff could be palmed for genuine
10888 upon any intelligent public of schoolboys.
10889 
10890 Then, again, in 1825, Bernard Germain, Count de Lacepede, a great
10891 naturalist, published a scientific systemized whale book, wherein are
10892 several pictures of the different species of the Leviathan.  All
10893 these are not only incorrect, but the picture of the Mysticetus or
10894 Greenland whale (that is to say, the Right whale), even Scoresby, a
10895 long experienced man as touching that species, declares not to have
10896 its counterpart in nature.
10897 
10898 But the placing of the cap-sheaf to all this blundering business was
10899 reserved for the scientific Frederick Cuvier, brother to the famous
10900 Baron.  In 1836, he published a Natural History of Whales, in which
10901 he gives what he calls a picture of the Sperm Whale.  Before showing
10902 that picture to any Nantucketer, you had best provide for your
10903 summary retreat from Nantucket.  In a word, Frederick Cuvier's Sperm
10904 Whale is not a Sperm Whale, but a squash.  Of course, he never had
10905 the benefit of a whaling voyage (such men seldom have), but whence he
10906 derived that picture, who can tell?  Perhaps he got it as his
10907 scientific predecessor in the same field, Desmarest, got one of his
10908 authentic abortions; that is, from a Chinese drawing.  And what sort
10909 of lively lads with the pencil those Chinese are, many queer cups and
10910 saucers inform us.
10911 
10912 As for the sign-painters' whales seen in the streets hanging over the
10913 shops of oil-dealers, what shall be said of them?  They are generally
10914 Richard III. whales, with dromedary humps, and very savage;
10915 breakfasting on three or four sailor tarts, that is whaleboats full
10916 of mariners: their deformities floundering in seas of blood and blue
10917 paint.
10918 
10919 But these manifold mistakes in depicting the whale are not so very
10920 surprising after all.  Consider!  Most of the scientific drawings
10921 have been taken from the stranded fish; and these are about as
10922 correct as a drawing of a wrecked ship, with broken back, would
10923 correctly represent the noble animal itself in all its undashed pride
10924 of hull and spars.  Though elephants have stood for their
10925 full-lengths, the living Leviathan has never yet fairly floated
10926 himself for his portrait.  The living whale, in his full majesty and
10927 significance, is only to be seen at sea in unfathomable waters; and
10928 afloat the vast bulk of him is out of sight, like a launched
10929 line-of-battle ship; and out of that element it is a thing eternally
10930 impossible for mortal man to hoist him bodily into the air, so as to
10931 preserve all his mighty swells and undulations.  And, not to speak of
10932 the highly presumable difference of contour between a young sucking
10933 whale and a full-grown Platonian Leviathan; yet, even in the case of
10934 one of those young sucking whales hoisted to a ship's deck, such is
10935 then the outlandish, eel-like, limbered, varying shape of him, that
10936 his precise expression the devil himself could not catch.
10937 
10938 But it may be fancied, that from the naked skeleton of the stranded
10939 whale, accurate hints may be derived touching his true form.  Not at
10940 all.  For it is one of the more curious things about this Leviathan,
10941 that his skeleton gives very little idea of his general shape.
10942 Though Jeremy Bentham's skeleton, which hangs for candelabra in the
10943 library of one of his executors, correctly conveys the idea of a
10944 burly-browed utilitarian old gentleman, with all Jeremy's other
10945 leading personal characteristics; yet nothing of this kind could be
10946 inferred from any leviathan's articulated bones.  In fact, as the
