11457 The whale-line is only two-thirds of an inch in thickness.  At first
11458 sight, you would not think it so strong as it really is.  By
11459 experiment its one and fifty yarns will each suspend a weight of one
11460 hundred and twenty pounds; so that the whole rope will bear a strain
11461 nearly equal to three tons.  In length, the common sperm whale-line
11462 measures something over two hundred fathoms.  Towards the stern of
11463 the boat it is spirally coiled away in the tub, not like the
11464 worm-pipe of a still though, but so as to form one round,
11465 cheese-shaped mass of densely bedded "sheaves," or layers of
11466 concentric spiralizations, without any hollow but the "heart," or
11467 minute vertical tube formed at the axis of the cheese.  As the least
11468 tangle or kink in the coiling would, in running out, infallibly take
11469 somebody's arm, leg, or entire body off, the utmost precaution is
11470 used in stowing the line in its tub.  Some harpooneers will consume
11471 almost an entire morning in this business, carrying the line high
11472 aloft and then reeving it downwards through a block towards the tub,
11473 so as in the act of coiling to free it from all possible wrinkles and
11474 twists.
11475 
11476 In the English boats two tubs are used instead of one; the same line
11477 being continuously coiled in both tubs.  There is some advantage in
11478 this; because these twin-tubs being so small they fit more readily
11479 into the boat, and do not strain it so much; whereas, the American
11480 tub, nearly three feet in diameter and of proportionate depth, makes
11481 a rather bulky freight for a craft whose planks are but one half-inch
11482 in thickness; for the bottom of the whale-boat is like critical ice,
11483 which will bear up a considerable distributed weight, but not very
11484 much of a concentrated one.  When the painted canvas cover is clapped
11485 on the American line-tub, the boat looks as if it were pulling off
11486 with a prodigious great wedding-cake to present to the whales.
11487 
11488 Both ends of the line are exposed; the lower end terminating in an
11489 eye-splice or loop coming up from the bottom against the side of the
11490 tub, and hanging over its edge completely disengaged from everything.
11491 This arrangement of the lower end is necessary on two accounts.
11492 First: In order to facilitate the fastening to it of an additional
11493 line from a neighboring boat, in case the stricken whale should sound
11494 so deep as to threaten to carry off the entire line originally
11495 attached to the harpoon.  In these instances, the whale of course is
11496 shifted like a mug of ale, as it were, from the one boat to the
11497 other; though the first boat always hovers at hand to assist its
11498 consort.  Second: This arrangement is indispensable for common
11499 safety's sake; for were the lower end of the line in any way attached
11500 to the boat, and were the whale then to run the line out to the end
11501 almost in a single, smoking minute as he sometimes does, he would not
11502 stop there, for the doomed boat would infallibly be dragged down
11503 after him into the profundity of the sea; and in that case no
11504 town-crier would ever find her again.
11505 
11506 Before lowering the boat for the chase, the upper end of the line is
11507 taken aft from the tub, and passing round the loggerhead there, is
11508 again carried forward the entire length of the boat, resting
11509 crosswise upon the loom or handle of every man's oar, so that it jogs
11510 against his wrist in rowing; and also passing between the men, as
11511 they alternately sit at the opposite gunwales, to the leaded chocks
11512 or grooves in the extreme pointed prow of the boat, where a wooden
11513 pin or skewer the size of a common quill, prevents it from slipping
11514 out.  From the chocks it hangs in a slight festoon over the bows, and
11515 is then passed inside the boat again; and some ten or twenty fathoms
11516 (called box-line) being coiled upon the box in the bows, it continues
