11519 with the harpoon; but previous to that connexion, the short-warp goes
11520 through sundry mystifications too tedious to detail.
11521 
11522 Thus the whale-line folds the whole boat in its complicated coils,
11523 twisting and writhing around it in almost every direction.  All the
11524 oarsmen are involved in its perilous contortions; so that to the
11525 timid eye of the landsman, they seem as Indian jugglers, with the
11526 deadliest snakes sportively festooning their limbs.  Nor can any son
11527 of mortal woman, for the first time, seat himself amid those hempen
11528 intricacies, and while straining his utmost at the oar, bethink him
11529 that at any unknown instant the harpoon may be darted, and all these
11530 horrible contortions be put in play like ringed lightnings; he cannot
11531 be thus circumstanced without a shudder that makes the very marrow in
11532 his bones to quiver in him like a shaken jelly.  Yet habit--strange
11533 thing! what cannot habit accomplish?--Gayer sallies, more merry
11534 mirth, better jokes, and brighter repartees, you never heard over
11535 your mahogany, than you will hear over the half-inch white cedar of
11536 the whale-boat, when thus hung in hangman's nooses; and, like the six
11537 burghers of Calais before King Edward, the six men composing the crew
11538 pull into the jaws of death, with a halter around every neck, as you
11539 may say.
11540 
11541 Perhaps a very little thought will now enable you to account for
11542 those repeated whaling disasters--some few of which are casually
11543 chronicled--of this man or that man being taken out of the boat by
11544 the line, and lost.  For, when the line is darting out, to be seated
11545 then in the boat, is like being seated in the midst of the manifold
11546 whizzings of a steam-engine in full play, when every flying beam, and
11547 shaft, and wheel, is grazing you.  It is worse; for you cannot sit
11548 motionless in the heart of these perils, because the boat is rocking
11549 like a cradle, and you are pitched one way and the other, without the
11550 slightest warning; and only by a certain self-adjusting buoyancy and
11551 simultaneousness of volition and action, can you escape being made a
11552 Mazeppa of, and run away with where the all-seeing sun himself could
11553 never pierce you out.
11554 
11555 Again: as the profound calm which only apparently precedes and
11556 prophesies of the storm, is perhaps more awful than the storm itself;
11557 for, indeed, the calm is but the wrapper and envelope of the storm;
11558 and contains it in itself, as the seemingly harmless rifle holds the
11559 fatal powder, and the ball, and the explosion; so the graceful repose
11560 of the line, as it silently serpentines about the oarsmen before
11561 being brought into actual play--this is a thing which carries more of
11562 true terror than any other aspect of this dangerous affair.  But why
11563 say more?  All men live enveloped in whale-lines.  All are born with
11564 halters round their necks; but it is only when caught in the swift,
11565 sudden turn of death, that mortals realize the silent, subtle,
11566 ever-present perils of life.  And if you be a philosopher, though
11567 seated in the whale-boat, you would not at heart feel one whit more
11568 of terror, than though seated before your evening fire with a poker,
11569 and not a harpoon, by your side.
