11793 
11794 According to the invariable usage of the fishery, the whale-boat
11795 pushes off from the ship, with the headsman or whale-killer as
11796 temporary steersman, and the harpooneer or whale-fastener pulling the
11797 foremost oar, the one known as the harpooneer-oar.  Now it needs a
11798 strong, nervous arm to strike the first iron into the fish; for
11799 often, in what is called a long dart, the heavy implement has to be
11800 flung to the distance of twenty or thirty feet.  But however
11801 prolonged and exhausting the chase, the harpooneer is expected to
11802 pull his oar meanwhile to the uttermost; indeed, he is expected to
11803 set an example of superhuman activity to the rest, not only by
11804 incredible rowing, but by repeated loud and intrepid exclamations;
11805 and what it is to keep shouting at the top of one's compass, while
11806 all the other muscles are strained and half started--what that is
11807 none know but those who have tried it.  For one, I cannot bawl very
11808 heartily and work very recklessly at one and the same time.  In this
11809 straining, bawling state, then, with his back to the fish, all at
11810 once the exhausted harpooneer hears the exciting cry--"Stand up, and
11811 give it to him!"  He now has to drop and secure his oar, turn round
11812 on his centre half way, seize his harpoon from the crotch, and with
11813 what little strength may remain, he essays to pitch it somehow into
11814 the whale.  No wonder, taking the whole fleet of whalemen in a body,
11815 that out of fifty fair chances for a dart, not five are successful;
11816 no wonder that so many hapless harpooneers are madly cursed and
11817 disrated; no wonder that some of them actually burst their
11818 blood-vessels in the boat; no wonder that some sperm whalemen are
11819 absent four years with four barrels; no wonder that to many ship
11820 owners, whaling is but a losing concern; for it is the harpooneer
11821 that makes the voyage, and if you take the breath out of his body how
11822 can you expect to find it there when most wanted!
11823 
11824 Again, if the dart be successful, then at the second critical
11825 instant, that is, when the whale starts to run, the boatheader and
11826 harpooneer likewise start to running fore and aft, to the imminent
11827 jeopardy of themselves and every one else.  It is then they change
11828 places; and the headsman, the chief officer of the little craft,
11829 takes his proper station in the bows of the boat.
