12247 CHAPTER 65
12248 
12249 The Whale as a Dish.
12250 
12251 
12252 That mortal man should feed upon the creature that feeds his lamp,
12253 and, like Stubb, eat him by his own light, as you may say; this seems
12254 so outlandish a thing that one must needs go a little into the
12255 history and philosophy of it.
12256 
12257 It is upon record, that three centuries ago the tongue of the Right
12258 Whale was esteemed a great delicacy in France, and commanded large
12259 prices there.  Also, that in Henry VIIIth's time, a certain cook of
12260 the court obtained a handsome reward for inventing an admirable sauce
12261 to be eaten with barbacued porpoises, which, you remember, are a
12262 species of whale.  Porpoises, indeed, are to this day considered fine
12263 eating.  The meat is made into balls about the size of billiard
12264 balls, and being well seasoned and spiced might be taken for
12265 turtle-balls or veal balls.  The old monks of Dunfermline were very
12266 fond of them.  They had a great porpoise grant from the crown.
12267 
12268 The fact is, that among his hunters at least, the whale would by all
12269 hands be considered a noble dish, were there not so much of him; but
12270 when you come to sit down before a meat-pie nearly one hundred feet
12271 long, it takes away your appetite.  Only the most unprejudiced of men
12272 like Stubb, nowadays partake of cooked whales; but the Esquimaux are
12273 not so fastidious.  We all know how they live upon whales, and have
12274 rare old vintages of prime old train oil.  Zogranda, one of their
12275 most famous doctors, recommends strips of blubber for infants, as
12276 being exceedingly juicy and nourishing.  And this reminds me that
12277 certain Englishmen, who long ago were accidentally left in Greenland
12278 by a whaling vessel--that these men actually lived for several months
12279 on the mouldy scraps of whales which had been left ashore after
12280 trying out the blubber.  Among the Dutch whalemen these scraps are
12281 called "fritters"; which, indeed, they greatly resemble, being brown
12282 and crisp, and smelling something like old Amsterdam housewives'
12283 dough-nuts or oly-cooks, when fresh.  They have such an eatable look
12284 that the most self-denying stranger can hardly keep his hands off.
12285 
12286 But what further depreciates the whale as a civilized dish, is his
12287 exceeding richness.  He is the great prize ox of the sea, too fat to
12288 be delicately good.  Look at his hump, which would be as fine eating
12289 as the buffalo's (which is esteemed a rare dish), were it not such a
12290 solid pyramid of fat.  But the spermaceti itself, how bland and
12291 creamy that is; like the transparent, half-jellied, white meat of a
12292 cocoanut in the third month of its growth, yet far too rich to supply
12293 a substitute for butter.  Nevertheless, many whalemen have a method
12294 of absorbing it into some other substance, and then partaking of it.
12295 In the long try watches of the night it is a common thing for the
12296 seamen to dip their ship-biscuit into the huge oil-pots and let them
12297 fry there awhile.  Many a good supper have I thus made.
12298 
12299 In the case of a small Sperm Whale the brains are accounted a fine
12300 dish.  The casket of the skull is broken into with an axe, and the
12301 two plump, whitish lobes being withdrawn (precisely resembling two
12302 large puddings), they are then mixed with flour, and cooked into a
12303 most delectable mess, in flavor somewhat resembling calves' head,
12304 which is quite a dish among some epicures; and every one knows that
12305 some young bucks among the epicures, by continually dining upon
12306 calves' brains, by and by get to have a little brains of their own,
12307 so as to be able to tell a calf's head from their own heads; which,
12308 indeed, requires uncommon discrimination.  And that is the reason why
12309 a young buck with an intelligent looking calf's head before him, is
12310 somehow one of the saddest sights you can see.  The head looks a sort
12311 of reproachfully at him, with an "Et tu Brute!" expression.
12312 
12313 It is not, perhaps, entirely because the whale is so excessively
12314 unctuous that landsmen seem to regard the eating of him with
12315 abhorrence; that appears to result, in some way, from the
12316 consideration before mentioned: i.e. that a man should eat a newly
12317 murdered thing of the sea, and eat it too by its own light.  But no
