12349 When in the Southern Fishery, a captured Sperm Whale, after long and
12350 weary toil, is brought alongside late at night, it is not, as a
12351 general thing at least, customary to proceed at once to the business
12352 of cutting him in.  For that business is an exceedingly laborious
12353 one; is not very soon completed; and requires all hands to set about
12354 it.  Therefore, the common usage is to take in all sail; lash the
12355 helm a'lee; and then send every one below to his hammock till
12356 daylight, with the reservation that, until that time, anchor-watches
12357 shall be kept; that is, two and two for an hour, each couple, the
12358 crew in rotation shall mount the deck to see that all goes well.
12359 
12360 But sometimes, especially upon the Line in the Pacific, this plan
12361 will not answer at all; because such incalculable hosts of sharks
12362 gather round the moored carcase, that were he left so for six hours,
12363 say, on a stretch, little more than the skeleton would be visible by
12364 morning.  In most other parts of the ocean, however, where these fish
12365 do not so largely abound, their wondrous voracity can be at times
12366 considerably diminished, by vigorously stirring them up with sharp
12367 whaling-spades, a procedure notwithstanding, which, in some
12368 instances, only seems to tickle them into still greater activity.
12369 But it was not thus in the present case with the Pequod's sharks;
12370 though, to be sure, any man unaccustomed to such sights, to have
12371 looked over her side that night, would have almost thought the whole
12372 round sea was one huge cheese, and those sharks the maggots in it.
