14448 But the monster's run was a brief one.  Giving a sudden gasp, he
14449 tumultuously sounded.  With a grating rush, the three lines flew
14450 round the loggerheads with such a force as to gouge deep grooves in
14451 them; while so fearful were the harpooneers that this rapid sounding
14452 would soon exhaust the lines, that using all their dexterous might,
14453 they caught repeated smoking turns with the rope to hold on; till at
14454 last--owing to the perpendicular strain from the lead-lined chocks of
14455 the boats, whence the three ropes went straight down into the
14456 blue--the gunwales of the bows were almost even with the water, while
14457 the three sterns tilted high in the air.  And the whale soon ceasing
14458 to sound, for some time they remained in that attitude, fearful of
14459 expending more line, though the position was a little ticklish.  But
14460 though boats have been taken down and lost in this way, yet it is
14461 this "holding on," as it is called; this hooking up by the sharp
14462 barbs of his live flesh from the back; this it is that often torments
14463 the Leviathan into soon rising again to meet the sharp lance of his
14464 foes.  Yet not to speak of the peril of the thing, it is to be
14465 doubted whether this course is always the best; for it is but
14466 reasonable to presume, that the longer the stricken whale stays under
14467 water, the more he is exhausted.  Because, owing to the enormous
14468 surface of him--in a full grown sperm whale something less than 2000
14469 square feet--the pressure of the water is immense.  We all know what
14470 an astonishing atmospheric weight we ourselves stand up under; even
14471 here, above-ground, in the air; how vast, then, the burden of a
14472 whale, bearing on his back a column of two hundred fathoms of ocean!
14473 It must at least equal the weight of fifty atmospheres.  One whaleman
14474 has estimated it at the weight of twenty line-of-battle ships, with
14475 all their guns, and stores, and men on board.
14476 
14477 As the three boats lay there on that gently rolling sea, gazing down
14478 into its eternal blue noon; and as not a single groan or cry of any
14479 sort, nay, not so much as a ripple or a bubble came up from its
14480 depths; what landsman would have thought, that beneath all that
14481 silence and placidity, the utmost monster of the seas was writhing
14482 and wrenching in agony!  Not eight inches of perpendicular rope were
14483 visible at the bows.  Seems it credible that by three such thin
14484 threads the great Leviathan was suspended like the big weight to an
14485 eight day clock.  Suspended? and to what?  To three bits of board.
14486 Is this the creature of whom it was once so triumphantly said--"Canst
14487 thou fill his skin with barbed irons? or his head with fish-spears?
14488 The sword of him that layeth at him cannot hold, the spear, the dart,
14489 nor the habergeon: he esteemeth iron as straw; the arrow cannot make
14490 him flee; darts are counted as stubble; he laugheth at the shaking of
14491 a spear!"  This the creature? this he?  Oh! that unfulfilments should
14492 follow the prophets.  For with the strength of a thousand thighs in
14493 his tail, Leviathan had run his head under the mountains of the sea,
14494 to hide him from the Pequod's fish-spears!
14495 
14496 In that sloping afternoon sunlight, the shadows that the three boats
14497 sent down beneath the surface, must have been long enough and broad
14498 enough to shade half Xerxes' army.  Who can tell how appalling to the
14499 wounded whale must have been such huge phantoms flitting over his
14500 head!
14501 
14502 "Stand by, men; he stirs," cried Starbuck, as the three lines
14503 suddenly vibrated in the water, distinctly conducting upwards to
14504 them, as by magnetic wires, the life and death throbs of the whale,
14505 so that every oarsman felt them in his seat.  The next moment,
14506 relieved in great part from the downward strain at the bows, the
14507 boats gave a sudden bounce upwards, as a small icefield will, when a
14508 dense herd of white bears are scared from it into the sea.
14509 
14510 "Haul in!  Haul in!" cried Starbuck again; "he's rising."
14511 
14512 The lines, of which, hardly an instant before, not one hand's breadth
14513 could have been gained, were now in long quick coils flung back all
14514 dripping into the boats, and soon the whale broke water within two
14515 ship's lengths of the hunters.
14516 
14517 His motions plainly denoted his extreme exhaustion.  In most land
14518 animals there are certain valves or flood-gates in many of their
14519 veins, whereby when wounded, the blood is in some degree at least
14520 instantly shut off in certain directions.  Not so with the whale; one
14521 of whose peculiarities it is to have an entire non-valvular structure
14522 of the blood-vessels, so that when pierced even by so small a point
14523 as a harpoon, a deadly drain is at once begun upon his whole
14524 arterial system; and when this is heightened by the extraordinary
14525 pressure of water at a great distance below the surface, his life may
14526 be said to pour from him in incessant streams.  Yet so vast is the
14527 quantity of blood in him, and so distant and numerous its interior
14528 fountains, that he will keep thus bleeding and bleeding for a
14529 considerable period; even as in a drought a river will flow, whose
14530 source is in the well-springs of far-off and undiscernible hills.
14531 Even now, when the boats pulled upon this whale, and perilously drew
14532 over his swaying flukes, and the lances were darted into him, they
14533 were followed by steady jets from the new made wound, which kept
14534 continually playing, while the natural spout-hole in his head was
14535 only at intervals, however rapid, sending its affrighted moisture
14536 into the air.  From this last vent no blood yet came, because no
14537 vital part of him had thus far been struck.  His life, as they
14538 significantly call it, was untouched.
14539 
14540 As the boats now more closely surrounded him, the whole upper part of
14541 his form, with much of it that is ordinarily submerged, was plainly
14542 revealed.  His eyes, or rather the places where his eyes had been,
14543 were beheld.  As strange misgrown masses gather in the knot-holes of
14544 the noblest oaks when prostrate, so from the points which the whale's
14545 eyes had once occupied, now protruded blind bulbs, horribly pitiable
14546 to see.  But pity there was none.  For all his old age, and his one
14547 arm, and his blind eyes, he must die the death and be murdered, in
14548 order to light the gay bridals and other merry-makings of men, and
14549 also to illuminate the solemn churches that preach unconditional
14550 inoffensiveness by all to all.  Still rolling in his blood, at last
14551 he partially disclosed a strangely discoloured bunch or protuberance,
14552 the size of a bushel, low down on the flank.
14553 
14554 "A nice spot," cried Flask; "just let me prick him there once."
14555 
14556 "Avast!" cried Starbuck, "there's no need of that!"
14557 
14558 But humane Starbuck was too late.  At the instant of the dart an
14559 ulcerous jet shot from this cruel wound, and goaded by it into more
14560 than sufferable anguish, the whale now spouting thick blood, with
14561 swift fury blindly darted at the craft, bespattering them and their
14562 glorying crews all over with showers of gore, capsizing Flask's boat
14563 and marring the bows.  It was his death stroke.  For, by this time,
14564 so spent was he by loss of blood, that he helplessly rolled away from
14565 the wreck he had made; lay panting on his side, impotently flapped
14566 with his stumped fin, then over and over slowly revolved like a
14567 waning world; turned up the white secrets of his belly; lay like a
14568 log, and died.  It was most piteous, that last expiring spout.  As
14569 when by unseen hands the water is gradually drawn off from some
14570 mighty fountain, and with half-stifled melancholy gurglings the
14571 spray-column lowers and lowers to the ground--so the last long dying
14572 spout of the whale.
14573 
14574 Soon, while the crews were awaiting the arrival of the ship, the body
14575 showed symptoms of sinking with all its treasures unrifled.
14576 Immediately, by Starbuck's orders, lines were secured to it at
14577 different points, so that ere long every boat was a buoy; the sunken
14578 whale being suspended a few inches beneath them by the cords.  By
14579 very heedful management, when the ship drew nigh, the whale was
14580 transferred to her side, and was strongly secured there by the
14581 stiffest fluke-chains, for it was plain that unless artificially
14582 upheld, the body would at once sink to the bottom.
14583 
14584 It so chanced that almost upon first cutting into him with the
14585 spade, the entire length of a corroded harpoon was found imbedded in
14586 his flesh, on the lower part of the bunch before described.  But as
14587 the stumps of harpoons are frequently found in the dead bodies of
14588 captured whales, with the flesh perfectly healed around them, and no
14589 prominence of any kind to denote their place; therefore, there must
14590 needs have been some other unknown reason in the present case fully
14591 to account for the ulceration alluded to.  But still more curious was
14592 the fact of a lance-head of stone being found in him, not far from
14593 the buried iron, the flesh perfectly firm about it.  Who had darted
14594 that stone lance?  And when?  It might have been darted by some Nor'
14595 West Indian long before America was discovered.
14596 
14597 What other marvels might have been rummaged out of this monstrous
14598 cabinet there is no telling.  But a sudden stop was put to further
14599 discoveries, by the ship's being unprecedentedly dragged over
14600 sideways to the sea, owing to the body's immensely increasing
14601 tendency to sink.  However, Starbuck, who had the ordering of
14602 affairs, hung on to it to the last; hung on to it so resolutely,
14603 indeed, that when at length the ship would have been capsized, if
14604 still persisting in locking arms with the body; then, when the
14605 command was given to break clear from it, such was the immovable
14606 strain upon the timber-heads to which the fluke-chains and cables
14607 were fastened, that it was impossible to cast them off.  Meantime
14608 everything in the Pequod was aslant.  To cross to the other side of
14609 the deck was like walking up the steep gabled roof of a house.  The
14610 ship groaned and gasped.  Many of the ivory inlayings of her bulwarks
14611 and cabins were started from their places, by the unnatural
14612 dislocation.  In vain handspikes and crows were brought to bear upon
14613 the immovable fluke-chains, to pry them adrift from the timberheads;
14614 and so low had the whale now settled that the submerged ends could
14615 not be at all approached, while every moment whole tons of
14616 ponderosity seemed added to the sinking bulk, and the ship seemed on
14617 the point of going over.
14618 
14619 "Hold on, hold on, won't ye?" cried Stubb to the body, "don't be in
14620 such a devil of a hurry to sink!  By thunder, men, we must do
14621 something or go for it.  No use prying there; avast, I say with your
14622 handspikes, and run one of ye for a prayer book and a pen-knife, and
14623 cut the big chains."
14624 
14625 "Knife?  Aye, aye," cried Queequeg, and seizing the carpenter's heavy
14626 hatchet, he leaned out of a porthole, and steel to iron, began
14627 slashing at the largest fluke-chains.  But a few strokes, full of
14628 sparks, were given, when the exceeding strain effected the rest.
14629 With a terrific snap, every fastening went adrift; the ship righted,
14630 the carcase sank.
14631 
14632 Now, this occasional inevitable sinking of the recently killed Sperm
14633 Whale is a very curious thing; nor has any fisherman yet adequately
14634 accounted for it.  Usually the dead Sperm Whale floats with great
14635 buoyancy, with its side or belly considerably elevated above the
14636 surface.  If the only whales that thus sank were old, meagre, and
14637 broken-hearted creatures, their pads of lard diminished and all their
14638 bones heavy and rheumatic; then you might with some reason assert
14639 that this sinking is caused by an uncommon specific gravity in the
14640 fish so sinking, consequent upon this absence of buoyant matter in
14641 him.  But it is not so.  For young whales, in the highest health, and
14642 swelling with noble aspirations, prematurely cut off in the warm
14643 flush and May of life, with all their panting lard about them; even
14644 these brawny, buoyant heroes do sometimes sink.
14645 
14646 Be it said, however, that the Sperm Whale is far less liable to this
14647 accident than any other species.  Where one of that sort go down,
14648 twenty Right Whales do.  This difference in the species is no doubt
14649 imputable in no small degree to the greater quantity of bone in the
14650 Right Whale; his Venetian blinds alone sometimes weighing more than a
14651 ton; from this incumbrance the Sperm Whale is wholly free.  But there
14652 are instances where, after the lapse of many hours or several days,
14653 the sunken whale again rises, more buoyant than in life.  But the
14654 reason of this is obvious.  Gases are generated in him; he swells to
14655 a prodigious magnitude; becomes a sort of animal balloon.  A
14656 line-of-battle ship could hardly keep him under then.  In the Shore
14657 Whaling, on soundings, among the Bays of New Zealand, when a Right
14658 Whale gives token of sinking, they fasten buoys to him, with plenty
14659 of rope; so that when the body has gone down, they know where to look
14660 for it when it shall have ascended again.
14661 
14662 It was not long after the sinking of the body that a cry was heard
14663 from the Pequod's mast-heads, announcing that the Jungfrau was again
14664 lowering her boats; though the only spout in sight was that of a
14665 Fin-Back, belonging to the species of uncapturable whales, because of
14666 its incredible power of swimming.  Nevertheless, the Fin-Back's spout
14667 is so similar to the Sperm Whale's, that by unskilful fishermen it is
14668 often mistaken for it.  And consequently Derick and all his host were
14669 now in valiant chase of this unnearable brute.  The Virgin crowding
14670 all sail, made after her four young keels, and thus they all
14671 disappeared far to leeward, still in bold, hopeful chase.
14672 
14673 Oh! many are the Fin-Backs, and many are the Dericks, my friend.
