14677 CHAPTER 82
14678 
14679 The Honour and Glory of Whaling.
14680 
14681 
14682 There are some enterprises in which a careful disorderliness is the
14683 true method.
14684 
14685 The more I dive into this matter of whaling, and push my researches
14686 up to the very spring-head of it so much the more am I impressed with
14687 its great honourableness and antiquity; and especially when I find so
14688 many great demi-gods and heroes, prophets of all sorts, who one way
14689 or other have shed distinction upon it, I am transported with the
14690 reflection that I myself belong, though but subordinately, to so
14691 emblazoned a fraternity.
14692 
14693 The gallant Perseus, a son of Jupiter, was the first whaleman; and to
14694 the eternal honour of our calling be it said, that the first whale
14695 attacked by our brotherhood was not killed with any sordid intent.
14696 Those were the knightly days of our profession, when we only bore
14697 arms to succor the distressed, and not to fill men's lamp-feeders.
14698 Every one knows the fine story of Perseus and Andromeda; how the
14699 lovely Andromeda, the daughter of a king, was tied to a rock on the
14700 sea-coast, and as Leviathan was in the very act of carrying her off,
14701 Perseus, the prince of whalemen, intrepidly advancing, harpooned the
14702 monster, and delivered and married the maid.  It was an admirable
14703 artistic exploit, rarely achieved by the best harpooneers of the
14704 present day; inasmuch as this Leviathan was slain at the very first
14705 dart.  And let no man doubt this Arkite story; for in the ancient
14706 Joppa, now Jaffa, on the Syrian coast, in one of the Pagan temples,
14707 there stood for many ages the vast skeleton of a whale, which the
14708 city's legends and all the inhabitants asserted to be the identical
14709 bones of the monster that Perseus slew.  When the Romans took Joppa,
14710 the same skeleton was carried to Italy in triumph.  What seems most
14711 singular and suggestively important in this story, is this: it was
14712 from Joppa that Jonah set sail.
14713 
14714 Akin to the adventure of Perseus and Andromeda--indeed, by some
14715 supposed to be indirectly derived from it--is that famous story of
14716 St. George and the Dragon; which dragon I maintain to have been a
14717 whale; for in many old chronicles whales and dragons are strangely
14718 jumbled together, and often stand for each other.  "Thou art as a
14719 lion of the waters, and as a dragon of the sea," saith Ezekiel;
14720 hereby, plainly meaning a whale; in truth, some versions of the Bible
14721 use that word itself.  Besides, it would much subtract from the glory
14722 of the exploit had St. George but encountered a crawling reptile of
14723 the land, instead of doing battle with the great monster of the deep.
14724 Any man may kill a snake, but only a Perseus, a St. George, a
14725 Coffin, have the heart in them to march boldly up to a whale.
14726 
14727 Let not the modern paintings of this scene mislead us; for though the
14728 creature encountered by that valiant whaleman of old is vaguely
14729 represented of a griffin-like shape, and though the battle is
14730 depicted on land and the saint on horseback, yet considering the
14731 great ignorance of those times, when the true form of the whale was
14732 unknown to artists; and considering that as in Perseus' case, St.
14733 George's whale might have crawled up out of the sea on the beach; and
14734 considering that the animal ridden by St. George might have been only
14735 a large seal, or sea-horse; bearing all this in mind, it will not
14736 appear altogether incompatible with the sacred legend and the
14737 ancientest draughts of the scene, to hold this so-called dragon no
14738 other than the great Leviathan himself.  In fact, placed before the
14739 strict and piercing truth, this whole story will fare like that fish,
14740 flesh, and fowl idol of the Philistines, Dagon by name; who being
14741 planted before the ark of Israel, his horse's head and both the palms
14742 of his hands fell off from him, and only the stump or fishy part of
14743 him remained.  Thus, then, one of our own noble stamp, even a
14744 whaleman, is the tutelary guardian of England; and by good rights, we
14745 harpooneers of Nantucket should be enrolled in the most noble order
14746 of St. George.  And therefore, let not the knights of that honourable
14747 company (none of whom, I venture to say, have ever had to do with a
14748 whale like their great patron), let them never eye a Nantucketer with
14749 disdain, since even in our woollen frocks and tarred trowsers we are
14750 much better entitled to St. George's decoration than they.
14751 
14752 Whether to admit Hercules among us or not, concerning this I long
14753 remained dubious: for though according to the Greek mythologies, that
14754 antique Crockett and Kit Carson--that brawny doer of rejoicing good
14755 deeds, was swallowed down and thrown up by a whale; still, whether
14756 that strictly makes a whaleman of him, that might be mooted.  It
14757 nowhere appears that he ever actually harpooned his fish, unless,
14758 indeed, from the inside.  Nevertheless, he may be deemed a sort of
14759 involuntary whaleman; at any rate the whale caught him, if he did not
14760 the whale.  I claim him for one of our clan.
14761 
14762 But, by the best contradictory authorities, this Grecian story of
14763 Hercules and the whale is considered to be derived from the still
14764 more ancient Hebrew story of Jonah and the whale; and vice versa;
14765 certainly they are very similar.  If I claim the demigod then, why
14766 not the prophet?
14767 
14768 Nor do heroes, saints, demigods, and prophets alone comprise the
14769 whole roll of our order.  Our grand master is still to be named; for
14770 like royal kings of old times, we find the head waters of our
14771 fraternity in nothing short of the great gods themselves.  That
14772 wondrous oriental story is now to be rehearsed from the Shaster,
14773 which gives us the dread Vishnoo, one of the three persons in the
14774 godhead of the Hindoos; gives us this divine Vishnoo himself for our
14775 Lord;--Vishnoo, who, by the first of his ten earthly incarnations,
14776 has for ever set apart and sanctified the whale.  When Brahma, or the
