15951 Fast-Fish and Loose-Fish.
15952 
15953 
15954 The allusion to the waif and waif-poles in the last chapter but one,
15955 necessitates some account of the laws and regulations of the whale
15956 fishery, of which the waif may be deemed the grand symbol and badge.
15957 
15958 It frequently happens that when several ships are cruising in
15959 company, a whale may be struck by one vessel, then escape, and be
15960 finally killed and captured by another vessel; and herein are
15961 indirectly comprised many minor contingencies, all partaking of this
15962 one grand feature.  For example,--after a weary and perilous chase
15963 and capture of a whale, the body may get loose from the ship by
15964 reason of a violent storm; and drifting far away to leeward, be
15965 retaken by a second whaler, who, in a calm, snugly tows it alongside,
15966 without risk of life or line.  Thus the most vexatious and violent
15967 disputes would often arise between the fishermen, were there not some
15968 written or unwritten, universal, undisputed law applicable to all
15969 cases.
15970 
15971 Perhaps the only formal whaling code authorized by legislative
15972 enactment, was that of Holland.  It was decreed by the States-General
15973 in A.D. 1695.  But though no other nation has ever had any written
15974 whaling law, yet the American fishermen have been their own
15975 legislators and lawyers in this matter.  They have provided a system
15976 which for terse comprehensiveness surpasses Justinian's Pandects and
15977 the By-laws of the Chinese Society for the Suppression of Meddling
15978 with other People's Business.  Yes; these laws might be engraven on a
15979 Queen Anne's forthing, or the barb of a harpoon, and worn round the
15980 neck, so small are they.
15981 
15982 I.  A Fast-Fish belongs to the party fast to it.
15983 
15984 II.  A Loose-Fish is fair game for anybody who can soonest catch it.
15985 
15986 But what plays the mischief with this masterly code is the admirable
15987 brevity of it, which necessitates a vast volume of commentaries to
15988 expound it.
15989 
15990 First: What is a Fast-Fish?  Alive or dead a fish is technically
15991 fast, when it is connected with an occupied ship or boat, by any
15992 medium at all controllable by the occupant or occupants,--a mast, an
15993 oar, a nine-inch cable, a telegraph wire, or a strand of cobweb, it
15994 is all the same.  Likewise a fish is technically fast when it bears a
15995 waif, or any other recognised symbol of possession; so long as the
15996 party waifing it plainly evince their ability at any time to take it
15997 alongside, as well as their intention so to do.
15998 
15999 These are scientific commentaries; but the commentaries of the
16000 whalemen themselves sometimes consist in hard words and harder
16001 knocks--the Coke-upon-Littleton of the fist.  True, among the more
16002 upright and honourable whalemen allowances are always made for
16003 peculiar cases, where it would be an outrageous moral injustice for
16004 one party to claim possession of a whale previously chased or killed
16005 by another party.  But others are by no means so scrupulous.
16006 
16007 Some fifty years ago there was a curious case of whale-trover
16008 litigated in England, wherein the plaintiffs set forth that after a
16009 hard chase of a whale in the Northern seas; and when indeed they (the
16010 plaintiffs) had succeeded in harpooning the fish; they were at last,
16011 through peril of their lives, obliged to forsake not only their
16012 lines, but their boat itself.  Ultimately the defendants (the crew of
16013 another ship) came up with the whale, struck, killed, seized, and
16014 finally appropriated it before the very eyes of the plaintiffs.  And
16015 when those defendants were remonstrated with, their captain snapped
16016 his fingers in the plaintiffs' teeth, and assured them that by way of
16017 doxology to the deed he had done, he would now retain their line,
16018 harpoons, and boat, which had remained attached to the whale at the
16019 time of the seizure.  Wherefore the plaintiffs now sued for the
16020 recovery of the value of their whale, line, harpoons, and boat.
16021 
16022 Mr. Erskine was counsel for the defendants; Lord Ellenborough was the
16023 judge.  In the course of the defence, the witty Erskine went on to
16024 illustrate his position, by alluding to a recent crim. con. case,
16025 wherein a gentleman, after in vain trying to bridle his wife's
16026 viciousness, had at last abandoned her upon the seas of life; but in
16027 the course of years, repenting of that step, he instituted an action
16028 to recover possession of her.  Erskine was on the other side; and he
16029 then supported it by saying, that though the gentleman had originally
16030 harpooned the lady, and had once had her fast, and only by reason of
16031 the great stress of her plunging viciousness, had at last abandoned
16032 her; yet abandon her he did, so that she became a loose-fish; and
16033 therefore when a subsequent gentleman re-harpooned her, the lady then
16034 became that subsequent gentleman's property, along with whatever
16035 harpoon might have been found sticking in her.
16036 
16037 Now in the present case Erskine contended that the examples of the
16038 whale and the lady were reciprocally illustrative of each other.
16039 
16040 These pleadings, and the counter pleadings, being duly heard, the
16041 very learned Judge in set terms decided, to wit,--That as for the
16042 boat, he awarded it to the plaintiffs, because they had merely
16043 abandoned it to save their lives; but that with regard to the
16044 controverted whale, harpoons, and line, they belonged to the
16045 defendants; the whale, because it was a Loose-Fish at the time of the
16046 final capture; and the harpoons and line because when the fish made
16047 off with them, it (the fish) acquired a property in those articles;
16048 and hence anybody who afterwards took the fish had a right to them.
16049 Now the defendants afterwards took the fish; ergo, the aforesaid
16050 articles were theirs.
