16521 Ambergris.
16522 
16523 
16524 Now this ambergris is a very curious substance, and so important as
16525 an article of commerce, that in 1791 a certain Nantucket-born Captain
16526 Coffin was examined at the bar of the English House of Commons on
16527 that subject.  For at that time, and indeed until a comparatively
16528 late day, the precise origin of ambergris remained, like amber
16529 itself, a problem to the learned.  Though the word ambergris is but
16530 the French compound for grey amber, yet the two substances are quite
16531 distinct.  For amber, though at times found on the sea-coast, is also
16532 dug up in some far inland soils, whereas ambergris is never found
16533 except upon the sea.  Besides, amber is a hard, transparent, brittle,
16534 odorless substance, used for mouth-pieces to pipes, for beads and
16535 ornaments; but ambergris is soft, waxy, and so highly fragrant and
16536 spicy, that it is largely used in perfumery, in pastiles, precious
16537 candles, hair-powders, and pomatum.  The Turks use it in cooking, and
16538 also carry it to Mecca, for the same purpose that frankincense is
16539 carried to St. Peter's in Rome.  Some wine merchants drop a few
16540 grains into claret, to flavor it.
16541 
16542 Who would think, then, that such fine ladies and gentlemen should
16543 regale themselves with an essence found in the inglorious bowels of a
16544 sick whale!  Yet so it is.  By some, ambergris is supposed to be the
16545 cause, and by others the effect, of the dyspepsia in the whale.  How
16546 to cure such a dyspepsia it were hard to say, unless by administering
16547 three or four boat loads of Brandreth's pills, and then running out
16548 of harm's way, as laborers do in blasting rocks.
16549 
16550 I have forgotten to say that there were found in this ambergris,
16551 certain hard, round, bony plates, which at first Stubb thought might
16552 be sailors' trowsers buttons; but it afterwards turned out that they
16553 were nothing more than pieces of small squid bones embalmed in that
16554 manner.
16555 
16556 Now that the incorruption of this most fragrant ambergris should be
16557 found in the heart of such decay; is this nothing?  Bethink thee of
16558 that saying of St. Paul in Corinthians, about corruption and
16559 incorruption; how that we are sown in dishonour, but raised in glory.
16560 And likewise call to mind that saying of Paracelsus about what it is
16561 that maketh the best musk.  Also forget not the strange fact that of
16562 all things of ill-savor, Cologne-water, in its rudimental
16563 manufacturing stages, is the worst.
16564 
16565 I should like to conclude the chapter with the above appeal, but
16566 cannot, owing to my anxiety to repel a charge often made against
16567 whalemen, and which, in the estimation of some already biased minds,
16568 might be considered as indirectly substantiated by what has been said
16569 of the Frenchman's two whales.  Elsewhere in this volume the
16570 slanderous aspersion has been disproved, that the vocation of whaling
16571 is throughout a slatternly, untidy business.  But there is another
16572 thing to rebut.  They hint that all whales always smell bad.  Now how
