16696 he suspended its sharp edge over the line, and turning towards Stubb,
16697 exclaimed interrogatively, "Cut?"  Meantime Pip's blue, choked face
16698 plainly looked, Do, for God's sake!  All passed in a flash.  In less
16699 than half a minute, this entire thing happened.
16700 
16701 "Damn him, cut!" roared Stubb; and so the whale was lost and Pip was
16702 saved.
16703 
16704 So soon as he recovered himself, the poor little negro was assailed
16705 by yells and execrations from the crew.  Tranquilly permitting these
16706 irregular cursings to evaporate, Stubb then in a plain,
16707 business-like, but still half humorous manner, cursed Pip officially;
16708 and that done, unofficially gave him much wholesome advice.  The
16709 substance was, Never jump from a boat, Pip, except--but all the rest
16710 was indefinite, as the soundest advice ever is.  Now, in general,
16711 STICK TO THE BOAT, is your true motto in whaling; but cases will
16712 sometimes happen when LEAP FROM THE BOAT, is still better.  Moreover,
16713 as if perceiving at last that if he should give undiluted
16714 conscientious advice to Pip, he would be leaving him too wide a
16715 margin to jump in for the future; Stubb suddenly dropped all advice,
16716 and concluded with a peremptory command, "Stick to the boat, Pip, or
16717 by the Lord, I won't pick you up if you jump; mind that.  We can't
16718 afford to lose whales by the likes of you; a whale would sell for
16719 thirty times what you would, Pip, in Alabama.  Bear that in mind, and
16720 don't jump any more."  Hereby perhaps Stubb indirectly hinted, that
16721 though man loved his fellow, yet man is a money-making animal, which
16722 propensity too often interferes with his benevolence.
16723 
16724 But we are all in the hands of the Gods; and Pip jumped again.  It
16725 was under very similar circumstances to the first performance; but
16726 this time he did not breast out the line; and hence, when the whale
16727 started to run, Pip was left behind on the sea, like a hurried
16728 traveller's trunk.  Alas!  Stubb was but too true to his word.  It
16729 was a beautiful, bounteous, blue day; the spangled sea calm and
16730 cool, and flatly stretching away, all round, to the horizon, like
16731 gold-beater's skin hammered out to the extremest.  Bobbing up and
16732 down in that sea, Pip's ebon head showed like a head of cloves.  No
16733 boat-knife was lifted when he fell so rapidly astern.  Stubb's
16734 inexorable back was turned upon him; and the whale was winged.  In
16735 three minutes, a whole mile of shoreless ocean was between Pip and
16736 Stubb.  Out from the centre of the sea, poor Pip turned his crisp,
16737 curling, black head to the sun, another lonely castaway, though the
16738 loftiest and the brightest.
16739 
16740 Now, in calm weather, to swim in the open ocean is as easy to the
16741 practised swimmer as to ride in a spring-carriage ashore.  But the
16742 awful lonesomeness is intolerable.  The intense concentration of self
16743 in the middle of such a heartless immensity, my God! who can tell it?
16744 Mark, how when sailors in a dead calm bathe in the open sea--mark
16745 how closely they hug their ship and only coast along her sides.
16746 
16747 But had Stubb really abandoned the poor little negro to his fate?
16748 No; he did not mean to, at least.  Because there were two boats in
16749 his wake, and he supposed, no doubt, that they would of course come
16750 up to Pip very quickly, and pick him up; though, indeed, such
16751 considerations towards oarsmen jeopardized through their own
16752 timidity, is not always manifested by the hunters in all similar
16753 instances; and such instances not unfrequently occur; almost
16754 invariably in the fishery, a coward, so called, is marked with the
16755 same ruthless detestation peculiar to military navies and armies.
16756 
16757 But it so happened, that those boats, without seeing Pip, suddenly
16758 spying whales close to them on one side, turned, and gave chase; and
16759 Stubb's boat was now so far away, and he and all his crew so intent
16760 upon his fish, that Pip's ringed horizon began to expand around him
16761 miserably.  By the merest chance the ship itself at last rescued him;
16762 but from that hour the little negro went about the deck an idiot;
16763 such, at least, they said he was.  The sea had jeeringly kept his
16764 finite body up, but drowned the infinite of his soul.  Not drowned
16765 entirely, though.  Rather carried down alive to wondrous depths,
16766 where strange shapes of the unwarped primal world glided to and fro
16767 before his passive eyes; and the miser-merman, Wisdom, revealed his
16768 hoarded heaps; and among the joyous, heartless, ever-juvenile
16769 eternities, Pip saw the multitudinous, God-omnipresent, coral
16770 insects, that out of the firmament of waters heaved the colossal
16771 orbs.  He saw God's foot upon the treadle of the loom, and spoke it;
16772 and therefore his shipmates called him mad.  So man's insanity is
16773 heaven's sense; and wandering from all mortal reason, man comes at
16774 last to that celestial thought, which, to reason, is absurd and
16775 frantic; and weal or woe, feels then uncompromised, indifferent as
16776 his God.
16777 
16778 For the rest, blame not Stubb too hardly.  The thing is common in
16779 that fishery; and in the sequel of the narrative, it will then be
16780 seen what like abandonment befell myself.
