16975 
16976 The Try-Works.
16977 
16978 
16979 Besides her hoisted boats, an American whaler is outwardly
16980 distinguished by her try-works.  She presents the curious anomaly of
16981 the most solid masonry joining with oak and hemp in constituting the
16982 completed ship.  It is as if from the open field a brick-kiln were
16983 transported to her planks.
16984 
16985 The try-works are planted between the foremast and mainmast, the
16986 most roomy part of the deck.  The timbers beneath are of a peculiar
16987 strength, fitted to sustain the weight of an almost solid mass of
16988 brick and mortar, some ten feet by eight square, and five in height.
16989 The foundation does not penetrate the deck, but the masonry is firmly
16990 secured to the surface by ponderous knees of iron bracing it on all
16991 sides, and screwing it down to the timbers.  On the flanks it is
16992 cased with wood, and at top completely covered by a large, sloping,
16993 battened hatchway.  Removing this hatch we expose the great try-pots,
16994 two in number, and each of several barrels' capacity.  When not in
16995 use, they are kept remarkably clean.  Sometimes they are polished
16996 with soapstone and sand, till they shine within like silver
16997 punch-bowls.  During the night-watches some cynical old sailors will
16998 crawl into them and coil themselves away there for a nap.  While
16999 employed in polishing them--one man in each pot, side by side--many
17000 confidential communications are carried on, over the iron lips.  It
17001 is a place also for profound mathematical meditation.  It was in the
17002 left hand try-pot of the Pequod, with the soapstone diligently
17003 circling round me, that I was first indirectly struck by the
17004 remarkable fact, that in geometry all bodies gliding along the
17005 cycloid, my soapstone for example, will descend from any point in
17006 precisely the same time.
17007 
17008 Removing the fire-board from the front of the try-works, the bare
17009 masonry of that side is exposed, penetrated by the two iron mouths of
17010 the furnaces, directly underneath the pots.  These mouths are fitted
17011 with heavy doors of iron.  The intense heat of the fire is prevented
17012 from communicating itself to the deck, by means of a shallow
17013 reservoir extending under the entire inclosed surface of the works.
17014 By a tunnel inserted at the rear, this reservoir is kept replenished
17015 with water as fast as it evaporates.  There are no external chimneys;
17016 they open direct from the rear wall.  And here let us go back for a
17017 moment.
17018 
17019 It was about nine o'clock at night that the Pequod's try-works were
17020 first started on this present voyage.  It belonged to Stubb to
17021 oversee the business.
17022 
17023 "All ready there?  Off hatch, then, and start her.  You cook, fire
17024 the works."  This was an easy thing, for the carpenter had been
17025 thrusting his shavings into the furnace throughout the passage.  Here
17026 be it said that in a whaling voyage the first fire in the try-works has
17027 to be fed for a time with wood.  After that no wood is used, except
17028 as a means of quick ignition to the staple fuel.  In a word, after
17029 being tried out, the crisp, shrivelled blubber, now called scraps or
17030 fritters, still contains considerable of its unctuous properties.
17031 These fritters feed the flames.  Like a plethoric burning martyr, or
17032 a self-consuming misanthrope, once ignited, the whale supplies his
17033 own fuel and burns by his own body.  Would that he consumed his own
17034 smoke! for his smoke is horrible to inhale, and inhale it you must,
17035 and not only that, but you must live in it for the time.  It has an
17036 unspeakable, wild, Hindoo odor about it, such as may lurk in the
17037 vicinity of funereal pyres.  It smells like the left wing of the day
17038 of judgment; it is an argument for the pit.
17039 
17040 By midnight the works were in full operation.  We were clear from the
17041 carcase; sail had been made; the wind was freshening; the wild ocean
17042 darkness was intense.  But that darkness was licked up by the fierce
17043 flames, which at intervals forked forth from the sooty flues, and
17044 illuminated every lofty rope in the rigging, as with the famed Greek
17045 fire.  The burning ship drove on, as if remorselessly commissioned to
17046 some vengeful deed.  So the pitch and sulphur-freighted brigs of the
17047 bold Hydriote, Canaris, issuing from their midnight harbors, with
17048 broad sheets of flame for sails, bore down upon the Turkish frigates,
