17077 darkness, seemed the material counterpart of her monomaniac
17078 commander's soul.
17079 
17080 So seemed it to me, as I stood at her helm, and for long hours
17081 silently guided the way of this fire-ship on the sea.  Wrapped, for
17082 that interval, in darkness myself, I but the better saw the redness,
17083 the madness, the ghastliness of others.  The continual sight of the
17084 fiend shapes before me, capering half in smoke and half in fire,
17085 these at last begat kindred visions in my soul, so soon as I began to
17086 yield to that unaccountable drowsiness which ever would come over me
17087 at a midnight helm.
17088 
17089 But that night, in particular, a strange (and ever since
17090 inexplicable) thing occurred to me.  Starting from a brief standing
17091 sleep, I was horribly conscious of something fatally wrong.  The
17092 jaw-bone tiller smote my side, which leaned against it; in my ears
17093 was the low hum of sails, just beginning to shake in the wind; I
17094 thought my eyes were open; I was half conscious of putting my fingers
17095 to the lids and mechanically stretching them still further apart.
17096 But, spite of all this, I could see no compass before me to steer by;
17097 though it seemed but a minute since I had been watching the card, by
17098 the steady binnacle lamp illuminating it.  Nothing seemed before me
17099 but a jet gloom, now and then made ghastly by flashes of redness.
17100 Uppermost was the impression, that whatever swift, rushing thing I
17101 stood on was not so much bound to any haven ahead as rushing from all
17102 havens astern.  A stark, bewildered feeling, as of death, came over
17103 me.  Convulsively my hands grasped the tiller, but with the crazy
17104 conceit that the tiller was, somehow, in some enchanted way,
17105 inverted.  My God! what is the matter with me? thought I.  Lo! in my
17106 brief sleep I had turned myself about, and was fronting the ship's
17107 stern, with my back to her prow and the compass.  In an instant I
17108 faced back, just in time to prevent the vessel from flying up into
17109 the wind, and very probably capsizing her.  How glad and how grateful
17110 the relief from this unnatural hallucination of the night, and the
17111 fatal contingency of being brought by the lee!
17112 
17113 Look not too long in the face of the fire, O man!  Never dream with
17114 thy hand on the helm!  Turn not thy back to the compass; accept the
17115 first hint of the hitching tiller; believe not the artificial fire,
17116 when its redness makes all things look ghastly.  To-morrow, in the
17117 natural sun, the skies will be bright; those who glared like devils
17118 in the forking flames, the morn will show in far other, at least
17119 gentler, relief; the glorious, golden, glad sun, the only true
17120 lamp--all others but liars!
17121 
17122 Nevertheless the sun hides not Virginia's Dismal Swamp, nor Rome's
17123 accursed Campagna, nor wide Sahara, nor all the millions of miles of
17124 deserts and of griefs beneath the moon.  The sun hides not the ocean,
17125 which is the dark side of this earth, and which is two thirds of this
17126 earth.  So, therefore, that mortal man who hath more of joy than
17127 sorrow in him, that mortal man cannot be true--not true, or
17128 undeveloped.  With books the same.  The truest of all men was the Man
17129 of Sorrows, and the truest of all books is Solomon's, and
17130 Ecclesiastes is the fine hammered steel of woe.  "All is vanity."
17131 ALL.  This wilful world hath not got hold of unchristian Solomon's
17132 wisdom yet.  But he who dodges hospitals and jails, and walks fast
17133 crossing graveyards, and would rather talk of operas than hell;
17134 calls Cowper, Young, Pascal, Rousseau, poor devils all of sick men;
17135 and throughout a care-free lifetime swears by Rabelais as passing
17136 wise, and therefore jolly;--not that man is fitted to sit down on
17137 tomb-stones, and break the green damp mould with unfathomably
17138 wondrous Solomon.
17139 
17140 But even Solomon, he says, "the man that wandereth out of the way of
17141 understanding shall remain" (I.E., even while living) "in the
17142 congregation of the dead."  Give not thyself up, then, to fire, lest
17143 it invert thee, deaden thee; as for the time it did me.  There is a
17144 wisdom that is woe; but there is a woe that is madness.  And there is
17145 a Catskill eagle in some souls that can alike dive down into the
17146 blackest gorges, and soar out of them again and become invisible in
17147 the sunny spaces.  And even if he for ever flies within the gorge,
17148 that gorge is in the mountains; so that even in his lowest swoop the
17149 mountain eagle is still higher than other birds upon the plain, even
17150 though they soar.
