19094 
19095 Queequeg in His Coffin.
19096 
19097 
19098 Upon searching, it was found that the casks last struck into the hold
19099 were perfectly sound, and that the leak must be further off.  So, it
19100 being calm weather, they broke out deeper and deeper, disturbing the
19101 slumbers of the huge ground-tier butts; and from that black midnight
19102 sending those gigantic moles into the daylight above.  So deep did
19103 they go; and so ancient, and corroded, and weedy the aspect of the
19104 lowermost puncheons, that you almost looked next for some mouldy
19105 corner-stone cask containing coins of Captain Noah, with copies of
19106 the posted placards, vainly warning the infatuated old world from the
19107 flood.  Tierce after tierce, too, of water, and bread, and beef, and
19108 shooks of staves, and iron bundles of hoops, were hoisted out, till
19109 at last the piled decks were hard to get about; and the hollow hull
19110 echoed under foot, as if you were treading over empty catacombs, and
19111 reeled and rolled in the sea like an air-freighted demijohn.
19112 Top-heavy was the ship as a dinnerless student with all Aristotle in
19113 his head.  Well was it that the Typhoons did not visit them then.
19114 
19115 Now, at this time it was that my poor pagan companion, and fast
19116 bosom-friend, Queequeg, was seized with a fever, which brought him
19117 nigh to his endless end.
19118 
19119 Be it said, that in this vocation of whaling, sinecures are unknown;
19120 dignity and danger go hand in hand; till you get to be Captain, the
19121 higher you rise the harder you toil.  So with poor Queequeg, who, as
19122 harpooneer, must not only face all the rage of the living whale,
19123 but--as we have elsewhere seen--mount his dead back in a rolling sea;
19124 and finally descend into the gloom of the hold, and bitterly sweating
19125 all day in that subterraneous confinement, resolutely manhandle the
19126 clumsiest casks and see to their stowage.  To be short, among
19127 whalemen, the harpooneers are the holders, so called.
19128 
19129 Poor Queequeg! when the ship was about half disembowelled, you should
19130 have stooped over the hatchway, and peered down upon him there;
19131 where, stripped to his woollen drawers, the tattooed savage was
19132 crawling about amid that dampness and slime, like a green spotted
19133 lizard at the bottom of a well.  And a well, or an ice-house, it
19134 somehow proved to him, poor pagan; where, strange to say, for all the
19135 heat of his sweatings, he caught a terrible chill which lapsed into a
19136 fever; and at last, after some days' suffering, laid him in his
19137 hammock, close to the very sill of the door of death.  How he wasted
19138 and wasted away in those few long-lingering days, till there seemed
19139 but little left of him but his frame and tattooing.  But as all else
19140 in him thinned, and his cheek-bones grew sharper, his eyes,
19141 nevertheless, seemed growing fuller and fuller; they became of a
19142 strange softness of lustre; and mildly but deeply looked out at you
19143 there from his sickness, a wondrous testimony to that immortal health
19144 in him which could not die, or be weakened.  And like circles on the
19145 water, which, as they grow fainter, expand; so his eyes seemed
19146 rounding and rounding, like the rings of Eternity.  An awe that
19147 cannot be named would steal over you as you sat by the side of this
19148 waning savage, and saw as strange things in his face, as any beheld
19149 who were bystanders when Zoroaster died.  For whatever is truly
19150 wondrous and fearful in man, never yet was put into words or books.
19151 And the drawing near of Death, which alike levels all, alike
19152 impresses all with a last revelation, which only an author from the
19153 dead could adequately tell.  So that--let us say it again--no dying
19154 Chaldee or Greek had higher and holier thoughts than those, whose
19155 mysterious shades you saw creeping over the face of poor Queequeg, as
19156 he quietly lay in his swaying hammock, and the rolling sea seemed
19157 gently rocking him to his final rest, and the ocean's invisible
19158 flood-tide lifted him higher and higher towards his destined heaven.
19159 
19160 Not a man of the crew but gave him up; and, as for Queequeg himself,
19161 what he thought of his case was forcibly shown by a curious favour he
19162 asked.  He called one to him in the grey morning watch, when the day
19163 was just breaking, and taking his hand, said that while in Nantucket
19164 he had chanced to see certain little canoes of dark wood, like the
19165 rich war-wood of his native isle; and upon inquiry, he had learned
19166 that all whalemen who died in Nantucket, were laid in those same dark
19167 canoes, and that the fancy of being so laid had much pleased him; for
19168 it was not unlike the custom of his own race, who, after embalming a
19169 dead warrior, stretched him out in his canoe, and so left him to be
19170 floated away to the starry archipelagoes; for not only do they
19171 believe that the stars are isles, but that far beyond all visible
19172 horizons, their own mild, uncontinented seas, interflow with the blue
19173 heavens; and so form the white breakers of the milky way.  He added,
19174 that he shuddered at the thought of being buried in his hammock,
19175 according to the usual sea-custom, tossed like something vile to the
19176 death-devouring sharks.  No: he desired a canoe like those of
19177 Nantucket, all the more congenial to him, being a whaleman, that like
19178 a whale-boat these coffin-canoes were without a keel; though that
19179 involved but uncertain steering, and much lee-way adown the dim ages.
19180 
19181 Now, when this strange circumstance was made known aft, the carpenter
19182 was at once commanded to do Queequeg's bidding, whatever it might
19183 include.  There was some heathenish, coffin-coloured old lumber
19184 aboard, which, upon a long previous voyage, had been cut from the
