19272 moment, he had just recalled a little duty ashore, which he was
19273 leaving undone; and therefore had changed his mind about dying: he
19274 could not die yet, he averred.  They asked him, then, whether to live
19275 or die was a matter of his own sovereign will and pleasure.  He
19276 answered, certainly.  In a word, it was Queequeg's conceit, that if a
19277 man made up his mind to live, mere sickness could not kill him:
19278 nothing but a whale, or a gale, or some violent, ungovernable,
19279 unintelligent destroyer of that sort.
19280 
19281 Now, there is this noteworthy difference between savage and
19282 civilized; that while a sick, civilized man may be six months
19283 convalescing, generally speaking, a sick savage is almost half-well
