19312 
19313 The Pacific.
19314 
19315 
19316 When gliding by the Bashee isles we emerged at last upon the great
19317 South Sea; were it not for other things, I could have greeted my dear
19318 Pacific with uncounted thanks, for now the long supplication of my
19319 youth was answered; that serene ocean rolled eastwards from me a
19320 thousand leagues of blue.
19321 
19322 There is, one knows not what sweet mystery about this sea, whose
19323 gently awful stirrings seem to speak of some hidden soul beneath;
19324 like those fabled undulations of the Ephesian sod over the buried
19325 Evangelist St. John.  And meet it is, that over these sea-pastures,
19326 wide-rolling watery prairies and Potters' Fields of all four
19327 continents, the waves should rise and fall, and ebb and flow
19328 unceasingly; for here, millions of mixed shades and shadows, drowned
19329 dreams, somnambulisms, reveries; all that we call lives and souls,
19330 lie dreaming, dreaming, still; tossing like slumberers in their beds;
19331 the ever-rolling waves but made so by their restlessness.
19332 
19333 To any meditative Magian rover, this serene Pacific, once beheld,
19334 must ever after be the sea of his adoption.  It rolls the midmost
19335 waters of the world, the Indian ocean and Atlantic being but its
19336 arms.  The same waves wash the moles of the new-built Californian
19337 towns, but yesterday planted by the recentest race of men, and lave
19338 the faded but still gorgeous skirts of Asiatic lands, older than
19339 Abraham; while all between float milky-ways of coral isles, and
19340 low-lying, endless, unknown Archipelagoes, and impenetrable Japans.
19341 Thus this mysterious, divine Pacific zones the world's whole bulk
19342 about; makes all coasts one bay to it; seems the tide-beating heart
19343 of earth.  Lifted by those eternal swells, you needs must own the
19344 seductive god, bowing your head to Pan.
19345 
19346 But few thoughts of Pan stirred Ahab's brain, as standing like an
19347 iron statue at his accustomed place beside the mizen rigging, with
19348 one nostril he unthinkingly snuffed the sugary musk from the Bashee
19349 isles (in whose sweet woods mild lovers must be walking), and with
19350 the other consciously inhaled the salt breath of the new found sea;
19351 that sea in which the hated White Whale must even then be swimming.
19352 Launched at length upon these almost final waters, and gliding
19353 towards the Japanese cruising-ground, the old man's purpose
19354 intensified itself.  His firm lips met like the lips of a vice; the
19355 Delta of his forehead's veins swelled like overladen brooks; in his
19356 very sleep, his ringing cry ran through the vaulted hull, "Stern all!
19357 the White Whale spouts thick blood!"
