19361 CHAPTER 112
19362 
19363 The Blacksmith.
19364 
19365 
19366 Availing himself of the mild, summer-cool weather that now reigned
19367 in these latitudes, and in preparation for the peculiarly active
19368 pursuits shortly to be anticipated, Perth, the begrimed, blistered
19369 old blacksmith, had not removed his portable forge to the hold again,
19370 after concluding his contributory work for Ahab's leg, but still
19371 retained it on deck, fast lashed to ringbolts by the foremast; being
19372 now almost incessantly invoked by the headsmen, and harpooneers, and
19373 bowsmen to do some little job for them; altering, or repairing, or
19374 new shaping their various weapons and boat furniture.  Often he would
19375 be surrounded by an eager circle, all waiting to be served; holding
19376 boat-spades, pike-heads, harpoons, and lances, and jealously watching
19377 his every sooty movement, as he toiled.  Nevertheless, this old man's
19378 was a patient hammer wielded by a patient arm.  No murmur, no
19379 impatience, no petulance did come from him.  Silent, slow, and
19380 solemn; bowing over still further his chronically broken back, he
19381 toiled away, as if toil were life itself, and the heavy beating of
19382 his hammer the heavy beating of his heart.  And so it was.--Most
19383 miserable!
19384 
19385 A peculiar walk in this old man, a certain slight but painful
19386 appearing yawing in his gait, had at an early period of the voyage
19387 excited the curiosity of the mariners.  And to the importunity of
19388 their persisted questionings he had finally given in; and so it came
19389 to pass that every one now knew the shameful story of his wretched
19390 fate.
19391 
19392 Belated, and not innocently, one bitter winter's midnight, on the
19393 road running between two country towns, the blacksmith half-stupidly
19394 felt the deadly numbness stealing over him, and sought refuge in a
19395 leaning, dilapidated barn.  The issue was, the loss of the
19396 extremities of both feet.  Out of this revelation, part by part, at
19397 last came out the four acts of the gladness, and the one long, and as
19398 yet uncatastrophied fifth act of the grief of his life's drama.
19399 
19400 He was an old man, who, at the age of nearly sixty, had postponedly
19401 encountered that thing in sorrow's technicals called ruin.  He had
19402 been an artisan of famed excellence, and with plenty to do; owned a
19403 house and garden; embraced a youthful, daughter-like, loving wife,
19404 and three blithe, ruddy children; every Sunday went to a
19405 cheerful-looking church, planted in a grove.  But one night, under
19406 cover of darkness, and further concealed in a most cunning
19407 disguisement, a desperate burglar slid into his happy home, and
19408 robbed them all of everything.  And darker yet to tell, the
19409 blacksmith himself did ignorantly conduct this burglar into his
19410 family's heart.  It was the Bottle Conjuror!  Upon the opening of
19411 that fatal cork, forth flew the fiend, and shrivelled up his home.
19412 Now, for prudent, most wise, and economic reasons, the blacksmith's
19413 shop was in the basement of his dwelling, but with a separate
19414 entrance to it; so that always had the young and loving healthy wife
19415 listened with no unhappy nervousness, but with vigorous pleasure, to
19416 the stout ringing of her young-armed old husband's hammer; whose
19417 reverberations, muffled by passing through the floors and walls, came
19418 up to her, not unsweetly, in her nursery; and so, to stout Labor's
19419 iron lullaby, the blacksmith's infants were rocked to slumber.
19420 
19421 Oh, woe on woe!  Oh, Death, why canst thou not sometimes be timely?
19422 Hadst thou taken this old blacksmith to thyself ere his full ruin
19423 came upon him, then had the young widow had a delicious grief, and
19424 her orphans a truly venerable, legendary sire to dream of in their
19425 after years; and all of them a care-killing competency.  But Death
19426 plucked down some virtuous elder brother, on whose whistling daily
19427 toil solely hung the responsibilities of some other family, and left
19428 the worse than useless old man standing, till the hideous rot of life
19429 should make him easier to harvest.
19430 
19431 Why tell the whole?  The blows of the basement hammer every day grew
19432 more and more between; and each blow every day grew fainter than the
19433 last; the wife sat frozen at the window, with tearless eyes,
19434 glitteringly gazing into the weeping faces of her children; the
19435 bellows fell; the forge choked up with cinders; the house was sold;
19436 the mother dived down into the long church-yard grass; her children
19437 twice followed her thither; and the houseless, familyless old man
19438 staggered off a vagabond in crape; his every woe unreverenced; his
19439 grey head a scorn to flaxen curls!
19440 
19441 Death seems the only desirable sequel for a career like this; but
19442 Death is only a launching into the region of the strange Untried; it
19443 is but the first salutation to the possibilities of the immense
19444 Remote, the Wild, the Watery, the Unshored; therefore, to the
19445 death-longing eyes of such men, who still have left in them some
19446 interior compunctions against suicide, does the all-contributed and
19447 all-receptive ocean alluringly spread forth his whole plain of
19448 unimaginable, taking terrors, and wonderful, new-life adventures; and
19449 from the hearts of infinite Pacifics, the thousand mermaids sing to
19450 them--"Come hither, broken-hearted; here is another life without the
19451 guilt of intermediate death; here are wonders supernatural, without
19452 dying for them.  Come hither! bury thyself in a life which, to your
19453 now equally abhorred and abhorring, landed world, is more oblivious
19454 than death.  Come hither! put up THY gravestone, too, within the
19455 churchyard, and come hither, till we marry thee!"
19456 
19457 Hearkening to these voices, East and West, by early sunrise, and by
19458 fall of eve, the blacksmith's soul responded, Aye, I come!  And so
19459 Perth went a-whaling.
