22084 Here be it said, that this pertinacious pursuit of one particular
22085 whale, continued through day into night, and through night into day,
22086 is a thing by no means unprecedented in the South sea fishery.  For
22087 such is the wonderful skill, prescience of experience, and invincible
22088 confidence acquired by some great natural geniuses among the
22089 Nantucket commanders; that from the simple observation of a whale
22090 when last descried, they will, under certain given circumstances,
22091 pretty accurately foretell both the direction in which he will
22092 continue to swim for a time, while out of sight, as well as his
22093 probable rate of progression during that period.  And, in these
22094 cases, somewhat as a pilot, when about losing sight of a coast, whose
22095 general trending he well knows, and which he desires shortly to
22096 return to again, but at some further point; like as this pilot stands
22097 by his compass, and takes the precise bearing of the cape at present
22098 visible, in order the more certainly to hit aright the remote, unseen
22099 headland, eventually to be visited: so does the fisherman, at his
22100 compass, with the whale; for after being chased, and diligently
22101 marked, through several hours of daylight, then, when night obscures
22102 the fish, the creature's future wake through the darkness is almost
22103 as established to the sagacious mind of the hunter, as the pilot's
22104 coast is to him.  So that to this hunter's wondrous skill, the
22105 proverbial evanescence of a thing writ in water, a wake, is to all
22106 desired purposes well nigh as reliable as the steadfast land.  And as
22107 the mighty iron Leviathan of the modern railway is so familiarly
22108 known in its every pace, that, with watches in their hands, men time
22109 his rate as doctors that of a baby's pulse; and lightly say of it,
22110 the up train or the down train will reach such or such a spot, at
22111 such or such an hour; even so, almost, there are occasions when these
22112 Nantucketers time that other Leviathan of the deep, according to the
22113 observed humor of his speed; and say to themselves, so many hours
22114 hence this whale will have gone two hundred miles, will have about
22115 reached this or that degree of latitude or longitude.  But to render
22116 this acuteness at all successful in the end, the wind and the sea
22117 must be the whaleman's allies; for of what present avail to the
22118 becalmed or windbound mariner is the skill that assures him he is
22119 exactly ninety-three leagues and a quarter from his port?  Inferable
22120 from these statements, are many collateral subtile matters touching
22121 the chase of whales.
